owns\" [Radio Edit] / \"The Perception Of Johnny Punter\" [US Radio Edit]\n* 1999: \"Incomplete\" (feat. [[Elisabeth Troy|Elisabeth Antwi]]) / \"Wake Up Call\" [Acoustic Version] / \"Incomplete\" [Demo Version Recorded At The Castle Marouatte France]\n* 2008: \"Arc Of The Curve\" [Single Edit] / \"Arc of the Curve\"\n* 2008: \"Zoe 25\" [Radio Edit] / \"Dark Star\" [Live In Amsterdam 2008] / \"13th Star\" [Live In Amsterdam 2008]\n* 2014: \"[[Blind to the Beautiful]]\"\n\n===EPs===\n* 2018: \"A Parley with Angels\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Fish (singer)}}\n*Official website (as of 2017) \u2013 {{Site|http://fishmusic.scot}}\n*Official website (old) \u2013 {{Site|http://www.fish-thecompany.com/}}\n*Official website (old) \u2013 {{Site|http://www.fishheads.club/}}\n*{{IMDb name|name=Fish|id=0279258}} provides information on Fish and his acting career.\n\n{{Fish (singer)}}\n{{Marillion}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fish}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish male actors]]\n[[Category:Art rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Marillion members]]\n[[Category:People associated with Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dalkeith High School]]\n[[Category:People from Dalkeith]]\n[[Category:People from Midlothian]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Scottish male film actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish male singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish male television actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish socialists]]\n[[Category:Scottish songwriters]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSolo career:Punctuation and capitalisation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fish_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "Adrian Bailey", "text_new": "{{about||the geographer|Adrian Bailey n (academic)|the similarly named MP|Adrian Baillie}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Adrian Bailey\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Official portrait of Mr Adrian Bailey crop 2.jpg\n| office = Chairman of the [[Business, Innovation and Skills Committee|Business, Innovation and Skills Select Committee]]\n| term_start = 10 June 2010\n| term_end = 30 March 2015\n| leader =\n| predecessor = [[Peter Luff]]\n| successor = [[Iain Wright]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[West Bromwich West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Bromwich West]]\n| majority2 = \n| predecessor2 = [[Betty Boothroyd]]\n| successor2 = [[Shaun Bailey (West Bromwich MP)|Shaun Bailey]]\n| term_start2 = 23 November 2000\n| term_end2 = 6 November 2019\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1945|12|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Salisbury]], Wiltshire, England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Jill Bailey\n| party = [[Labour and Co-operative|Labour Co-op]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Exeter]], [[Loughborough University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = [https://www.adrianbaileymp.com/ https://www.adrianbaileymp.com/] [http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/mr-adrian-bailey/320 parliament..adrian-bailey]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Adrian Edward Bailey''' (born 11 December 1945) is a retired British [[Labour Co-operative]] politician. He was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[West Bromwich West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Bromwich West]] from 2000, when he won the seat at a [[2000 West Bromwich West by-election|by-election in November 2000]] until he stood down at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election in 2019]]. He was the Chairman of the [[Business, Innovation and Skills Committee]] 2010\u20132015.\n\n==Early life==\n\nBorn in [[Salisbury]], Bailey was educated at [[Cheltenham Grammar School]] before going on to university at the [[University of Exeter]], graduating in 1967 with an Honours Degree in Economic History.<ref name=\"politics\">{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Adrian|title=Biography|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/adrian-edward-bailey|website=Politics.co.uk|accessdate=17 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922145223/http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/adrian-edward-bailey|archive-date=22 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently, he trained at the [[Loughborough]] College of Librarianship and graduated in 1971 with a postgraduate diploma in Librarianship. From 1971\u20131982 he was employed as a professional librarian by Cheshire County Council and from 1973 to 1982 he also worked as a librarian and teacher of [[study skills]] in a Cheshire Comprehensive school.<ref name=\"politics\" />\n\n==Political career==\n\nBailey contested the seat of [[South Worcestershire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Worcestershire]] at the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]], where he was easily defeated by [[Gerald Nabarro]]. At both the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]] and [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general election]] he unsuccessfully contested the Cheshire seat of [[Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Nantwich]], where he was defeated by [[John Cockroft (politician)|John Cockcroft]].\n\nIn 1976, the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[Selwyn Lloyd]] decided to stand down from [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|the Commons]], and Bailey contested the [[1976 Wirral by-election|resulting by-election]]. However, he was again easily defeated, this time by [[David Hunt, Baron Hunt of Wirral|David Hunt]], who was later to enter the Cabinet of [[John Major]]. Bailey was not to fight a Parliamentary election again for 24 years, but contested and lost the [[Cheshire West (European Parliament constituency)|Cheshire West]] European seat in [[1979 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1979]].\n\nIn 1982, Bailey moved to the West Midlands to become a full-time political organiser for the [[Co-operative Party]] covering the Midlands and South Yorkshire region. He held this post until his election to Parliament in 2000.<ref name=\"politics\" />\n\nHe was elected as a councillor for [[Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council|Sandwell Borough Council]] in 1991 and was its Deputy Leader from 1997 to 2000. At the time of the resignation of Commons Speaker, [[Betty Boothroyd, Baroness Boothroyd of Sandwell|Betty Boothroyd]] in 2000, Bailey was the Secretary of the constituency Labour Party and Deputy Leader of the local council and seemed the obvious choice to fight what was then a safe Labour seat in the impending [[2000 West Bromwich West by-election|by-election]]. He was chosen to fight the seat and won fairly comfortably on 23 November 2000, entering the Commons 30 years after his first attempt. He is unusual in that he has contested two Parliamentary by-elections caused by the resignation of two different Speakers of the House of Commons.\n\nFollowing its establishment in 2002, Bailey took the position of Secretary of The All Party Parliamentary Group for Steel which acts as a group to promote the interests of the steel manufacturing industry and the communities that work in that industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030822020645/http://www.uksteel.org.uk/appg/index.htm|title=All Party Parliamentary Group on Steel|date=22 August 2003|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Bailey became a [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]] and served successive Secretaries of State, [[David Blunkett]] and [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]]. He also served as the Parliamentary Private Secretary to [[Bob Ainsworth]], the [[Minister of State]] at the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]].\n\nHe supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=2016-07-21|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715214543/https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe announced that he will not be standing as an MP in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AdrianBaileyMP/status/1189577564605550592|title=Adrian Bailey MP on Twitter|date=2019-10-30|website=Twitter|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030164213/https://twitter.com/AdrianBaileyMP/status/1189577564605550592|archive-date=30 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn 1989 Bailey married Jill, a schoolteacher,<ref name=\"politics\" /> and has a stepson named Daniel. He is a keen fan of [[cricket]] and [[association football|football]] supporting [[Cheltenham Town F.C.]] and is an enthusiastic swimmer.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = mr-adrian-bailey/320 | hansard = mr-adrian-bailey | guardian = 185/adrian-bailey | publicwhip = Adrian_Bailey | theywork = adrian_bailey/west_bromwich_west | record = Adrian-Bailey/West-Bromwich-West/21 | bbc = 25800.stm | journalisted = }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110716063120/http://yourdemocracy.newstatesman.com/profile/adrian-bailey Adrian Bailey Profile] at ''[[New Statesman]]'' Your democracy\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Betty Boothroyd]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament for [[West Bromwich West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Bromwich West]]|years=[[2000 West Bromwich West by-election|2000]]\u2013[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Shaun Bailey (West Bromwich MP)|Shaun Bailey]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, Adrian}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Co-operative MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Loughborough University]]\n[[Category:People educated at Pate's Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the West Midlands (county)]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the geographer|Adrian Bailey (academic)|the similarly named MP|Adrian Baillie}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Adrian Bailey\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Official portrait of Mr Adrian Bailey crop 2.jpg\n| office = Chairman of the [[Business, Innovation and Skills Committee|Business, Innovation and Skills Select Committee]]\n| term_start = 10 June 2010\n| term_end = 30 March 2015\n| leader =\n| predecessor = [[Peter Luff]]\n| successor = [[Iain Wright]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[West Bromwich West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Bromwich West]]\n| majority2 = \n| predecessor2 = [[Betty Boothroyd]]\n| successor2 = [[Shaun Bailey (West Bromwich MP)|Shaun Bailey]]\n| term_start2 = 23 November 2000\n| term_end2 = 6 November 2019\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1945|12|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Salisbury]], Wiltshire, England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Jill Bailey\n| party = [[Labour and Co-operative|Labour Co-op]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Exeter]], [[Loughborough University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = [https://www.adrianbaileymp.com/ https://www.adrianbaileymp.com/] [http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/mr-adrian-bailey/320 parliament..adrian-bailey]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Adrian Edward Bailey''' (born 11 December 1945) is a retired British [[Labour Co-operative]] politician. He was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[West Bromwich West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Bromwich West]] from 2000, when he won the seat at a [[2000 West Bromwich West by-election|by-election in November 2000]] until he stood down at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election in 2019]]. He was the Chairman of the [[Business, Innovation and Skills Committee]] 2010\u20132015.\n\n==Early life==\n\nBorn in [[Salisbury]], Bailey was educated at [[Cheltenham Grammar School]] before going on to university at the [[University of Exeter]], graduating in 1967 with an Honours Degree in Economic History.<ref name=\"politics\">{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Adrian|title=Biography|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/adrian-edward-bailey|website=Politics.co.uk|accessdate=17 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922145223/http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/adrian-edward-bailey|archive-date=22 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently, he trained at the [[Loughborough]] College of Librarianship and graduated in 1971 with a postgraduate diploma in Librarianship. From 1971\u20131982 he was employed as a professional librarian by Cheshire County Council and from 1973 to 1982 he also worked as a librarian and teacher of [[study skills]] in a Cheshire Comprehensive school.<ref name=\"politics\" />\n\n==Political career==\n\nBailey contested the seat of [[South Worcestershire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Worcestershire]] at the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]], where he was easily defeated by [[Gerald Nabarro]]. At both the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]] and [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general election]] he unsuccessfully contested the Cheshire seat of [[Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Nantwich]], where he was defeated by [[John Cockroft (politician)|John Cockcroft]].\n\nIn 1976, the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[Selwyn Lloyd]] decided to stand down from [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|the Commons]], and Bailey contested the [[1976 Wirral by-election|resulting by-election]]. However, he was again easily defeated, this time by [[David Hunt, Baron Hunt of Wirral|David Hunt]], who was later to enter the Cabinet of [[John Major]]. Bailey was not to fight a Parliamentary election again for 24 years, but contested and lost the [[Cheshire West (European Parliament constituency)|Cheshire West]] European seat in [[1979 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1979]].\n\nIn 1982, Bailey moved to the West Midlands to become a full-time political organiser for the [[Co-operative Party]] covering the Midlands and South Yorkshire region. He held this post until his election to Parliament in 2000.<ref name=\"politics\" />\n\nHe was elected as a councillor for [[Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council|Sandwell Borough Council]] in 1991 and was its Deputy Leader from 1997 to 2000. At the time of the resignation of Commons Speaker, [[Betty Boothroyd, Baroness Boothroyd of Sandwell|Betty Boothroyd]] in 2000, Bailey was the Secretary of the constituency Labour Party and Deputy Leader of the local council and seemed the obvious choice to fight what was then a safe Labour seat in the impending [[2000 West Bromwich West by-election|by-election]]. He was chosen to fight the seat and won fairly comfortably on 23 November 2000, entering the Commons 30 years after his first attempt. He is unusual in that he has contested two Parliamentary by-elections caused by the resignation of two different Speakers of the House of Commons.\n\nFollowing its establishment in 2002, Bailey took the position of Secretary of The All Party Parliamentary Group for Steel which acts as a group to promote the interests of the steel manufacturing industry and the communities that work in that industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030822020645/http://www.uksteel.org.uk/appg/index.htm|title=All Party Parliamentary Group on Steel|date=22 August 2003|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Bailey became a [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]] and served successive Secretaries of State, [[David Blunkett]] and [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]]. He also served as the Parliamentary Private Secretary to [[Bob Ainsworth]], the [[Minister of State]] at the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]].\n\nHe supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=2016-07-21|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715214543/https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe announced that he will not be standing as an MP in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AdrianBaileyMP/status/1189577564605550592|title=Adrian Bailey MP on Twitter|date=2019-10-30|website=Twitter|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030164213/https://twitter.com/AdrianBaileyMP/status/1189577564605550592|archive-date=30 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn 1989 Bailey married Jill, a schoolteacher,<ref name=\"politics\" /> and has a stepson named Daniel. He is a keen fan of [[cricket]] and [[association football|football]] supporting [[Cheltenham Town F.C.]] and is an enthusiastic swimmer.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = mr-adrian-bailey/320 | hansard = mr-adrian-bailey | guardian = 185/adrian-bailey | publicwhip = Adrian_Bailey | theywork = adrian_bailey/west_bromwich_west | record = Adrian-Bailey/West-Bromwich-West/21 | bbc = 25800.stm | journalisted = }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110716063120/http://yourdemocracy.newstatesman.com/profile/adrian-bailey Adrian Bailey Profile] at ''[[New Statesman]]'' Your democracy\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Betty Boothroyd]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament for [[West Bromwich West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Bromwich West]]|years=[[2000 West Bromwich West by-election|2000]]\u2013[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Shaun Bailey (West Bromwich MP)|Shaun Bailey]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, Adrian}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Co-operative MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Loughborough University]]\n[[Category:People educated at Pate's Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the West Midlands (county)]]\n", "name_user": "24.78.56.73", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrian_Bailey"}
{"title_page": "Daily fantasy sports", "text_new": "{{About|daily fantasy sports|fantasy sports in general|Fantasy sport}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n'''Daily fantasy sports''' ('''DFS''') are a subset of [[fantasy sport]] games. As with traditional fantasy sports games, players compete against others by building a team of [[professional athlete]]s from a particular [[sports league|league]] or competition while remaining under a [[salary cap]], and earn points based on the actual statistical performance of the players in real-world competitions. Daily fantasy sports are an accelerated variant of traditional fantasy sports that are conducted over short-term periods, such as a week or single day of competition, as opposed to those that are played across an entire season. Daily fantasy sports are typically structured in the form of paid competitions typically referred to as a \"contest\"; winners receive a share of a pre-determined pot funded by their entry fees. A portion of entry fee payments go to the provider as [[Rake (poker)|rake]] revenue.<ref name=sg-dk500k>{{cite web|title=$500,000 DraftKings 1-Day Fantasy Baseball Contest Could Make You Rich Overnight|url=http://www.sportsgrid.com/uncategorized/500000-draftkings-1-day-fantasy-baseball-contest-could-make-you-rich-overnight/|website=[[SportsGrid]]|publisher=Anthem Media Group|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=washington1>{{cite web|last1=Kilgore|first1=Adam|title=Daily fantasy sports Web sites find riches in Internet gaming law loophole|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/daily-fantasy-sports-web-sites-find-riches-in-internet-gaming-law-loophole/2015/03/27/92988444-d172-11e4-a62f-ee745911a4ff_story.html|work=The Washington Post|date=March 27, 2015|accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[United States]], the daily fantasy sports industry is dominated by two competing services: the [[New York City|New York]]-based [[FanDuel]], and the [[Boston]]-based [[DraftKings]]. Both companies were established as [[venture capital]]-backed [[startup company|startup companies]], received funding from investment firms, sports broadcasters, leagues, and team owners, and became known for the aggressive marketing of their services. As of September 2015, both companies have an estimated value of at least $1 billion, and control 95% of the  U.S. DFS market.<ref name=adage-dkspending/><ref name=wsj-realitycheck>{{cite web|title=Daily Fantasy-Sports Operators Await Reality Check|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/daily-fantasy-sports-operators-await-reality-check-1441835630|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=September 9, 2015}}{{subscription required}}</ref> The two primarily compete against smaller DFS services, such as DRAFT, Fantasy Aces, and [[Yahoo! Sports]].<ref name=\"scn-fantasyaces\">{{cite web|url=https://sportsplatform.in/fantasy-aces-could-be-the-pick-of-the-fantasy-sports-space/2284/|title=Fantasy Aces Could Be the \u2018Pick\u2019 of the Fantasy Sports Space|last=|first=|date=|work=Sports Platform|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref name=nyt-yahoodailyfantasy/> The popularity of the daily fantasy format has been credited to its convenience in comparison to season-length games, as well as the focus on major cash prizes in the promotion of these services. Daily fantasy has also been credited with helping to improve television viewership and engagement with sports.\n\nDaily fantasy sports have faced notable legal challenges, including disputes over whether DFS constitutes [[gambling]]. Politicians and other critics have argued that due to their format, players are essentially making [[proposition bet|proposition wagers]] on the varying performance of individual athletes in specific games, and not managing the performance of their selections on a week-to-week basis. Proponents have defended DFS as being a [[game of skill]], as the required familiarity with the players and teams, as well as salary cap management, rewards skilled players. Local laws have varying definitions of gambling games, such as whether a game's elements of chance are predominant over those or skill, or how much control the player has over the outcome of the game.\n\nIn the United States, the legality of DFS has been determined on a state-by-state basis based on local gambling laws and other rulings. The federal [[Unlawful Internet Gambling Enforcement Act]] (UIEGA) contains language dictating that fantasy sports are not considered an unlawful wager under the act; however, the act only prohibits the electronic transfer of funds from unlawful gambling as defined under state laws. A number of [[state attorneys general]] issued opinions concluding that DFS is a form of gambling, while the state of [[Nevada]] declared that DFS games must be licensed as a [[sports pool]]. The [[New York State]] lawsuit, which resulted from an investigation of DFS services after it was alleged that employees working for DraftKings and FanDuel had used [[inside information]] to win cash prizes from each other, spawned retaliatory lawsuits from the companies which alleged that the rulings were the result of a misinterpretation of the nature of their services. By December 2017, 18 states, including [[Massachusetts]] and [[Virginia]], had ruled that DFS was a legal game of skill.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gouker |first=Dustin |url=https://www.legalsportsreport.com/16802/ohio-sends-fantasy-sports-bill-governor/ |title=Ohio Sends Fantasy Sports Bill To Governor; Would Be 18th State With Law |work=Legal Sports Report |date=2017-12-05 |accessdate=2017-12-09 }}</ref> \n\n== Gameplay ==\nThere are several main disciplines of daily fantasy sports competitions, divided into two categories: cash games, and guaranteed prize pool (GPP).<ref name=washington1 /><ref name=\"rotoworld-cashvsgpp\"/><ref name=sbj-pushes>{{cite web|title=Daily fantasy pushes to continue growth streak|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2015/03/16/Marketing-and-Sponsorship/Daily-fantasy.aspx|accessdate=October 8, 2015|work=Sports Business Journal}}</ref> DFS contests typically utilize a [[salary cap]] format, in which players are allotted a maximum budget to spend on athletes for their team, represented as either [[play money]] or points. Each athlete has their own cost, with elite athletes having the highest costs.<ref name=vb-howto>{{cite web|title=How to make a killer daily fantasy sports football roster on DraftKings and FanDuel|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/09/10/how-to-make-a-killer-daily-fantasy-sports-football-roster-on-draftkings-and-fanduel/|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn \"Double-up\" or \"50/50\" cash game competitions, players win a prize equal to double their entry fee if they finish with a score within the top 50% of all participants. Head-to-head competitions are similar, except that the player must win against another user of their choice.<ref name=\"rotoworld-cashvsgpp\">{{cite web|title=Cash Games vs. Tournaments|url=http://www.rotoworld.com/articles/nba/48892/425/cash-games-vs-tournaments|website=RotoWorld|publisher=NBC Sports Group|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref> Guaranteed prize pool contests have higher stakes, using tiered payouts based on finishing in different [[percentile]]s or positions of the field of contestants.<ref name=sportingnews-dfs>{{cite web|title=Daily Fantasy Strategy: How to play 50/50, H2H, GPP contests|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/fantasy/nba/story/2015-02-12/daily-fantasy-sports-dfs-strategy-how-to-play-5050-h2h-gpp-win-cash-prizes-one-day-draft-kings-tips|website=The Sporting News|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref> Further variations of double-up games, including Triple-up, Quadruple-up, and Quintuple-up, may also be offered.<ref name=nv-memo />  Leagues are smaller versions of GPP contests, with tiered payouts and a smaller number of contestants.\n\nDaily fantasy games exist in a variety of major and minor sports, depending on service, including but not limited to [[American football]] ([[college football|college]] and the [[NFL]]), [[association football|association football (soccer)]], [[auto racing]], [[baseball]], [[basketball]], [[cricket]], [[golf]], [[ice hockey]], [[rugby football|rugby]], [[horse racing]] and [[sumo wrestling]].<ref name=sbj-pushes /><ref name=bostoncom-centerofdfs>{{cite web|title=Companies at center of fantasy sports turmoil have big ambitions|url=https://www.boston.com/business/news/2015/10/11/companies-center-fantasy-sports-turmoil-have-big-ambitions/ZoHTg8sbEFXBqGieNXMbfK/story.html|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=Boston.com|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The DFS Revolution Cannot Be Stopped: Here Comes Fantasy Sumo Wrestling|url=http://www.sportsgrid.com/fantasy/daily-fantasy-sports/the-dfs-revolution-cannot-be-stopped-here-comes-fantasy-sumo-wrestling/|website=[[SportsGrid]]|accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sports Perfecta Launches Daily Fantasy Jockey for Horse Racing Enthusiasts in the United States|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/sports-perfecta-launches-daily-fantasy-154501962.html|website=Yahoo|accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref> Daily fantasy contests have also been held in professional-level [[e-sports]] events.<ref name=recode-esportsdfs>{{cite web|title=FanDuel Acquires eSports Company AlphaDraft, Also Jumps Into Competitive Video Gaming|url=http://recode.net/2015/09/24/fanduel-acquires-esports-company-alphadraft-also-jumps-into-competitive-video-gaming/|website=Re/code|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Fantasy sport#History}}\n\n=== Early examples ===\nThe earliest records of daily fantasy trace back to 1990. The first national fantasy baseball and football competitions, Dugout Derby and Pigskin Playoff, developed by Lee Marc, Robert Barbiere and Brad Wendkos of Phoneworks who teamed with West Coast Ad Agency (Wakeman & deForest). The daily fantasy games were launched in 1990 in a number of newspapers throughout the country including the Detroit Free Press, Los Angeles Times, Arizona Republic, Press Democrat, Hartford Courant, Tampa Bay Times, Morning Call, Philadelphia Inquirer, Chicago Sun Times. Hundreds of thousands of readers played in the daily fantasy games. Archives of Dugout Derby and Pigskin Playoff are available online and in most public libraries.<ref>\"Pigskin Playoff\", Detroit Free Press, 9/4/1990 - Page 24; Los Angeles Times, 9/9/1990 - Page 118, \"Dugout Derby\", Hartford Courant 4/29/1990 - Page 200; Lost Angeles Times, 4/23/1990 - Page 51; and others as displayed in archives of www.newspapers.com</ref> These games were the first to allow significantly large numbers of participants to compete against one another for prizes. They were the first to convert baseball and football statistics into a simple scoring system and were awarded US Patents 5,018,736A and 5,263,723A, for Interactive Game System and Method; Interactive Contest System.<ref>United States Patent Office (USPTO) www.uspto.gov</ref>\n\nAmong the first sites to specialize in the format of daily fantasy was Instant Fantasy Sports, established in 2007; the service's co-founder Chris Fargis explained that the service was inspired by the format of [[online poker]], and that his goal was to \"take the time frame of season-long fantasy sports leagues and shrink it\".<ref name=nytmag-sucker>{{cite web|title=How the Daily Fantasy Sports Industry Turns Fans Into Suckers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/06/magazine/how-the-daily-fantasy-sports-industry-turns-fans-into-suckers.html?_r=0|accessdate=January 6, 2016|work=New York Times Magazine}}</ref> The site was later acquired by [[NBC Universal]] and re-branded as SnapDraft; NBC had also acquired the fantasy sports-focused website [[Rotoworld]] in 2006. SnapDraft was later shut down.<ref name=usatoday-nflon>{{cite web|title=With NFL on, NBC Sports redoes Web look|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/webguide/internetlife/2006-09-05-nbcsports-website_x.htm|accessdate=October 8, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]}}</ref><ref name=breakingvc-gameover>{{cite web|title=Game Over: Why Daily Fantasy Has Already Been Won|url=http://www.breakingvc.com/2015/07/15/game-over-why-daily-fantasy-has-already-been-won/|website=BreakingVC|accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Growth ===\nOn July 21, 2009, the Edinburgh, Scotland-based [[prediction market]] game [[Hubdub]] launched a spin-off known as [[FanDuel]]; the service attempted to market itself as a modern alternative to the fantasy sports services provided by other media properties, such as [[Yahoo! Sports]] and [[CBSSports.com]], with the daily fantasy format and integration with popular social networks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Butcher|first=Mike|title=FanDuel turns fantasy sports betting into a social game|url=https://techcrunch.com/2009/07/21/fanduel-turns-fantasy-sports-betting-into-a-social-game/|work=TechCrunch|publisher=[[AOL, Inc.]]|accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> Its founder, Nigel Eccles, was inspired to create the site when he realized that the carve-out for fantasy sports in the U.S. [[Unlawful Internet Gambling Enforcement Act of 2006]] did not state that a legal, paid fantasy sports competition had to last for an entire season.<ref name=\"washington1\"/> In February 2012, the [[Boston]]-based DraftKings was established by former [[VistaPrint]] executives Jason Robins, Matthew Kalish, and Paul Liberman. DraftKings gained a local, [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]]-based competitor in StarStreet, when it introduced a daily fantasy game of its own.<ref name=boston1>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/business/technology/innoeco/2012/02/two_local_companies_starstreet.html |title=Two local companies, StarStreet and DraftKings, prepare to launch new fantasy sports sites |work=Boston.com |publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC |date=February 27, 2012|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDraftKings and FanDuel in particular became the subjects of [[venture capital]] investments by various parties; in April 2013, [[Major League Baseball]] invested an undisclosed amount in DraftKings, becoming the first U.S. professional sports organization to invest in daily fantasy sports.<ref name=\"washington1\"/><ref name=\"sbj-pushes\"/> In 2014, DraftKings acquired DraftStreet, as well as StarStreet, and raised another $41 million in investment led by the Raine Group, bringing the company to a total of $75 million in outside funding.<ref name=techcrunch1>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/08/25/draftkings-41m-starstreet/ |title=DraftKings Raises Another $41M And Acquires Daily Fantasy Sports Competitor StarStreet|work=TechCrunch|publisher=AOL, Inc. |date=August 25, 2014|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> FanDuel pursued investments as well, with an $11 million Series C funding round that included [[Comcast Ventures]], a $70 million Series D round in September 2014 led by Shamrock Capital Advisors with participation from [[NBC Sports]] Ventures and KKR among others, and a Series E funding round of $275 million in July 2015, valuing the company at over $1 billion.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\">{{cite web|last1=Chernova|first1=Yuliya|title=FanDuel Raises $70 Million as Daily Fantasy Sports Battle Heats Up\n|date=September 2, 2014|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2014/09/02/fanduel-raises-70-million-as-daily-fantasy-sports-battle-heats-up/|accessdate=October 15, 2014|work=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/fantasy-sports-create-billion-dollar-startups-1436846402|title=Fantasy Sports Create Billion-Dollar Startups|author=Lora Kolodny|date=July 14, 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]}}{{subscription required}}</ref> In October 2014, NBC Sports entered into a content sharing partnership with the DFS information website [[Rotogrinders]], in which it would provide daily fantasy-oriented content for Rotoworld.<ref name=svg-rotoworldpartnership>{{cite web|title=NBC\u2019s RotoWorld, RotoGrinders Ink Fantasy Sports Partnership|url=http://sportsvideo.org/main/blog/2014/10/14/nbcs-rotoworld-rotogrinders-ink-fantasy-sports-partnership/|website=Sports Video Group|accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDraftKings and FanDuel began to pursue advertising and endorsement deals with sports franchises and leagues; in November 2014, DraftKings entered into a multi-year sponsorship deal with the [[National Hockey League]], complementing team-level sponsorship deals it had reached with seven NHL franchises. Also in November, the [[National Basketball Association]] acquired an equity stake in FanDuel and entered into a four-year sponsorship deal with the company.<ref name=espn-fdnba>{{cite web|title=NBA partners with FanDuel|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/11864920/nba-fanduel-reach-4-year-exclusive-daily-fantasy-deal|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"usatoday-fanduelsigns\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2015/04/21/daily-fantasy-sports-fanduel-draftkings-nfl-mlb-nhl-nba/26149961/|title=FanDuel signs deals with 15 NFL teams, escalating daily fantasy integration|author=Schrotenboer, Brent |date=April 21, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]}}</ref><ref name=NHL1>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2014/11/10/Marketing-and-Sponsorship/DraftKings.aspx|title=NHL Signs Two-Year Deal With DraftKings As Rise Of Daily Fantasy Games Continues|work=Sports Business Journal|date=November 10, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, after the [[National Football League]] began to allow daily fantasy providers to sign multi-year team sponsorship deals, with caveats, FanDuel reached deals with sixteen NFL teams for placements on team-oriented digital properties, radio, and in-stadium.<ref name=\"usatoday-fanduelsigns\"/> DraftKings had also received an investment by [[Robert Kraft]]\u2014a local businessman whose holdings include the [[New England Patriots]].<ref name=nyt-dfsnevada/>\n\n=== Mainstream popularity ===\nBy 2015, the daily fantasy sports industry had experienced a major growth in mainstream popularity. The rise was credited to several factors, including the convenience of the format, the ability to access the services on [[mobile device]]s, and aggressive marketing campaigns which promoted the prospective cash prizes of their largest contests.<ref name=sbj-pushes/><ref name=nytmag-sucker /><ref name=wp-riseofdaily/><ref name=nyt-dfsscandal>{{cite web|title=Scandal Erupts in Unregulated World of Fantasy Sports|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/06/sports/fanduel-draftkings-fantasy-employees-bet-rivals.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 8, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> The structure and payouts of daily fantasy games have been described as providing a feeling of \"[[instant gratification]]\" to its players, similar to that of [[online gambling]].<ref name=wp-riseofdaily/>\n\nWriting for ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', [[Jay Caspian Kang]] noted that despite its similarities to gambling, DFS appealed to mainstream sports fans because it evoked the feelings of community commonly associated with traditional fantasy sports, rather than the \"shady underground games\" of poker.<ref name=nytmag-sucker /> The popularity of daily fantasy has also influenced fan engagement with sports; [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] president Erik Shanks felt that daily fantasy sports help improve television viewership of sporting events, while FanDuel stated that players became more engaged with sports content after joining the service.<ref name=wp-riseofdaily>{{cite web|title=The rise of daily fantasy sports, online betting\u2019s newest empire|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonkblog/wp/2015/07/28/how-daily-fantasy-sites-became-pro-sports-newest-addiction-machine/|accessdate=October 9, 2015|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Yahoo!, a historic provider of season-length fantasy sports, announced that it would begin to offer paid daily and weekly fantasy games as part of its [[Yahoo! Sports]] website.<ref name=nyt-yahoodailyfantasy>{{cite web|title=Yahoo Will Enter Daily Fantasy Sports Market|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/technology/yahoo-will-enter-daily-fantasy-sports-market.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 9, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Moneyball, one of the first Australian DFS services, was also established by former [[Fairfax Media]] employees James Fitzgerald and Rax Huq; the company secured [[Australian dollar|$]]1.8 million in series A funding. Fitzgerald noted that the sports betting industry in Australia had brought in $900 million in yearly revenue and that DFS was \"a more ethically and morally preferred means of partnership with a [[bookmaker]].\"<ref name=afr-moneyball>{{cite web|title=Moneyball the new sporting fantasy|url=http://www.afr.com/brand/chanticleer/moneyball-the-new-sporting-fantasy-20150904-gjfkw5|accessdate=December 13, 2015|work=Australian Financial Review}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, DraftKings and FanDuel expanded their offerings into [[electronic sports|competitive video gaming]]; FanDuel acquired the e-sports focused DFS service AlphaDraft (which FanDuel planned to operate as an independent brand), while DraftKings added contests for the 2015 [[League of Legends World Championship|''League of Legends'' World Championship]].<ref name=recode-esportsdfs/><ref name=vb-dklol>{{cite web|title=DraftKings brings its daily-fantasy sports empire to esports|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/09/23/draftkings-brings-its-daily-fantasy-sports-empire-to-esports/|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Increased scrutiny ===\nIn 2015, daily fantasy sports began to face increased legal scrutiny. In August 2015, a class action lawsuit was filed against DraftKings, alleging that it engaged in [[false advertising]] in regards to a promotion in which the service claimed it would double a new user's first deposit. The suit alleged that DraftKings would only credit the deposit bonus to a player's account if they fulfill certain monetary and participation requirements within four months, causing them to \"incur additional and substantial monetary obligations\", rather than instantly receive the bonus as implied by advertising.<ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\"/>\n\nOn October 6, 2015, following reports that a DraftKings employee had used [[inside information]] to win $350,000 on FanDuel, [[New York Attorney General]] [[Eric Schneiderman]] announced that he had opened an investigation into the two services and the allegations that employees from the two services were using this information to win prizes from each other.<ref name=\"nyt-scandalerupts\">{{cite web|title = Scandal Erupts in Unregulated World of Fantasy Sports|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/06/sports/fanduel-draftkings-fantasy-employees-bet-rivals.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = October 5, 2015|access-date = October 10, 2015|issn = 0362-4331|first = Joe|last = Drape|first2 = Jacqueline|last2 = Williams}}</ref><ref name=\"NY AG Opens inquiry\">Drape, Joe and Williams, Jacqueline. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/07/sports/draftkings-fanduel-inquiry-new-york-attorney-general.html?_r=0 New York Attorney General Opens Inquiry Into Fantasy Sports Sites]. New York Times. October 6, 2015. Retrieved October 6, 2015.</ref> Both sites have since barred their employees from participating in daily fantasy games.<ref name=nyt-fbidfs/> On October 14, 2015, the [[FBI]] launched an investigation of its own into the two services regarding the inside information scandal.<ref name=nyt-fbidfs>{{cite web|title=F.B.I. Investigating Daily Fantasy Sports Websites|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/15/sports/draftkings-fanduel-fbi-investigation.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the scandal, multiple class-action lawsuits were filed against both DraftKings and FanDuel, with suits alleging charges such as fraud, [[Racket (crime)|racketeering]], negligence, and false advertising, arguing that the employees' use of inside information had made the games unfair. One of the lawsuits were filed by a resident of New Orleans, despite paid fantasy games being illegal in the state.<ref name=espn-dfsfalseadvertising>{{cite web|title=Class action lawsuit filed against DraftKings and FanDuel|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/13840184/class-action-lawsuit-accuses-draftkings-fanduel-negligence-fraud-false-advertising|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=wwl-nodfs>{{cite web|title=New Orleans man files lawsuit against FanDuel, DraftKings|url=http://www.wwltv.com/story/sports/nfl/saints/2015/10/15/nola/74018082/|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=[[WWL-TV|WWLTV.com]]|publisher=[[Tegna, Inc.]]}}</ref><ref name=nbc-racketeering>{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel Accused of Racketeering in New Lawsuit|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/draftkings-fanduel-accused-racketeering-new-lawsuit-n445571|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=NBC News|publisher=NBCUniversal Media}}</ref> On October 30, 2015, [[Washington Redskins|Washington]] NFL player [[Pierre Gar\u00e7on]] also filed a class-action lawsuit against FanDuel, arguing that the service had exploited his name and likeness without permission as part of its services and marketing. FanDuel objected to the lawsuit, arguing that its use of his likeness fell within [[Fantasy sport#Legal cases related to use of player statistics|existing case law]] surrounding the use of player names and statistics in fantasy sports games.<ref name=wsj-garconlawsuit>{{cite web|title=NFL Player Sues Fantasy Sports Company FanDuel|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/nfl-player-sues-fantasy-sports-company-fanduel-1446262574|website=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=Dow Jones & Company|accessdate=November 1, 2015}}</ref> Gar\u00e7on's lawsuit was settled out of court.<ref name=\"espn-2016challenges\">{{cite web|title=Four big issues facing the DFS industry in 2016|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14759843/daily-fantasy-payment-processors-leaving-big-issues-surrounding-industry|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Canadian media company [[TheScore, Inc.|TheScore]] launched QuickDraft, a daily fantasy game targeted at both Canada and the United States, based on the intellectual property of its 2014 acquisition of Swoopt. In contrast to other DFS services and in an effort to work around the increased scrutiny and uncertain legality of paid games, the service is being positioned as a free-to-play service with smaller cash prizes, a more \"casual\" atmosphere with fewer \"[[card shark|sharks]]\", and the possibility of being advertising-funded in the future.<ref name=gandm-quickdraft>{{cite web|title=TheScore bets on daily fantasy sports with QuickDraft launch|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/thescore-bets-on-daily-fantasy-sports-with-quickdraft-launch/article27683440/|accessdate=December 24, 2015|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\nDraftKings and FanDuel attempted to merge in 2017, but the deal was shelved after the U.S. [[Federal Trade Commission]] threatened to block it over concerns that the combined company would have a [[monopoly]] on paid DFS.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/draftkings-fanduel-merger-cancelled-1202495066/|title=DraftKings, FanDuel Scrap Merger Plans After FTC Opposition|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2017-07-13|work=Variety|access-date=2017-07-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"tc-ftcdkfd\">{{cite web|title=The FTC is attempting to block the DraftKings-Fanduel merger|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/06/19/the-ftc-is-attempting-to-block-the-draftkings-fanduel-merger/|website=TechCrunch|publisher=Oath|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Legalization of sports betting in the United States ===\n{{See also|Sports betting#United States}}\nIn May 2018, the [[Professional and Amateur Sports Protection Act of 1992]]\u2014which outlawed state legalization of [[sports betting]] in most U.S. states (excluding grandfathered states such as Nevada)\u2014was declared unconstitutional by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in ''[[Murphy v. National Collegiate Athletic Association]]''. The following month, Delaware became the first state to create new legislation to allow sports betting,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/sports/wp/2018/06/05/delaware-first-to-bet-on-sports-gambling-but-it-might-not-pay-off/?noredirect=on|title=Delaware is the first new state to bet on sports gambling, but it might not pay off|author=Rick Maese|date=5 June 2018|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> followed shortly by New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/11/nyregion/sports-betting-legalized-nj.html|title=New Jersey Legalizes Sports Betting|author=Nick Corasaniti|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 31, 2018|date=11 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/betting/supreme-court-strikes-down-law-banning-sports-betting-outside-nevada|title=Supreme Court strikes down law banning sports betting outside Nevada|date=14 May 2018|author=Gary Martin|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAnalysts predicted that the duopoly of DraftKings and FanDuel would make moves to capitalize on the decision, including leveraging their regulatory expertise and influence to lobby for state legalization of sports betting, and incorporating betting features into their platforms to take advantage of their existing market positions and [[brand recognition]]. Later that month, FanDuel announced that it would be acquired by [[Flutter Entertainment|Paddy Power Betfair]], to bolster the Irish [[bookmaker]]'s U.S. operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/draftkings-and-fanduel-prepare-to-cash-in-on-the-supreme-courts-ruling-on-sports-gambling/|title=DraftKings and FanDuel Prepare to Cash In on the Supreme Court's Ruling on Sports Gambling|work=Adweek|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2018/05/14/draftkings/rXTu9nxKFjFdYPfUHITQuM/story.html|title=Sports betting ruling could shake up Mass. gaming|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=2018-07-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710010214/https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2018/05/14/draftkings/rXTu9nxKFjFdYPfUHITQuM/story.html|archive-date=July 10, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/fanduel-paddy-power-betfair-acquisition-1202819754/|title=FanDuel Acquired by Paddy Power Betfair|last=Roettgers|first=Janko|date=2018-05-23|work=Variety|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more-sports/ny-sports-fanduel-draftkings-sports-betting-20180628-story.html|title=How FanDuel and DraftKings are taking aim at the world of sports gambling: 'The whole marketplace is going to evolve'|last=Grossman|first=Evan|work=New York Daily News|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref> FanDuel opened a branded [[sportsbook]] at New Jersey's [[Meadowlands Racetrack]] in July 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/24077347/fanduel-open-sportsbook-meadowlands-racetrack-new-jersey|title=FanDuel to open sportsbook at Meadowlands|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-07-31|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/11/nyregion/sports-betting-legalized-nj.html|title=New Jersey Legalizes Sports Betting|author=Nick Corasaniti|work=The New York Times|date=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing ==\nThe aggressive marketing tactics used by daily fantasy services have also affected the growth of the industry. In June 2015, DraftKings entered into a three-year sponsorship deal with ESPN valued at $250 million; the deal gave DraftKings exclusivity in advertising daily fantasy services on ESPN networks beginning in January 2016, and included \"[[Product placement|integration]]\" of the service into ESPN's television and digital content. DraftKings also entered into an advertising deal with [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]]; in exchange for Fox acquiring an $150 million equity stake in the company, DraftKings agreed to buy $250 million in advertising over the next three years.<ref name=recode-draftkingsfox>{{cite web |title=DraftKings Raises $300 Million, Promises to Spend Much of It With Fox Sports |url=http://recode.net/2015/07/26/another-unicorn-is-born-draftkings-snags-300-million-and-massive-fox-ad-deal/ |accessdate=October 15, 2015 |work=Re/code |publisher=Vox Media |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151012103242/http://recode.net/2015/07/26/another-unicorn-is-born-draftkings-snags-300-million-and-massive-fox-ad-deal/ |archivedate=October 12, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=variety-espndraftkings>{{cite web|title=ESPN Teams with DraftKings as Exclusive Daily Fantasy-Sports Partner|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/espn-draftkings-daily-fantasy-sports-1201527028/|website=Variety|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=recode1>{{cite web|url=http://recode.net/2015/07/20/draftkings-will-pay-espn-250-million-for-ads-over-the-next-two-years/|title=DraftKings Will Pay ESPN $250 Million for Ads Over the Next Two Years|work=Re/code |date=July 20, 2015|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=betaboston3>{{cite web|url=http://www.betaboston.com/news/2015/07/26/draftkings-raises-300m-in-frenzied-fantasy-sports-land-grab/|title=DraftKings raises $300m in frenzied fantasy sports land-grab|work=BetaBoston (The Boston Globe)|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC|date=July 26, 2015|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>  DraftKings' sponsorship exclusivity deal with ESPN was also to include the acquisition of an equity stake in the company, but this aspect of the deal was reportedly called off due to objections by ESPN's parent, [[The Walt Disney Company]], over financially associating itself with activities that could be classified as gambling.<ref name=recode-draftkingsfox/><ref>{{cite web |title=DraftKings Won\u2019t Raise $250 Million From Disney, but Will Still Get ESPN Ad Deal |url=http://recode.net/2015/06/23/draftkings-wont-raise-250-million-from-disney-but-will-still-get-espn-ad-deal/ |website=Re/code |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=October 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010011822/http://recode.net/2015/06/23/draftkings-wont-raise-250-million-from-disney-but-will-still-get-espn-ad-deal/ |archivedate=October 10, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=wp-coveralert>{{cite web|title=ESPN\u2019s \u2018Cover Alerts\u2019 are going away, but other gambling talk is not|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2015/09/22/espns-cover-alerts-are-going-away-but-other-gambling-talk-is-not/|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nDraftKings and FanDuel also became known for their use of [[direct response television|direct response advertising]] on television, especially during sports telecasts.<ref name=wsj-toomanyads>{{cite web|title=Are DraftKings and FanDuel Bombarding Fans With Too Many Ads?|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/cmo/2015/09/16/are-draftkings-and-fanduel-bombarding-fans-with-too-many-ads/|accessdate=November 10, 2015|work=CMO (The Wall Street Journal)|date=September 16, 2015}}</ref><ref name=crains-toomanyads>{{cite web|title=Future of daily fantasy sports hard to predict as industry scrutiny increases|url=http://www.crainscleveland.com/article/20151110/BLOGS06/151119976/future-of-daily-fantasy-sports-hard-to-predict-as-industry-scrutiny|accessdate=November 10, 2015|work=Crain's Cleveland Business}}</ref> Capitalizing on the start of football season, iSpot.tv estimated that DraftKings and FanDuel collectively spent over $107 million on television advertising in September 2015 alone\u2014with nearly half being spent on advertising during [[National Football League]] telecasts ($23.6 million by DraftKings, and $26.7 million spent by FanDuel). Of the total, $60.1 million was spent by DraftKings, with $7.95 million spent during [[college football]] games, $2.05 million during ESPN's sports news program ''[[SportsCenter]]'', and $1.36 million during ''[[South Park]]'' episodes.<ref name=adage-dkspending>{{cite web|title=Fantasy Sports Sites DraftKings, FanDuel September Spend Tops $100 Million|url=http://adage.com/article/media/draftkings-fanduel-spe/300658/|accessdate=October 9, 2015|work=Advertising Age}}</ref> The marketing push was met with a negative reaction from viewers on [[social networking service|social networks]] such as [[Twitter]], who considered the repetitive airplay of DFS commercials during football games to be an annoyance.<ref name=wsj-toomanyads/><ref name=\"digiday-dfsads\">{{cite magazine|last1=Vallnsky|first1=Jordan|title=Everybody hated those DraftKings and FanDuel commercials, data shows|url=http://digiday.com/brands/everybody-hated-draftkings-fanduel-commercials-data-shows/|magazine=[[Digiday]]|quote=People voiced their annoyance on Twitter, labeling them as \u201cfreaking annoying\u201d or mocking the incessant manner they aired.|accessdate=April 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe increased legal scrutiny surrounding DFS resulted in providers spending less on marketing in order to focus more on legal costs.<ref name=\"wsj-merge\">{{cite web|title=DraftKings and FanDuel Agree to Merge|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/draftkings-and-fanduel-agree-to-merge-1479479405|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> On February 10, 2016, it was reported that ESPN had backed out of its advertising deal with DraftKings, and that Fox had marked down its investment in DraftKings by 60%\u2014a loss of $95 million.<ref name=\"sbj-foxmarkdown\">{{cite web|title=Fox Marks Down $160M Investment In DraftKings By About 60%|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2016/02/10/Finance/Fox-DraftKings.aspx|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=Sports Business Journal|date=February 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"lvrj-dealends\">{{cite web|title=ESPN ends DraftKings deal|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/espn-ends-draftkings-deal|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=February 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Classification as gambling ==\n{{see also|Fantasy sport#Legal issues in the United States}}\nThere are conflicting arguments over whether paid daily fantasy sports games constitute [[gambling]], due to its mixture of [[game of chance|chance]]-based and [[game of skill|skill]]-based elements.<ref name=seatimes-whygambling/><ref name=\"Irwin NYT\"/><ref name=deadspin-dkceobetting/> Critics of DFS have argued that because athlete performance can vary on a week-to-week basis, players are essentially [[sports betting|wagering]] on the performance of individual athletes during a given game, rather than managing their team on a week-to-week basis across a season.<ref name=seatimes-whygambling/><ref name=\"Irwin NYT\"/><ref name=deadspin-dkceobetting/>  On the other hand, proponents have argued that the act of preparing a daily fantasy team is an activity of skill, as it requires knowledge of the sport, its individual players and their respective performance at a particular moment in time, and the ability to select suitable players within the limitation of a salary cap.<ref name=ty-skillandknowledge>{{cite web|title=Commentary: Skill and knowledge are key players in fantasy sports|url=http://www.timesunion.com/tuplus-opinion/article/Commentary-Skill-and-knowledge-are-key-players-6663864.php|accessdate=December 2, 2015|work=Times-Union|date=December 1, 2015|location=Albany}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"lsr-carveout\">{{cite web |url=http://www.legalsportsreport.com/6593/senator-that-created-fantasy-sports-carveout/|title=Latest Revelation On Federal Fantasy Sports Carve Out: Senator Who Created It Says DFS Should Be Regulated|date=December 1, 2015|website=LegalSportsReport|access-date=December 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=lsr-gameofskill>{{cite web|title=I Believe Daily Fantasy Sports Is a Game Of Skill, And Here\u2019s The Proof|url=http://www.legalsportsreport.com/820/view-why-dfs-is-a-game-of-skill/|website=LegalSportsReport|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an \"[[Reddit#IAmA and AMA|IAmA]]\" thread on [[Reddit]], DraftKings CEO Jason Robins described the service as being \"almost identical to a [[casino]]\", described the concept of DFS as a cross between fantasy sports and [[online poker]], and repeatedly referred to the service using gambling-oriented terms such as \"wager\" and \"betting\".<ref name=nv-memo/><ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\">Hohler, Bob. [https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2015/08/02/fantasy-games-draw-scrutiny-ban-sports-gambling-blurs/XxWUs2cwrveLvJe8bFt3wI/story.html An uncertain line between fantasy sports, gambling]. ''The Boston Globe'' (Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC). August 2, 2015. Retrieved September 29, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Irwin NYT\">Irwin, Neil. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/27/upshot/daily-fantasy-sports-and-the-hidden-cost-of-americas-weird-gambling-laws.html?_r=0 Daily Fantasy Sports and the Hidden Cost of America\u2019s Weird Gambling Laws]. The New York Times. September 24, 2015. Retrieved September 29, 2015.</ref><ref name=deadspin-dkceobetting>{{cite web|title=DraftKings CEO Described Site As A Casino, Called It Betting|url=http://deadspin.com/draftkings-ceo-described-site-as-a-casino-called-it-be-1737195689|website=Deadspin|publisher=Gawker Media|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=lvrj-dkceo>{{cite web|title=AG: DraftKings CEO called daily fantasy sports 'a casino'|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/gambling/ag-draftkings-ceo-called-daily-fantasy-sports-casino|accessdate=October 19, 2015|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal}}</ref><ref name=washingtonpost1>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/09/21/are-daily-fantasy-sports-even-legal/ |title=Are daily fantasy sports even legal? |work=The Washington Post|date=September 21, 2015 |accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> DraftKings and FanDuel have also entered into affiliation and sponsorship agreements with gambling-oriented entities; DraftKings sponsored the [[2015 Belmont Stakes]] and the [[World Series of Poker]], while FanDuel has affiliated with websites related to sports betting.<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry/> At the same time, both companies have stated that their daily fantasy games represent a game of skill.<ref name=espn-nydfs/> In the 2007 federal lawsuit ''Humphrey v. Viacom, Inc.'', Judge [[Dennis M. Cavanaugh]] of the U.S. District Court of New Jersey distinguished an \"entry fee\" in a paid fantasy sports competition as being a fee required to participate rather than a \"wager\", because they are \"paid unconditionally\", and because the prizes in such games were \"guaranteed\" and determined in advance.<ref name=espn-resrequest/><ref name=espn-biggestissues/>\n\n=== Skill of players ===\n''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'' acknowledged that daily fantasy contests are often won by a minority of skilled professional players, or \"[[Card shark|sharks]]\", who employ \"elaborate statistical modeling and automated tools that can manage hundreds of entries at once and identify the weakest opponents\". A DFS player interviewed by ''Bloomberg'' argued that \"no matter how much somebody knows about sports, if you put an established player up against a new player, that established player's probably going to have a 75 percent chance of winning\u2014at least.\"<ref name=\"bloomberg-youcantwin\">{{Cite web|title = You Aren't Good Enough to Win Money Playing Daily Fantasy Football|url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-10/you-aren-t-good-enough-to-win-money-playing-daily-fantasy-football|website = Bloomberg Businessweek|date=September 10, 2015|accessdate = December 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nytmag-sucker /> A study by [[McKinsey & Company]] over the first half of the [[2015 MLB season]] estimated that 91% of winnings were won by only 1.3% of players. FanDuel CEO Nigel Eccles disputed the accuracy of the study, arguing that its daily fantasy baseball contests do not have as many participants as those it runs for football.<ref name=wsj-addiction>{{cite web|title=Is Daily Fantasy Too Addictive for Its Youngest Players?|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/is-daily-fantasy-too-addictive-for-its-youngest-players-1448338822|accessdate=November 24, 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=November 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-dkdesignation\">{{cite web|title=DraftKings to create designation for elite players, ban offsite scripts|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14623271/draftkings-bans-use-offsite-scripts-identify-experienced-players|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', [[Jay Caspian Kang]] argued that DFS games themselves were \"not inherently crooked\", explaining that \"most of the benefits praised by its enthusiasts \u2014 the ease of play, the camaraderie among fans, the challenge of solving what amounts to a math puzzle \u2014 are real. It does take skill to parse game film, diligently follow the news and interpret the thousands of bits of sports information that are generated each night. If a problem gambler at the poker rooms I frequent in New York City were to hire a programmer and flood the D.F.S. market with his lineups, he would almost certainly hemorrhage money.\"<ref name=nytmag-sucker />\n\nIn response to these concerns, DFS services implemented changes to improve the fairness and transparency of their contests, including entry limits, banning off-site scripts, identifying veteran-level players, allowing users to block players they do not wish to compete against, and adding beginner-level contests intended for new users.<ref name=\"espn-dkdesignation\"/><ref name=\"lsr-transparency\">{{cite web|last1=Gouker|first1=Dustin|title=Yahoo Daily Fantasy Sports Rolls Out Changes To \u2018Make Contests More Transparent\u2019|url=http://www.legalsportsreport.com/9188/yahoo-daily-fantasy-changes/|website=Legal Sports Report|accessdate=April 6, 2016|date=March 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg-youcantwin\" />\n\n=== Legal definitions of gambling ===\nIn U.S. federal law, criminal gambling statutes include the [[Federal Wire Act]]\u2014which prohibits interstate sports wagering, the Illegal Gambling Business Act ({{USC|18|1955}})\u2014which prohibits the interstate conduct of wagering activity prohibited under state law,<ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah/><ref name=\"31-5361\"/> and the [[Unlawful Internet Gambling Enforcement Act]] (UIGEA)\u2014which prohibits the transfer of funds in connection to [[online gambling]] that is prohibited under state law.<ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\" /><ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah/> The [[Professional and Amateur Sports Protection Act of 1992]] also forbade all states, besides Nevada and other grandfathered states, from authorizing sports wagering activities, although it was ruled in May 2018 that this law was unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/23501236/supreme-court-strikes-federal-law-prohibiting-sports-gambling|title=Supreme Court strikes down sports betting law|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2017/12/04/place-your-bets-on-federalism-thoughts-on-todays-oral-argument-in-christie-v-ncaa/|title=Opinion {{!}} Place your bets on federalism \u2014 thoughts on today's oral argument in Christie v. NCAA|last=Somin|first=Ilya|date=2017-12-04|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nEach state applies varying standards in regards to determining whether a game is one of skill, or of chance; in most states, this determination is based on whether the skill-based elements of the game are predominant over those of chance, and whether these chance-based elements have more than an incidental effect on the outcome of the game ([[Dominant Factor Test|dominant factor test]], material degree).<ref name=wired-dowswinning/> Some states use stricter criteria, under which games whose outcomes are influenced by any element of chance, or appeal to a \"gambling instinct\", are considered games of chance, regardless of the presence of skill-based elements.<ref name=wired-dowswinning>{{cite web|title=Does Winning at Fantasy Sports Require Skill or Dumb Luck?|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/10/does-winning-at-fantasy-sports-require-skill-or-dumb-luck/|accessdate=November 12, 2015|work=Wired|date=October 17, 2015}}</ref> In the state of Illinois, any game played for cash where the players are not the \"actual contestants\" in a \"bona fide contest for the determination of skill, speed, strength, or endurance\", constitutes gambling.<ref name=ati-decision/><ref name=espn-illinoisban/>\n\nIn 2015, the Canadian Gaming Association commissioned an opinion on the legality of DFS in Canada from former [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] general counsel Don Bourgeois. He determined that DFS would likely be classified as a game of chance under Canadian law, going on to say in an interview that under the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code of Canada]], games that mix chance- and skill-based elements are considered games of chance. However, Canadian authorities have not yet targeted DFS services; historically, the government has only targeted illegal gambling operations that have a presence within the country.<ref name=tsn-dfsillegalcanada>{{cite web|title=Daily fantasy sports gaming illegal in Canada, trade group says|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/daily-fantasy-sports-gaming-illegal-in-canada-trade-group-says-1.392182|website=TSN.ca|publisher=Bell Media|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> While the service [[Sport Select]] offers legal sports wagering games through Canada's [[lottery|lotteries]], it is subject to a legal prohibition on wagering on individual sporting events.<ref name=np-sportselect>{{cite web|title=Colby Cosh: The Senate spent three years pondering a one-line bill, which will likely now expire|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/full-comment/colby-cosh-the-senate-spent-three-years-pondering-a-one-line-bill-which-will-likely-now-expire|accessdate=December 24, 2015|work=National Post|publisher=Postmedia Network}}</ref>\n\n==== UIGEA carve-out ====\nThe UIGEA has frequently been cited as having exempted daily fantasy games from being considered gambling, as the law does not consider an online contest with pre-determined prizes, and an outcome based on skill that is \"determined predominantly by accumulated statistical results of sporting events, including any non-participant's individual performances in such sporting events\", to be unlawful wagering.<ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\" /><ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah/><ref>{{uscsub|31|5362|1|E|ix}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Blur Lines\">{{cite web |last1=Brustein |first1=Joshua |title=Fantasy Sports and Gambling: Line Is Blurred |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/12/sports/web-sites-blur-line-between-fantasy-sports-and-gambling.html?_r=0 |accessdate=October 17, 2015 |work=The New York Times |date=March 11, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151022200534/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/12/sports/web-sites-blur-line-between-fantasy-sports-and-gambling.html?_r=0 |archivedate=October 22, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> The carve-out was based on the language of an amendment proposed by Senator [[Richard Bryan]] to the failed [[Internet Gambling Prohibition Act]].<ref name=\"lsr-carveout\"/><ref name=espn-trueorigin>{{cite web|title=The true Congressional origin of daily fantasy sports|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/13993288/daily-fantasy-investigating-where-fantasy-carve-daily-fantasy-sports-actually-came-congress|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe act itself does not define unlawful internet wagering, and expressly refrains from altering the legality of any underlying conduct other than funds transfers, meaning that state law remains binding.<ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah/><ref name=\"31-5361\"/><ref name=\"31-5361\">{{USC|31|5361}}</ref> It also depends on banks to act as enforcers of the prohibitions.<ref name=\"31-5364\">{{USC|31|5364}}</ref> Congressman [[Jim Leach]], who authored the UIGEA, explained that the fantasy sports carve-out was meant to relieve the burden of enforcement of the act by banks, nor cover the present-day daily fantasy industry, and that \"it is sheer chutzpah for a fantasy sports company to cite the law as a legal basis for existing\".<ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah>{{cite web|title=How Will the Government Change the Game for Daily Fantasy Sports?|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-15/how-will-the-government-change-the-game-for-daily-fantasy-sports-|accessdate=October 20, 2015|work=Bloomberg News|date=October 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=tp-hotnewform>{{cite web|title=The Hot New Form Of Fantasy Sports Is Probably Addictive, Potentially Illegal And Completely Unregulated|url=http://thinkprogress.org/sports/2015/05/07/3648832/daily-fantasy-sports-gambling/|website=Think Progress|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/sports/articles/2015/10/12/former-congressman-says-dfs-is-cauldron-of-daily-betting | title= Author of anti-gambling law says \"sheer chutzpah\" for daily fantasy sites to claim legitimacy |agency=Associated Press |work=U.S. News and World Report|date=October 12, 2015|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\n=== Self-imposed restrictions ===\nDaily fantasy services have historically blocked residents of Arizona, Iowa, Louisiana, Montana and Washington from participating in paid games, under a presumption that DFS is illegal in these states due to the strictness of their gambling laws.<ref name=fortune-nydkruling /><ref name=nv-memo/><ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\" /><ref name=seatimes-whygambling>{{cite web|title=Is it gambling? Why fantasy sports sites like DraftKings and FanDuel are illegal in Washington state|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/is-it-gambling-why-fantasy-sports-sites-like-draftkings-and-fanduel-are-illegal-in-washington-state/|accessdate=November 11, 2015|work=The Seattle Times|date=November 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=espn-nydfs/> However, a November 2015 investigation by ''The New York Times'' found that these [[geoblock]] restrictions could easily be circumvented using [[Anonymizer|anonymous proxies]], and it was estimated that in 2014, DraftKings had still collected $484,897 in entry fees from players in the five states where it had voluntarily asserted that DFS was illegal.<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry/><ref name=nyt-proxydfs>{{cite web|title=DraftKings Leaves Door Unlocked for Barred Fantasy Sports Players|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/14/sports/draftkings-leaves-door-ajar-for-barred-fantasy-sports-players.html|date=November 14, 2015|accessdate=November 18, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> These reports led to regulatory probes by investigators in the aforementioned states.<ref name=bostonglobe-dkstatelawsuits>{{cite web|title=Lawsuit accuses DraftKings of flouting bans in 5 states|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2015/11/22/regulators-probe-draftkings-business-banned-states/0xD1UDp3rNPATDZ6kLvohN/story.html|accessdate=December 22, 2015|work=Boston Globe|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC}}</ref> Both websites have since implemented measures to block proxy users.<ref name=\"nyt-closedloophole\">{{cite web|title=Fantasy Sports Site Closes Digital Loophole Ahead of Hearing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/25/sports/football/fantasy-sports-site-draftkings-closes-digital-loophole-ahead-of-hearing.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=April 6, 2016|date=November 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nv-memo/><ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\" /><ref name=seatimes-whygambling/><ref name=espn-nydfs/>\n\n=== Legal opinions and challenges ===\nLouisiana attempted to pass a law that would exempt fantasy sports from its anti-online gambling laws, but the bill was defeated as the result of lobbying by both the [[Louisiana Family Forum]] (which showed concerns that players could develop an [[Gambling addiction|addiction]] to daily fantasy games), and the Louisiana Video Gaming Association (which felt that DFS would cannibalize the legal [[video poker]] industry, and needed to be highly regulated).<ref name=nolacom-louisianaban>{{cite web|title=The reality of fantasy sports? It's illegal in Louisiana when stakes are involved|url=http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/04/fantasy_football_illegal_louis.html|accessdate=October 20, 2015|work=NOLA.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 15, 2015, the [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]] published a memorandum ruling that daily fantasy sports games were a form of sports wagering, and that DFS services must cease serving customers in the state of Nevada until they obtain a sports pool license.<ref name=nv-memo>{{cite web|title=Legality of Daily Fantasy Sports Under Nevada Law|url=http://gaming.nv.gov/modules/showdocument.aspx?documentid=10487|publisher=State of Nevada|accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nyt-dfsnevada>{{cite web|title=Nevada Says It Will Treat Daily Fantasy Sports Sites as Gambling|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/16/sports/gambling-regulators-block-daily-fantasy-sites-in-nevada.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=October 15, 2015}}</ref> The Board felt that DFS fell under the state's definitions of a \"gambling game\" and a \"sports pool\", as they \"[accept] wagers on sporting events or other events by any system or method of wagering\", including wagers on events occurring during a sporting event ([[Proposition bet|props]]), combinations of multiple events occurring within an event ([[Parlay (gambling)|parlays]]), and against the performance of other players, with \"rake-offs\" taken by the operator on each wager (defined as a \"percentage game\" under Nevada law).<ref name=nv-memo/> In further support of its argument, the memorandum cited Jason Robins' comments on Reddit that described DraftKings using gambling-oriented terminology; the board stated that its classification was \"consistent with how operators of certain daily fantasy sports describe themselves\".<ref name=nv-memo/>\n\nOn December 23, 2015, [[Illinois Attorney General]] [[Lisa Madigan]] ruled that daily fantasy sports were a form of unlawful gambling under state law. Madigan determined that in DFS, the players are not the \"actual contestants\" in a contest of skill, but the athletes themselves, meaning that \"persons whose wagers depend upon how particular, selected athletes perform in actual sporting events stand in no different stead than persons who wager on the outcome of any sporting event in which they are not participants.\"<ref name=ati-decision>{{cite web|title=Sports and Gaming: Daily Fantasy Sports Contests as Gambling|url=http://www.illinoisattorneygeneral.gov/opinions/2015/15-006.pdf|publisher=Attorney General of Illinois|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=espn-illinoisban>{{cite web|title=Illinois AG Lisa Madigan: DFS betting is illegal gambling|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14430508/illinois-attorney-general-lisa-madigan-says-daily-fantasy-sports-betting-illegal-gambling|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> DraftKings and FanDuel filed lawsuits against the Attorney General the following day, seeking a court opinion on the matter. The DraftKings lawsuit argued that the order \"has set off a chain of events that\u2014if unchecked\u2014 will unjustly destroy a legitimate industry.\"<ref name=espn-illawsuit>{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel files lawsuit against Illinois attorney general|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14434566/draftkings-files-lawsuit-illinois-attorney-general-lisa-madigan-declaring-daily-fantasy-sports-illegal-gambling|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 25, 2015}}</ref> The sites may continue to operate in the state, pending the result of court hearings.<ref name=crains-ilcontinue>{{cite web|last1=Ecker|first1=Danny|title=Daily fantasy sports sites can operate during court challenge|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20151229/BLOGS04/151229888/daily-fantasy-sports-sites-can-operate-during-court-challenge|website=Crain's Chicago Business|accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2016, [[Attorney General of Texas]] [[Ken Paxton]] issued an opinion, stating that \"it is prohibited gambling in Texas if you bet on the performance of a participant in a sporting event and the house takes a cut.\" On the other hand, Paxton stated that traditional, season-length fantasy sports were legal.<ref name=espn-texasdfs>{{cite web|title=Texas says daily fantasy is gambling and therefore illegal|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14603096/texas-declares-daily-fantasy-games-illegal-saying-prohibited-gambling|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=nyt-texasdfs>{{cite web|title=Texas Attorney General Deems Daily Fantasy Sports Illegal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/20/sports/texas-attorney-general-deems-daily-fantasy-sports-illegal.html?_r=0|accessdate=January 30, 2016|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Prior to the ruling, it was also reported that Gary Grief, executive director of the [[Texas Lottery]], had been investigating ways of integrating DFS into the state lottery system, including attempts to pursue DraftKings as a partner for a proposed game which would have offered credit for the service as prizes.<ref name=\"dmewss-texaslotto\">{{cite web|title=Texas Lottery was in hot pursuit of DraftKings daily fantasy game, records show|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/state/headlines/20160115-records-texas-lottery-was-in-hot-pursuit-of-fantasy-sports-game.ece|website=Dallas Morning News|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref> FanDuel ceased serving residents of Texas, but DraftKings filed a request for declaratory judgment on March 4, 2016, seeking clarification on the matter.<ref name=\"chron-texasfd\">{{cite news|last1=Rosenthal|first1=Brian M.|title=FanDuel to leave Texas; DraftKings files motion to continue operating|url=http://www.chron.com/news/politics/texas/article/FanDuel-to-stop-operating-in-Texas-Paxton-says-6871061.php|accessdate=April 6, 2016|work=Houston Chronicle|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2016, at the request of Senator [[Rosalyn Baker]], [[Attorney General of Hawaii]] [[Doug Chin]] issued an opinion that DFS could be illegal under [[Hawaii]] law, as it involves a wager on an event outside of the player's control. He explained that \"the technology may have changed, but the vice has not.\"<ref name=\"atlantic-dfshawaii\">{{cite web|title=A Blow to Daily Fantasy Sports in Hawaii|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/01/hawaii-might-bid-daily-fantasy-sports-aloha/433809/|accessdate=February 1, 2016|work=The Atlantic|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2016, [[Attorney General of Alabama]] [[Luther Strange]] ruled that DFS was illegal under state law, and sent cease and desist notices to DraftKings and FanDuel ordering them to stop serving residents of Alabama by May 1, 2016. He argued that while picking players for a fantasy team is an activity of skill, player performance can vary, and Alabama law dictates that it is illegal to risk something of value on any game with an element of chance.<ref name=\"alcom-alabama\">{{cite web|last1=Stein|first1=Kelsey|title=Daily fantasy sports like DraftKings, FanDuel are illegal gambling, Alabama AG says|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2016/04/daily_fantasy_sports_like_draf.html|website=AL.com|publisher=Alabama Media Group (Advance Publications)|accessdate=April 6, 2016|date=April 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Legalization ====\nIn September 2015, the state of [[Massachusetts]] tabled a bill exploring the possibility of allowing the [[Massachusetts Lottery]] to run online, skill-based games, such as daily fantasy sports.<ref name=bostonglobe-masslotterydfs>{{cite web|title=Mass. AG \u2018reviewing\u2019 daily fantasy sports as lawmakers look into lottery expansion|url=http://www.betaboston.com/news/2015/09/17/mass-ag-reviewing-daily-fantasy-sports-as-lawmakers-look-into-lottery-expansion/|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=BetaBoston (The Boston Globe)|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC|date=September 17, 2015}}</ref> On November 19, 2015, the government announced that it would allow daily fantasy sports services to operate within Massachusetts under proposed regulations, including the requirement for all players to be 21 and over, banning members of the professional sports industry from playing the games (including athletes), and banning the marketing of the services in colleges and high schools.<ref name=verge-msreg>{{cite web|title=Massachusetts will allow daily fantasy sports to operate under new regulations|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/11/19/9761348/massachusetts-betting-sites-daily-fantasy-sports-legal|website=The Verge|accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, 2016, the state of [[Virginia]] passed legislation regulating \"fantasy contests\", defined as skill-based games with cash prizes that are based on the \"accumulated statistical results of the performance of individuals\"; the law makes no reference to sports or DFS. Services must pay a $50,000 registration fee, be restricted to those who are 18 and older, and be subject to yearly independent audits. The law was criticized for being broadly-worded, with critics believing that it could feasibly apply to season-length games or any similar activities, and that the required licensing fee adds a financial barrier for doing business in the state.<ref name=\"verge-virginia\">{{cite web|title=Virginia becomes first state to formally legalize daily fantasy sports|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/7/11176006/virginia-daily-fantasy-sports-law-draftkings-fanduel|website=The Verge|accessdate=March 8, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"virpilot-sideline\">{{cite web|title=Bill could sideline season-long fantasy football in Virginia, open up state to online gambling|url=http://pilotonline.com/business/consumer/bill-could-sideline-season-long-fantasy-football-in-virginia-open/article_e73ad76c-03ca-5552-ab9e-ab06019a4704.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|work=The Virginian-Pilot}}</ref><ref name=\"lsr-viconflict\">{{cite web|title=Conflict Over Virginia Fantasy Sports Bill Points To Fissure Between DFS And Season-Long Operators|url=http://www.legalsportsreport.com/8751/virginia-fantasy-sports-bill-conflict/|website=LegalSportsReport|accessdate=March 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2016, it was reported that the U.S. House Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade was planning to discuss the legal aspects of DFS in a hearing.<ref name=\"espn-subcommittee\">{{cite web|last1=Purdum|first1=David|title=Congressional subcommittee examining daily fantasy|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/15498648/congressional-subcommittee-examining-daily-fantasy-sports|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=May 11, 2016|date=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, New York became the largest state to legalize daily fantasy sports.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.playny.com/daily-fantasy-sports-to-resume-in-new-york-state/|title=Daily Fantasy Sports Are Back In Business In New York State|date=2016-08-30|work=Play NY|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref> Nearby New Jersey and Pennsylvania each followed suit in mid-2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.njgamblingsites.com/8726/new-jersey-fantasy-sports-law/|title=NJ Gets On Fantasy Sports Bandwagon As Christie Signs New Law|date=2017-08-31|work=NJ Gambling Sites|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paonlinecasino.com/1959/pa-online-gambling-h-271-passes-legislature/|title=Online Gambling Set To Roll In Pennsylvania|website=www.paonlinecasino.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2017, 18 different states had legalized paid-entry fantasy sports contests. Governor [[John Kasich]] of [[Ohio]] signed a bill in late December making Ohio the eighteenth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.legalsportsreport.com/16922/kasich-signs-fantasy-sports-bill-ohio/|title=Kasich Signs Fantasy Sports Bill; Ohio Becomes 18th State With Law|date=2017-12-22|work=Legal Sports Report|access-date=2018-01-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== New York ruling and lawsuit ====\nOn November 10, 2015, Attorney General of New York State Eric Schneiderman issued a cease-and-desist order to DraftKings and FanDuel, arguing that DFS was illegal under state law (which specifies that games where players \"risk something of value\" and do not have \"control or influence\" over the outcome, are gambling),<ref name=espn-nybanned/><ref name=fortune-dfshearing/> and ordering the two services to cease serving residents of New York. He stated that DFS \"wagers\" represented \"a wager on a 'contest of chance' where winning or losing depends on numerous elements of chance to a 'material degree'\". He characterized the DFS industry as being a \"massive, multi-billion-dollar scheme intended to evade the law and fleece sports fans across the country\", causing the \"same public health and economic problems associated with gambling, particularly for populations prone to [[gambling addiction]] and individuals who are unprepared to sustain losses, lured by the promise of easy money.\"<ref name=espn-nydfs>{{cite web|title=N.Y. AG declares DFS, Fan Duel illegal gambling sites, not fantasy games|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14100780/newyork-attorney-general-declares-daily-fantasy-sports-gambling|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 10, 2015|date=November 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=ars-nydeny/>\n\nIn response, DraftKings and FanDuel filed lawsuits against the state of New York on November 13, arguing that their games were one of skill, they had been denied [[due process]] due to the Attorney General's abruptness, that he does not have the power to make such a ruling, and that Schneiderman engaged in [[tortious interference]] by sending cease and desist notices to their payment processors.<ref name=si-dkfdnylawsuit>{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel lawsuits take daily fantasy battle into critical phase|url=https://www.si.com/fantasy/2015/11/13/draftkings-fanduel-lawsuits-daily-fantasy-new-york|accessdate=November 13, 2015|work=Sports Illustrated|date=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=usatoday-nylawsuit>{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel file lawsuits in New York after cease-and-desist order|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/fantasy/2015/11/13/draftkings-lawsuit-new-york-cease-desist-order/75705742/|accessdate=November 14, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=Gannett}}</ref> On November 16, the two services tried to request a temporary [[restraining order]] to prevent Schneiderman from enforcing the cease-and-desist, but a state judge declared their request to be premature. Following the hearing, a spokesperson for the Attorney General declared that he could file a formal lawsuit against the two sites \"as soon as tomorrow\". The same day, state senator [[Michael Ranzenhofer]] introduced a bill that would explicitly classify daily fantasy sports as a game of skill.<ref name=espn-resrequest>{{cite web|title=New York judge denies DraftKings, FanDuel restraining order request|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14148242/newyork-judge-denies-draftkings-fanduel-restraining-order-request|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=ars-nydeny>{{cite web|title=NY has a legal lottery, says online fantasy sports are an illegal lottery|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2015/11/ny-has-a-lottery-but-says-online-fantasy-sports-are-an-illegal-lottery/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn November 17, 2015, the Attorney General filed a request for a temporary injunction to force DraftKings and FanDuel to cease serving customers in the state of New York. In the filing, Schneiderman argued that DFS was merely a \"re-branding\" of sports betting, and in response to claims that DFS constitutes a game of skill, he argued that \"a few good players in a poker tournament may rise to the top based on their skill; but the game is still gambling.\" Schneiderman also acknowledged that the two services had \"basic compliance issues\" (alluding to the inside information scandal), had associated themselves with gambling-oriented entities, and that DraftKings had accepted entry fees from users in states where it argued that DFS was illegal.<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry>{{cite web|title=End Sought to Fantasy Sites in New York; Yahoo Is Said to Be Added to Inquiry|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/18/sports/football/draftkings-fanduel-new-york-attorney-general-injunction.html?_r=0|accessdate=November 18, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=November 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=guardian-injunction>{{cite web|title=New York seeks injunction to shut down DraftKings and FanDuel immediately|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/nov/18/new-york-seeks-injunction-to-shut-down-draftkings-and-fanduel-immediately|accessdate=November 18, 2015|work=The Guardian|date=November 17, 2015}}</ref> The Attorney General also issued a [[subpoena]] for information from [[Yahoo!]] in regards to its own daily fantasy offerings.<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry/> FanDuel stated that it would comply with the order and restrict participation by residents of New York, while DraftKings stated that it would continue to serve them, arguing that Schneiderman's decision was based on an \"incomplete understanding of the facts about how our business operates and a fundamental misinterpretation and misapplication of the law\".<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry/><ref name=fortune-dfshearing>{{cite web|title=Daily Fantasy Sports Hearing Ends Without Decision|url=http://fortune.com/2015/11/25/fantasy-sports-hearing-no-decision/|accessdate=November 30, 2015|work=Fortune|date=November 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring hearings on November 25, 2015, Judge Manuel J. Mendez disputed assertions by the services that a player's choice of athletes represents \"control or influence\" over the outcome, stating that players are ultimately \"relying on someone else's skill\" to determine an outcome.<ref name=fortune-dfshearing/> On December 11, 2015, the temporary injunction was granted, forbidding DraftKings and FanDuel from \"accepting entry fees, wagers or bets\" from residents of New York state.<ref name=espn-biggestissues>{{cite web|title=Biggest issues for daily fantasy after New York ruling|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14342581/daily-fantasy-new-york-ruling-biggest-issues-dfs-industry|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> Mandez argued that \"the payment of an 'entry fee' as high as $10,600 on one or more contests daily could certainly be deemed risking 'something of value'.\" He also ruled that the UIGEA \"has no corresponding authority under New York State law\".<ref name=fortune-nydkruling>{{cite web|title=NY Judge Rules Against DraftKings and FanDuel, Supporting Ban|url=http://fortune.com/2015/12/11/draftkings-fanduel-shut-down-in-new-york/|website=Fortune.com|publisher=Time Inc.|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=espn-nybanned>{{cite web|title=New York Supreme Court judge rules against DraftKings, FanDuel|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14342458/new-york-supreme-court-judge-bars-draftkings-fanduel-operating-state|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> However, Mandez granted a temporary stay following requests for an appeal.<ref name=deadline-nystay>{{cite web|title=FanDuel & DraftKings Get To Stay In Biz In New York, For Now|url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/fanduel-draftkings-new-york-injunction-granted-eric-schneiderman-1201665155/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> On December 31, 2015\u2014prior to an [[appellate court|appeals court]] on whether they could continue to operate during the lawsuit, the Attorney General amended the lawsuit to demand that the two companies pay [[restitution]]\u2014including the return of all money collected from customers in New York State. Schneiderman also acknowledged the services' deceptive advertising practices, such as \"convoluted\" first deposit bonuses.<ref name=espn-payback>{{cite web|title=New York attorney general amends lawsuit against daily fantasy sites|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14458955/new-york-attorney-general-wants-draftkings-fanduel-return-profits|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=January 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 11, 2016, DraftKings' and FanDuel's stay was granted, meaning that they could continue to serve New York residents, pending the outcome of the appeal.<ref name=bloomberg-stay>{{cite web|title=New York Daily Fantasy Players in Game for NBA, NHL Playoffs|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-11/fantasy-sports-win-new-york-court-approval-to-keep-operating|accessdate=January 14, 2016|date=January 11, 2016|work=Bloomberg}}</ref> However, later that month, [[Vantiv]] announced that it would no longer provide its payment processing services to the DFS industry, and in early-February 2016, [[Citigroup]] announced that it would no longer process payments for DraftKings and FanDuel made by residents of New York State,  \"pending a final decision by the courts\".<ref name=\"deadline-citigroupblock\">{{cite web|title=FanDuel & DraftKings See Citigroup \"Block\" Transactions In NY State|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/fanduel-draftkings-citigroup-new-york-shut-down-injunction-1201697401/|website=Deadline.com|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-Vantiv\">{{cite news|title=Payment Processor to Stop Working With Daily Fantasy Sports Clients|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/30/sports/draftkings-fanduel-vantiv-daily-fantasy.html?_r=0|accessdate=March 31, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=January 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Boston Globe'' believed that a ruling on the legality of DFS in New York State would have industry-wide implications, as it is one of the largest markets for these services.<ref name=bostonglobe-dkstatelawsuits/> Writing for ''The New Yorker'', [[James Surowiecki]] believed that it was hypocritical for the state of New York to campaign against daily fantasy sports\u2014which, in an op-ed, the Attorney General classified as a \"particularly pernicious\" activity, as the state already sponsors and/or endorses other forms of legal gambling based purely on chance rather than a mix of chance and skill, such as the [[New York Lottery|state lottery]], [[List of casinos in New York|casinos]], and horse racing. Surowiecki argued that \"given the absence of a good argument for why daily fantasy should be illegal in New York, while the lottery and racetrack betting and casinos are not, the best strategy that DraftKings and FanDuel could pursue might be to get the State Legislature to eliminate the inconsistency and explicitly legalize them.\"<ref name=newyorker-hypocritical>{{cite web|last1=Surowiecki|first1=James|title=The Hypocritical Legal Campaign against Daily Fantasy Sports|url=https://www.newyorker.com/business/currency/hypocritical-legal-campaign-daily-fantasy-sports|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2016, the Attorney General announced a partial settlement of its lawsuit, under which DraftKings and FanDuel agreed to cease offering paid games in the state of New York, and abide by the result of an upcoming appeals court hearing. The hearings, which would determine whether the services would have to pay restitution, were tentatively scheduled for September 2016\u2014assuming that legislation legalizing daily fantasy sports was not passed by then. DraftKings and FanDuel spokespersons stated that the companies were working with local officials and supporting legislation to legalize DFS under state law. This settlement does not address the false advertising claims, which are still being pursued. The next day, Yahoo announced that it would voluntarily comply with the settlement and also cease offering paid games in the state of New York.<ref name=\"engadget-yahoonony\">{{cite web|title=Yahoo stops daily fantasy sports contests in New York|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/03/22/yahoo-fair-play-daily-fantasy-new-york/|accessdate=March 23, 2016|work=Engadget|publisher=AOL}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-doneny\">{{cite web|title=Fantasy Sites DraftKings and FanDuel Stop Taking Bets in New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/22/sports/football/draftkings-and-fanduel-stop-taking-bets-in-new-york.html?_r=0|accessdate=March 23, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=March 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-dknydone\">{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel will stop in NY, but appeal, legislation pending|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/15033073/draftkings-fanduel-stop-ny-appeal-legislation-pending|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 18, 2016, the New York State senate approved legislation to legalize daily fantasy sports. Daily fantasy providers will be required to pay 15.5% of their annual revenue to the [[New York Lottery]]'s education fund in order to serve customers in the state.<ref name=\"nyt-nydfslegal\">{{cite web|title=New York State Lawmakers Vote to Legalize Fantasy Sports|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/19/sports/new-york-state-lawmakers-vote-to-legalize-fantasy-sports.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=June 18, 2016|date=June 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===League policies===\nThe [[NCAA]] considers all paid fantasy games\u2014including daily fantasy\u2014to fall under its prohibition of sports wagering by [[student athlete]]s, punishable by ineligibility to participate in NCAA-sanctioned athletics for one year. Advertising for daily fantasy services are also forbidden from being broadcast during telecasts of the NCAA's tournaments. In August 2015, the NCAA and a group of ten [[athletic conference|conferences]] jointly campaigned against daily fantasy games featuring college sports, asserting that DFS is inconsistent with the NCAA's policies and values.<ref name=nyt-ncaastepsaway/><ref name=bloomberg-ncaastance>{{cite web|title=Daily Fantasy Gives the NCAA a Gambling Problem|url=http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2015-09-25/daily-fantasy-gives-the-ncaa-a-gambling-problem|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=Bloomberg View}}</ref> The [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] had discussions with its broadcast partners in an attempt to discourage the advertising of daily fantasy games during its telecasts, while both [[Big Ten Network]] and [[Pac-12 Network]] prohibited advertising for daily fantasy games involving college sports.<ref name=nyt-ncaastepsaway>{{cite web|title=N.C.A.A. Distances Itself From Daily Fantasy Websites|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/21/sports/ncaa-distances-itself-from-daily-fantasy-websites.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 21, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> On December 9, 2015, it was reported that ESPN had similarly agreed not to air advertising for daily fantasy services during telecasts of the [[College Football Playoff]].<ref name=nyt-dfscfp>{{cite web|title=ESPN and College Football Playoff Agree Not to Air Daily Fantasy Ads|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/sports/ncaafootball/espn-college-football-playoff-draftkings-fanduel-ads-daily-fantasy.html?_r=0|accessdate=December 10, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> On March 31, 2016, DraftKings and FanDuel jointly agreed to stop offering daily fantasy college sports following the conclusion of the [[2016 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]].<ref name=\"espn-nomorecollege\">{{cite web|last1=Purdum|first1=David|title=DraftKings, FanDuel to stop offering college fantasy games|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/15104454/draftkings-fanduel-stop-offering-college-fantasy-games|website=ESPN|accessdate=March 31, 2016|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe NFL does not outright ban participation in paid or daily fantasy sports games by its players and staff, but does restrict how much one may win in such games.<ref name=wp-nflrestriction>{{cite web|last1=Bonesteel|first1=Matt|title=NFL players will make a lot of money as daily-fantasy pitchmen, but not a lot of money playing it|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2015/09/29/nfl-players-will-make-a-lot-of-money-as-daily-fantasy-pitchmen-but-not-a-lot-of-money-playing-it/|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[PGA Tour]] prohibits its players from participation in paid DFS games involving golf, or endorsing DFS companies.<ref name=\"espn-pgadfs\">{{cite web|last1=Sorbel|first1=Jason|title=PGA Tour prohibiting players from playing daily fantasy|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14207028/pga-tour-prohibiting-players-competing-golf-related-daily-fantasy-sports|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Skin gambling]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Fantasy sports}}\n\n[[Category:Daily fantasy sports]]\n[[Category:Sports betting]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|daily fantasy sports|fantasy sports in general|Fantasy sport}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n'''Daily fantasy sports''' ('''DFS''') are a subset of [[fantasy sport]] games. As with traditional fantasy sports games, players compete against others by building a team of [[professional athlete]]s from a particular [[sports league|league]] or competition while remaining under a [[salary cap]], and earn points based on the actual statistical performance of the players in real-world competitions. Daily fantasy sports are an accelerated variant of traditional fantasy sports that are conducted over short-term periods, such as a week or single day of competition, as opposed to those that are played across an entire season. Daily fantasy sports are typically structured in the form of paid competitions typically referred to as a \"contest\"; winners receive a share of a pre-determined pot funded by their entry fees. A portion of entry fee payments go to the provider as [[Rake (poker)|rake]] revenue.<ref name=sg-dk500k>{{cite web|title=$500,000 DraftKings 1-Day Fantasy Baseball Contest Could Make You Rich Overnight|url=http://www.sportsgrid.com/uncategorized/500000-draftkings-1-day-fantasy-baseball-contest-could-make-you-rich-overnight/|website=[[SportsGrid]]|publisher=Anthem Media Group|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=washington1>{{cite web|last1=Kilgore|first1=Adam|title=Daily fantasy sports Web sites find riches in Internet gaming law loophole|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/daily-fantasy-sports-web-sites-find-riches-in-internet-gaming-law-loophole/2015/03/27/92988444-d172-11e4-a62f-ee745911a4ff_story.html|work=The Washington Post|date=March 27, 2015|accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[United States]], the daily fantasy sports industry is dominated by two competing services: the [[New York City|New York]]-based [[FanDuel]], and the [[Boston]]-based [[DraftKings]]. Both companies were established as [[venture capital]]-backed [[startup company|startup companies]], received funding from investment firms, sports broadcasters, leagues, and team owners, and became known for the aggressive marketing of their services. As of September 2015, both companies have an estimated value of at least $1 billion, and control 95% of the  U.S. DFS market.<ref name=adage-dkspending/><ref name=wsj-realitycheck>{{cite web|title=Daily Fantasy-Sports Operators Await Reality Check|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/daily-fantasy-sports-operators-await-reality-check-1441835630|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=September 9, 2015}}{{subscription required}}</ref> The two primarily compete against smaller DFS services, such as DRAFT, Fantasy Aces, and [[Yahoo! Sports]].<ref name=scn-fantasyaces>{{cite web|title=Fantasy Aces Could Be the \u2018Pick\u2019 of the Fantasy Sports Space |url=http://www.smallcapnetwork.com/Fantasy-Aces-Could-Be-the-Pick-of-the-Fantasy-Sports-Space/s/via/28141/article/view/p/mid/1/id/90/ |accessdate=October 15, 2015 |work=SmallCap Network }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=nyt-yahoodailyfantasy/> The popularity of the daily fantasy format has been credited to its convenience in comparison to season-length games, as well as the focus on major cash prizes in the promotion of these services. Daily fantasy has also been credited with helping to improve television viewership and engagement with sports.\n\nDaily fantasy sports have faced notable legal challenges, including disputes over whether DFS constitutes [[gambling]]. Politicians and other critics have argued that due to their format, players are essentially making [[proposition bet|proposition wagers]] on the varying performance of individual athletes in specific games, and not managing the performance of their selections on a week-to-week basis. Proponents have defended DFS as being a [[game of skill]], as the required familiarity with the players and teams, as well as salary cap management, rewards skilled players. Local laws have varying definitions of gambling games, such as whether a game's elements of chance are predominant over those or skill, or how much control the player has over the outcome of the game.\n\nIn the United States, the legality of DFS has been determined on a state-by-state basis based on local gambling laws and other rulings. The federal [[Unlawful Internet Gambling Enforcement Act]] (UIEGA) contains language dictating that fantasy sports are not considered an unlawful wager under the act; however, the act only prohibits the electronic transfer of funds from unlawful gambling as defined under state laws. A number of [[state attorneys general]] issued opinions concluding that DFS is a form of gambling, while the state of [[Nevada]] declared that DFS games must be licensed as a [[sports pool]]. The [[New York State]] lawsuit, which resulted from an investigation of DFS services after it was alleged that employees working for DraftKings and FanDuel had used [[inside information]] to win cash prizes from each other, spawned retaliatory lawsuits from the companies which alleged that the rulings were the result of a misinterpretation of the nature of their services. By December 2017, 18 states, including [[Massachusetts]] and [[Virginia]], had ruled that DFS was a legal game of skill.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gouker |first=Dustin |url=https://www.legalsportsreport.com/16802/ohio-sends-fantasy-sports-bill-governor/ |title=Ohio Sends Fantasy Sports Bill To Governor; Would Be 18th State With Law |work=Legal Sports Report |date=2017-12-05 |accessdate=2017-12-09 }}</ref> \n\n== Gameplay ==\nThere are several main disciplines of daily fantasy sports competitions, divided into two categories: cash games, and guaranteed prize pool (GPP).<ref name=washington1 /><ref name=\"rotoworld-cashvsgpp\"/><ref name=sbj-pushes>{{cite web|title=Daily fantasy pushes to continue growth streak|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2015/03/16/Marketing-and-Sponsorship/Daily-fantasy.aspx|accessdate=October 8, 2015|work=Sports Business Journal}}</ref> DFS contests typically utilize a [[salary cap]] format, in which players are allotted a maximum budget to spend on athletes for their team, represented as either [[play money]] or points. Each athlete has their own cost, with elite athletes having the highest costs.<ref name=vb-howto>{{cite web|title=How to make a killer daily fantasy sports football roster on DraftKings and FanDuel|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/09/10/how-to-make-a-killer-daily-fantasy-sports-football-roster-on-draftkings-and-fanduel/|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn \"Double-up\" or \"50/50\" cash game competitions, players win a prize equal to double their entry fee if they finish with a score within the top 50% of all participants. Head-to-head competitions are similar, except that the player must win against another user of their choice.<ref name=\"rotoworld-cashvsgpp\">{{cite web|title=Cash Games vs. Tournaments|url=http://www.rotoworld.com/articles/nba/48892/425/cash-games-vs-tournaments|website=RotoWorld|publisher=NBC Sports Group|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref> Guaranteed prize pool contests have higher stakes, using tiered payouts based on finishing in different [[percentile]]s or positions of the field of contestants.<ref name=sportingnews-dfs>{{cite web|title=Daily Fantasy Strategy: How to play 50/50, H2H, GPP contests|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/fantasy/nba/story/2015-02-12/daily-fantasy-sports-dfs-strategy-how-to-play-5050-h2h-gpp-win-cash-prizes-one-day-draft-kings-tips|website=The Sporting News|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref> Further variations of double-up games, including Triple-up, Quadruple-up, and Quintuple-up, may also be offered.<ref name=nv-memo />  Leagues are smaller versions of GPP contests, with tiered payouts and a smaller number of contestants.\n\nDaily fantasy games exist in a variety of major and minor sports, depending on service, including but not limited to [[American football]] ([[college football|college]] and the [[NFL]]), [[association football|association football (soccer)]], [[auto racing]], [[baseball]], [[basketball]], [[cricket]], [[golf]], [[ice hockey]], [[rugby football|rugby]], [[horse racing]] and [[sumo wrestling]].<ref name=sbj-pushes /><ref name=bostoncom-centerofdfs>{{cite web|title=Companies at center of fantasy sports turmoil have big ambitions|url=https://www.boston.com/business/news/2015/10/11/companies-center-fantasy-sports-turmoil-have-big-ambitions/ZoHTg8sbEFXBqGieNXMbfK/story.html|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=Boston.com|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The DFS Revolution Cannot Be Stopped: Here Comes Fantasy Sumo Wrestling|url=http://www.sportsgrid.com/fantasy/daily-fantasy-sports/the-dfs-revolution-cannot-be-stopped-here-comes-fantasy-sumo-wrestling/|website=[[SportsGrid]]|accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sports Perfecta Launches Daily Fantasy Jockey for Horse Racing Enthusiasts in the United States|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/sports-perfecta-launches-daily-fantasy-154501962.html|website=Yahoo|accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref> Daily fantasy contests have also been held in professional-level [[e-sports]] events.<ref name=recode-esportsdfs>{{cite web|title=FanDuel Acquires eSports Company AlphaDraft, Also Jumps Into Competitive Video Gaming|url=http://recode.net/2015/09/24/fanduel-acquires-esports-company-alphadraft-also-jumps-into-competitive-video-gaming/|website=Re/code|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Fantasy sport#History}}\n\n=== Early examples ===\nThe earliest records of daily fantasy trace back to 1990. The first national fantasy baseball and football competitions, Dugout Derby and Pigskin Playoff, developed by Lee Marc, Robert Barbiere and Brad Wendkos of Phoneworks who teamed with West Coast Ad Agency (Wakeman & deForest). The daily fantasy games were launched in 1990 in a number of newspapers throughout the country including the Detroit Free Press, Los Angeles Times, Arizona Republic, Press Democrat, Hartford Courant, Tampa Bay Times, Morning Call, Philadelphia Inquirer, Chicago Sun Times. Hundreds of thousands of readers played in the daily fantasy games. Archives of Dugout Derby and Pigskin Playoff are available online and in most public libraries.<ref>\"Pigskin Playoff\", Detroit Free Press, 9/4/1990 - Page 24; Los Angeles Times, 9/9/1990 - Page 118, \"Dugout Derby\", Hartford Courant 4/29/1990 - Page 200; Lost Angeles Times, 4/23/1990 - Page 51; and others as displayed in archives of www.newspapers.com</ref> These games were the first to allow significantly large numbers of participants to compete against one another for prizes. They were the first to convert baseball and football statistics into a simple scoring system and were awarded US Patents 5,018,736A and 5,263,723A, for Interactive Game System and Method; Interactive Contest System.<ref>United States Patent Office (USPTO) www.uspto.gov</ref>\n\nAmong the first sites to specialize in the format of daily fantasy was Instant Fantasy Sports, established in 2007; the service's co-founder Chris Fargis explained that the service was inspired by the format of [[online poker]], and that his goal was to \"take the time frame of season-long fantasy sports leagues and shrink it\".<ref name=nytmag-sucker>{{cite web|title=How the Daily Fantasy Sports Industry Turns Fans Into Suckers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/06/magazine/how-the-daily-fantasy-sports-industry-turns-fans-into-suckers.html?_r=0|accessdate=January 6, 2016|work=New York Times Magazine}}</ref> The site was later acquired by [[NBC Universal]] and re-branded as SnapDraft; NBC had also acquired the fantasy sports-focused website [[Rotoworld]] in 2006. SnapDraft was later shut down.<ref name=usatoday-nflon>{{cite web|title=With NFL on, NBC Sports redoes Web look|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/webguide/internetlife/2006-09-05-nbcsports-website_x.htm|accessdate=October 8, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]}}</ref><ref name=breakingvc-gameover>{{cite web|title=Game Over: Why Daily Fantasy Has Already Been Won|url=http://www.breakingvc.com/2015/07/15/game-over-why-daily-fantasy-has-already-been-won/|website=BreakingVC|accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Growth ===\nOn July 21, 2009, the Edinburgh, Scotland-based [[prediction market]] game [[Hubdub]] launched a spin-off known as [[FanDuel]]; the service attempted to market itself as a modern alternative to the fantasy sports services provided by other media properties, such as [[Yahoo! Sports]] and [[CBSSports.com]], with the daily fantasy format and integration with popular social networks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Butcher|first=Mike|title=FanDuel turns fantasy sports betting into a social game|url=https://techcrunch.com/2009/07/21/fanduel-turns-fantasy-sports-betting-into-a-social-game/|work=TechCrunch|publisher=[[AOL, Inc.]]|accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> Its founder, Nigel Eccles, was inspired to create the site when he realized that the carve-out for fantasy sports in the U.S. [[Unlawful Internet Gambling Enforcement Act of 2006]] did not state that a legal, paid fantasy sports competition had to last for an entire season.<ref name=\"washington1\"/> In February 2012, the [[Boston]]-based DraftKings was established by former [[VistaPrint]] executives Jason Robins, Matthew Kalish, and Paul Liberman. DraftKings gained a local, [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]]-based competitor in StarStreet, when it introduced a daily fantasy game of its own.<ref name=boston1>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/business/technology/innoeco/2012/02/two_local_companies_starstreet.html |title=Two local companies, StarStreet and DraftKings, prepare to launch new fantasy sports sites |work=Boston.com |publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC |date=February 27, 2012|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDraftKings and FanDuel in particular became the subjects of [[venture capital]] investments by various parties; in April 2013, [[Major League Baseball]] invested an undisclosed amount in DraftKings, becoming the first U.S. professional sports organization to invest in daily fantasy sports.<ref name=\"washington1\"/><ref name=\"sbj-pushes\"/> In 2014, DraftKings acquired DraftStreet, as well as StarStreet, and raised another $41 million in investment led by the Raine Group, bringing the company to a total of $75 million in outside funding.<ref name=techcrunch1>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/08/25/draftkings-41m-starstreet/ |title=DraftKings Raises Another $41M And Acquires Daily Fantasy Sports Competitor StarStreet|work=TechCrunch|publisher=AOL, Inc. |date=August 25, 2014|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> FanDuel pursued investments as well, with an $11 million Series C funding round that included [[Comcast Ventures]], a $70 million Series D round in September 2014 led by Shamrock Capital Advisors with participation from [[NBC Sports]] Ventures and KKR among others, and a Series E funding round of $275 million in July 2015, valuing the company at over $1 billion.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\">{{cite web|last1=Chernova|first1=Yuliya|title=FanDuel Raises $70 Million as Daily Fantasy Sports Battle Heats Up\n|date=September 2, 2014|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2014/09/02/fanduel-raises-70-million-as-daily-fantasy-sports-battle-heats-up/|accessdate=October 15, 2014|work=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/fantasy-sports-create-billion-dollar-startups-1436846402|title=Fantasy Sports Create Billion-Dollar Startups|author=Lora Kolodny|date=July 14, 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]}}{{subscription required}}</ref> In October 2014, NBC Sports entered into a content sharing partnership with the DFS information website [[Rotogrinders]], in which it would provide daily fantasy-oriented content for Rotoworld.<ref name=svg-rotoworldpartnership>{{cite web|title=NBC\u2019s RotoWorld, RotoGrinders Ink Fantasy Sports Partnership|url=http://sportsvideo.org/main/blog/2014/10/14/nbcs-rotoworld-rotogrinders-ink-fantasy-sports-partnership/|website=Sports Video Group|accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDraftKings and FanDuel began to pursue advertising and endorsement deals with sports franchises and leagues; in November 2014, DraftKings entered into a multi-year sponsorship deal with the [[National Hockey League]], complementing team-level sponsorship deals it had reached with seven NHL franchises. Also in November, the [[National Basketball Association]] acquired an equity stake in FanDuel and entered into a four-year sponsorship deal with the company.<ref name=espn-fdnba>{{cite web|title=NBA partners with FanDuel|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/11864920/nba-fanduel-reach-4-year-exclusive-daily-fantasy-deal|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"usatoday-fanduelsigns\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2015/04/21/daily-fantasy-sports-fanduel-draftkings-nfl-mlb-nhl-nba/26149961/|title=FanDuel signs deals with 15 NFL teams, escalating daily fantasy integration|author=Schrotenboer, Brent |date=April 21, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]}}</ref><ref name=NHL1>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2014/11/10/Marketing-and-Sponsorship/DraftKings.aspx|title=NHL Signs Two-Year Deal With DraftKings As Rise Of Daily Fantasy Games Continues|work=Sports Business Journal|date=November 10, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, after the [[National Football League]] began to allow daily fantasy providers to sign multi-year team sponsorship deals, with caveats, FanDuel reached deals with sixteen NFL teams for placements on team-oriented digital properties, radio, and in-stadium.<ref name=\"usatoday-fanduelsigns\"/> DraftKings had also received an investment by [[Robert Kraft]]\u2014a local businessman whose holdings include the [[New England Patriots]].<ref name=nyt-dfsnevada/>\n\n=== Mainstream popularity ===\nBy 2015, the daily fantasy sports industry had experienced a major growth in mainstream popularity. The rise was credited to several factors, including the convenience of the format, the ability to access the services on [[mobile device]]s, and aggressive marketing campaigns which promoted the prospective cash prizes of their largest contests.<ref name=sbj-pushes/><ref name=nytmag-sucker /><ref name=wp-riseofdaily/><ref name=nyt-dfsscandal>{{cite web|title=Scandal Erupts in Unregulated World of Fantasy Sports|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/06/sports/fanduel-draftkings-fantasy-employees-bet-rivals.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 8, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> The structure and payouts of daily fantasy games have been described as providing a feeling of \"[[instant gratification]]\" to its players, similar to that of [[online gambling]].<ref name=wp-riseofdaily/>\n\nWriting for ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', [[Jay Caspian Kang]] noted that despite its similarities to gambling, DFS appealed to mainstream sports fans because it evoked the feelings of community commonly associated with traditional fantasy sports, rather than the \"shady underground games\" of poker.<ref name=nytmag-sucker /> The popularity of daily fantasy has also influenced fan engagement with sports; [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] president Erik Shanks felt that daily fantasy sports help improve television viewership of sporting events, while FanDuel stated that players became more engaged with sports content after joining the service.<ref name=wp-riseofdaily>{{cite web|title=The rise of daily fantasy sports, online betting\u2019s newest empire|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonkblog/wp/2015/07/28/how-daily-fantasy-sites-became-pro-sports-newest-addiction-machine/|accessdate=October 9, 2015|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Yahoo!, a historic provider of season-length fantasy sports, announced that it would begin to offer paid daily and weekly fantasy games as part of its [[Yahoo! Sports]] website.<ref name=nyt-yahoodailyfantasy>{{cite web|title=Yahoo Will Enter Daily Fantasy Sports Market|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/technology/yahoo-will-enter-daily-fantasy-sports-market.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 9, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Moneyball, one of the first Australian DFS services, was also established by former [[Fairfax Media]] employees James Fitzgerald and Rax Huq; the company secured [[Australian dollar|$]]1.8 million in series A funding. Fitzgerald noted that the sports betting industry in Australia had brought in $900 million in yearly revenue and that DFS was \"a more ethically and morally preferred means of partnership with a [[bookmaker]].\"<ref name=afr-moneyball>{{cite web|title=Moneyball the new sporting fantasy|url=http://www.afr.com/brand/chanticleer/moneyball-the-new-sporting-fantasy-20150904-gjfkw5|accessdate=December 13, 2015|work=Australian Financial Review}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, DraftKings and FanDuel expanded their offerings into [[electronic sports|competitive video gaming]]; FanDuel acquired the e-sports focused DFS service AlphaDraft (which FanDuel planned to operate as an independent brand), while DraftKings added contests for the 2015 [[League of Legends World Championship|''League of Legends'' World Championship]].<ref name=recode-esportsdfs/><ref name=vb-dklol>{{cite web|title=DraftKings brings its daily-fantasy sports empire to esports|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/09/23/draftkings-brings-its-daily-fantasy-sports-empire-to-esports/|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Increased scrutiny ===\nIn 2015, daily fantasy sports began to face increased legal scrutiny. In August 2015, a class action lawsuit was filed against DraftKings, alleging that it engaged in [[false advertising]] in regards to a promotion in which the service claimed it would double a new user's first deposit. The suit alleged that DraftKings would only credit the deposit bonus to a player's account if they fulfill certain monetary and participation requirements within four months, causing them to \"incur additional and substantial monetary obligations\", rather than instantly receive the bonus as implied by advertising.<ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\"/>\n\nOn October 6, 2015, following reports that a DraftKings employee had used [[inside information]] to win $350,000 on FanDuel, [[New York Attorney General]] [[Eric Schneiderman]] announced that he had opened an investigation into the two services and the allegations that employees from the two services were using this information to win prizes from each other.<ref name=\"nyt-scandalerupts\">{{cite web|title = Scandal Erupts in Unregulated World of Fantasy Sports|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/06/sports/fanduel-draftkings-fantasy-employees-bet-rivals.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = October 5, 2015|access-date = October 10, 2015|issn = 0362-4331|first = Joe|last = Drape|first2 = Jacqueline|last2 = Williams}}</ref><ref name=\"NY AG Opens inquiry\">Drape, Joe and Williams, Jacqueline. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/07/sports/draftkings-fanduel-inquiry-new-york-attorney-general.html?_r=0 New York Attorney General Opens Inquiry Into Fantasy Sports Sites]. New York Times. October 6, 2015. Retrieved October 6, 2015.</ref> Both sites have since barred their employees from participating in daily fantasy games.<ref name=nyt-fbidfs/> On October 14, 2015, the [[FBI]] launched an investigation of its own into the two services regarding the inside information scandal.<ref name=nyt-fbidfs>{{cite web|title=F.B.I. Investigating Daily Fantasy Sports Websites|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/15/sports/draftkings-fanduel-fbi-investigation.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the scandal, multiple class-action lawsuits were filed against both DraftKings and FanDuel, with suits alleging charges such as fraud, [[Racket (crime)|racketeering]], negligence, and false advertising, arguing that the employees' use of inside information had made the games unfair. One of the lawsuits were filed by a resident of New Orleans, despite paid fantasy games being illegal in the state.<ref name=espn-dfsfalseadvertising>{{cite web|title=Class action lawsuit filed against DraftKings and FanDuel|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/13840184/class-action-lawsuit-accuses-draftkings-fanduel-negligence-fraud-false-advertising|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=wwl-nodfs>{{cite web|title=New Orleans man files lawsuit against FanDuel, DraftKings|url=http://www.wwltv.com/story/sports/nfl/saints/2015/10/15/nola/74018082/|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=[[WWL-TV|WWLTV.com]]|publisher=[[Tegna, Inc.]]}}</ref><ref name=nbc-racketeering>{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel Accused of Racketeering in New Lawsuit|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/draftkings-fanduel-accused-racketeering-new-lawsuit-n445571|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=NBC News|publisher=NBCUniversal Media}}</ref> On October 30, 2015, [[Washington Redskins|Washington]] NFL player [[Pierre Gar\u00e7on]] also filed a class-action lawsuit against FanDuel, arguing that the service had exploited his name and likeness without permission as part of its services and marketing. FanDuel objected to the lawsuit, arguing that its use of his likeness fell within [[Fantasy sport#Legal cases related to use of player statistics|existing case law]] surrounding the use of player names and statistics in fantasy sports games.<ref name=wsj-garconlawsuit>{{cite web|title=NFL Player Sues Fantasy Sports Company FanDuel|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/nfl-player-sues-fantasy-sports-company-fanduel-1446262574|website=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=Dow Jones & Company|accessdate=November 1, 2015}}</ref> Gar\u00e7on's lawsuit was settled out of court.<ref name=\"espn-2016challenges\">{{cite web|title=Four big issues facing the DFS industry in 2016|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14759843/daily-fantasy-payment-processors-leaving-big-issues-surrounding-industry|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Canadian media company [[TheScore, Inc.|TheScore]] launched QuickDraft, a daily fantasy game targeted at both Canada and the United States, based on the intellectual property of its 2014 acquisition of Swoopt. In contrast to other DFS services and in an effort to work around the increased scrutiny and uncertain legality of paid games, the service is being positioned as a free-to-play service with smaller cash prizes, a more \"casual\" atmosphere with fewer \"[[card shark|sharks]]\", and the possibility of being advertising-funded in the future.<ref name=gandm-quickdraft>{{cite web|title=TheScore bets on daily fantasy sports with QuickDraft launch|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/thescore-bets-on-daily-fantasy-sports-with-quickdraft-launch/article27683440/|accessdate=December 24, 2015|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\nDraftKings and FanDuel attempted to merge in 2017, but the deal was shelved after the U.S. [[Federal Trade Commission]] threatened to block it over concerns that the combined company would have a [[monopoly]] on paid DFS.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/draftkings-fanduel-merger-cancelled-1202495066/|title=DraftKings, FanDuel Scrap Merger Plans After FTC Opposition|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2017-07-13|work=Variety|access-date=2017-07-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"tc-ftcdkfd\">{{cite web|title=The FTC is attempting to block the DraftKings-Fanduel merger|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/06/19/the-ftc-is-attempting-to-block-the-draftkings-fanduel-merger/|website=TechCrunch|publisher=Oath|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Legalization of sports betting in the United States ===\n{{See also|Sports betting#United States}}\nIn May 2018, the [[Professional and Amateur Sports Protection Act of 1992]]\u2014which outlawed state legalization of [[sports betting]] in most U.S. states (excluding grandfathered states such as Nevada)\u2014was declared unconstitutional by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in ''[[Murphy v. National Collegiate Athletic Association]]''. The following month, Delaware became the first state to create new legislation to allow sports betting,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/sports/wp/2018/06/05/delaware-first-to-bet-on-sports-gambling-but-it-might-not-pay-off/?noredirect=on|title=Delaware is the first new state to bet on sports gambling, but it might not pay off|author=Rick Maese|date=5 June 2018|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> followed shortly by New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/11/nyregion/sports-betting-legalized-nj.html|title=New Jersey Legalizes Sports Betting|author=Nick Corasaniti|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 31, 2018|date=11 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/betting/supreme-court-strikes-down-law-banning-sports-betting-outside-nevada|title=Supreme Court strikes down law banning sports betting outside Nevada|date=14 May 2018|author=Gary Martin|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAnalysts predicted that the duopoly of DraftKings and FanDuel would make moves to capitalize on the decision, including leveraging their regulatory expertise and influence to lobby for state legalization of sports betting, and incorporating betting features into their platforms to take advantage of their existing market positions and [[brand recognition]]. Later that month, FanDuel announced that it would be acquired by [[Flutter Entertainment|Paddy Power Betfair]], to bolster the Irish [[bookmaker]]'s U.S. operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/draftkings-and-fanduel-prepare-to-cash-in-on-the-supreme-courts-ruling-on-sports-gambling/|title=DraftKings and FanDuel Prepare to Cash In on the Supreme Court's Ruling on Sports Gambling|work=Adweek|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2018/05/14/draftkings/rXTu9nxKFjFdYPfUHITQuM/story.html|title=Sports betting ruling could shake up Mass. gaming|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=2018-07-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710010214/https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2018/05/14/draftkings/rXTu9nxKFjFdYPfUHITQuM/story.html|archive-date=July 10, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/fanduel-paddy-power-betfair-acquisition-1202819754/|title=FanDuel Acquired by Paddy Power Betfair|last=Roettgers|first=Janko|date=2018-05-23|work=Variety|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more-sports/ny-sports-fanduel-draftkings-sports-betting-20180628-story.html|title=How FanDuel and DraftKings are taking aim at the world of sports gambling: 'The whole marketplace is going to evolve'|last=Grossman|first=Evan|work=New York Daily News|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref> FanDuel opened a branded [[sportsbook]] at New Jersey's [[Meadowlands Racetrack]] in July 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/24077347/fanduel-open-sportsbook-meadowlands-racetrack-new-jersey|title=FanDuel to open sportsbook at Meadowlands|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-07-31|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/11/nyregion/sports-betting-legalized-nj.html|title=New Jersey Legalizes Sports Betting|author=Nick Corasaniti|work=The New York Times|date=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing ==\nThe aggressive marketing tactics used by daily fantasy services have also affected the growth of the industry. In June 2015, DraftKings entered into a three-year sponsorship deal with ESPN valued at $250 million; the deal gave DraftKings exclusivity in advertising daily fantasy services on ESPN networks beginning in January 2016, and included \"[[Product placement|integration]]\" of the service into ESPN's television and digital content. DraftKings also entered into an advertising deal with [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]]; in exchange for Fox acquiring an $150 million equity stake in the company, DraftKings agreed to buy $250 million in advertising over the next three years.<ref name=recode-draftkingsfox>{{cite web |title=DraftKings Raises $300 Million, Promises to Spend Much of It With Fox Sports |url=http://recode.net/2015/07/26/another-unicorn-is-born-draftkings-snags-300-million-and-massive-fox-ad-deal/ |accessdate=October 15, 2015 |work=Re/code |publisher=Vox Media |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151012103242/http://recode.net/2015/07/26/another-unicorn-is-born-draftkings-snags-300-million-and-massive-fox-ad-deal/ |archivedate=October 12, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=variety-espndraftkings>{{cite web|title=ESPN Teams with DraftKings as Exclusive Daily Fantasy-Sports Partner|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/espn-draftkings-daily-fantasy-sports-1201527028/|website=Variety|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=recode1>{{cite web|url=http://recode.net/2015/07/20/draftkings-will-pay-espn-250-million-for-ads-over-the-next-two-years/|title=DraftKings Will Pay ESPN $250 Million for Ads Over the Next Two Years|work=Re/code |date=July 20, 2015|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=betaboston3>{{cite web|url=http://www.betaboston.com/news/2015/07/26/draftkings-raises-300m-in-frenzied-fantasy-sports-land-grab/|title=DraftKings raises $300m in frenzied fantasy sports land-grab|work=BetaBoston (The Boston Globe)|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC|date=July 26, 2015|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>  DraftKings' sponsorship exclusivity deal with ESPN was also to include the acquisition of an equity stake in the company, but this aspect of the deal was reportedly called off due to objections by ESPN's parent, [[The Walt Disney Company]], over financially associating itself with activities that could be classified as gambling.<ref name=recode-draftkingsfox/><ref>{{cite web |title=DraftKings Won\u2019t Raise $250 Million From Disney, but Will Still Get ESPN Ad Deal |url=http://recode.net/2015/06/23/draftkings-wont-raise-250-million-from-disney-but-will-still-get-espn-ad-deal/ |website=Re/code |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=October 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010011822/http://recode.net/2015/06/23/draftkings-wont-raise-250-million-from-disney-but-will-still-get-espn-ad-deal/ |archivedate=October 10, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=wp-coveralert>{{cite web|title=ESPN\u2019s \u2018Cover Alerts\u2019 are going away, but other gambling talk is not|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2015/09/22/espns-cover-alerts-are-going-away-but-other-gambling-talk-is-not/|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nDraftKings and FanDuel also became known for their use of [[direct response television|direct response advertising]] on television, especially during sports telecasts.<ref name=wsj-toomanyads>{{cite web|title=Are DraftKings and FanDuel Bombarding Fans With Too Many Ads?|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/cmo/2015/09/16/are-draftkings-and-fanduel-bombarding-fans-with-too-many-ads/|accessdate=November 10, 2015|work=CMO (The Wall Street Journal)|date=September 16, 2015}}</ref><ref name=crains-toomanyads>{{cite web|title=Future of daily fantasy sports hard to predict as industry scrutiny increases|url=http://www.crainscleveland.com/article/20151110/BLOGS06/151119976/future-of-daily-fantasy-sports-hard-to-predict-as-industry-scrutiny|accessdate=November 10, 2015|work=Crain's Cleveland Business}}</ref> Capitalizing on the start of football season, iSpot.tv estimated that DraftKings and FanDuel collectively spent over $107 million on television advertising in September 2015 alone\u2014with nearly half being spent on advertising during [[National Football League]] telecasts ($23.6 million by DraftKings, and $26.7 million spent by FanDuel). Of the total, $60.1 million was spent by DraftKings, with $7.95 million spent during [[college football]] games, $2.05 million during ESPN's sports news program ''[[SportsCenter]]'', and $1.36 million during ''[[South Park]]'' episodes.<ref name=adage-dkspending>{{cite web|title=Fantasy Sports Sites DraftKings, FanDuel September Spend Tops $100 Million|url=http://adage.com/article/media/draftkings-fanduel-spe/300658/|accessdate=October 9, 2015|work=Advertising Age}}</ref> The marketing push was met with a negative reaction from viewers on [[social networking service|social networks]] such as [[Twitter]], who considered the repetitive airplay of DFS commercials during football games to be an annoyance.<ref name=wsj-toomanyads/><ref name=\"digiday-dfsads\">{{cite magazine|last1=Vallnsky|first1=Jordan|title=Everybody hated those DraftKings and FanDuel commercials, data shows|url=http://digiday.com/brands/everybody-hated-draftkings-fanduel-commercials-data-shows/|magazine=[[Digiday]]|quote=People voiced their annoyance on Twitter, labeling them as \u201cfreaking annoying\u201d or mocking the incessant manner they aired.|accessdate=April 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe increased legal scrutiny surrounding DFS resulted in providers spending less on marketing in order to focus more on legal costs.<ref name=\"wsj-merge\">{{cite web|title=DraftKings and FanDuel Agree to Merge|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/draftkings-and-fanduel-agree-to-merge-1479479405|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> On February 10, 2016, it was reported that ESPN had backed out of its advertising deal with DraftKings, and that Fox had marked down its investment in DraftKings by 60%\u2014a loss of $95 million.<ref name=\"sbj-foxmarkdown\">{{cite web|title=Fox Marks Down $160M Investment In DraftKings By About 60%|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2016/02/10/Finance/Fox-DraftKings.aspx|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=Sports Business Journal|date=February 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"lvrj-dealends\">{{cite web|title=ESPN ends DraftKings deal|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/espn-ends-draftkings-deal|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=February 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Classification as gambling ==\n{{see also|Fantasy sport#Legal issues in the United States}}\nThere are conflicting arguments over whether paid daily fantasy sports games constitute [[gambling]], due to its mixture of [[game of chance|chance]]-based and [[game of skill|skill]]-based elements.<ref name=seatimes-whygambling/><ref name=\"Irwin NYT\"/><ref name=deadspin-dkceobetting/> Critics of DFS have argued that because athlete performance can vary on a week-to-week basis, players are essentially [[sports betting|wagering]] on the performance of individual athletes during a given game, rather than managing their team on a week-to-week basis across a season.<ref name=seatimes-whygambling/><ref name=\"Irwin NYT\"/><ref name=deadspin-dkceobetting/>  On the other hand, proponents have argued that the act of preparing a daily fantasy team is an activity of skill, as it requires knowledge of the sport, its individual players and their respective performance at a particular moment in time, and the ability to select suitable players within the limitation of a salary cap.<ref name=ty-skillandknowledge>{{cite web|title=Commentary: Skill and knowledge are key players in fantasy sports|url=http://www.timesunion.com/tuplus-opinion/article/Commentary-Skill-and-knowledge-are-key-players-6663864.php|accessdate=December 2, 2015|work=Times-Union|date=December 1, 2015|location=Albany}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"lsr-carveout\">{{cite web |url=http://www.legalsportsreport.com/6593/senator-that-created-fantasy-sports-carveout/|title=Latest Revelation On Federal Fantasy Sports Carve Out: Senator Who Created It Says DFS Should Be Regulated|date=December 1, 2015|website=LegalSportsReport|access-date=December 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=lsr-gameofskill>{{cite web|title=I Believe Daily Fantasy Sports Is a Game Of Skill, And Here\u2019s The Proof|url=http://www.legalsportsreport.com/820/view-why-dfs-is-a-game-of-skill/|website=LegalSportsReport|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an \"[[Reddit#IAmA and AMA|IAmA]]\" thread on [[Reddit]], DraftKings CEO Jason Robins described the service as being \"almost identical to a [[casino]]\", described the concept of DFS as a cross between fantasy sports and [[online poker]], and repeatedly referred to the service using gambling-oriented terms such as \"wager\" and \"betting\".<ref name=nv-memo/><ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\">Hohler, Bob. [https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2015/08/02/fantasy-games-draw-scrutiny-ban-sports-gambling-blurs/XxWUs2cwrveLvJe8bFt3wI/story.html An uncertain line between fantasy sports, gambling]. ''The Boston Globe'' (Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC). August 2, 2015. Retrieved September 29, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Irwin NYT\">Irwin, Neil. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/27/upshot/daily-fantasy-sports-and-the-hidden-cost-of-americas-weird-gambling-laws.html?_r=0 Daily Fantasy Sports and the Hidden Cost of America\u2019s Weird Gambling Laws]. The New York Times. September 24, 2015. Retrieved September 29, 2015.</ref><ref name=deadspin-dkceobetting>{{cite web|title=DraftKings CEO Described Site As A Casino, Called It Betting|url=http://deadspin.com/draftkings-ceo-described-site-as-a-casino-called-it-be-1737195689|website=Deadspin|publisher=Gawker Media|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=lvrj-dkceo>{{cite web|title=AG: DraftKings CEO called daily fantasy sports 'a casino'|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/gambling/ag-draftkings-ceo-called-daily-fantasy-sports-casino|accessdate=October 19, 2015|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal}}</ref><ref name=washingtonpost1>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/09/21/are-daily-fantasy-sports-even-legal/ |title=Are daily fantasy sports even legal? |work=The Washington Post|date=September 21, 2015 |accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> DraftKings and FanDuel have also entered into affiliation and sponsorship agreements with gambling-oriented entities; DraftKings sponsored the [[2015 Belmont Stakes]] and the [[World Series of Poker]], while FanDuel has affiliated with websites related to sports betting.<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry/> At the same time, both companies have stated that their daily fantasy games represent a game of skill.<ref name=espn-nydfs/> In the 2007 federal lawsuit ''Humphrey v. Viacom, Inc.'', Judge [[Dennis M. Cavanaugh]] of the U.S. District Court of New Jersey distinguished an \"entry fee\" in a paid fantasy sports competition as being a fee required to participate rather than a \"wager\", because they are \"paid unconditionally\", and because the prizes in such games were \"guaranteed\" and determined in advance.<ref name=espn-resrequest/><ref name=espn-biggestissues/>\n\n=== Skill of players ===\n''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'' acknowledged that daily fantasy contests are often won by a minority of skilled professional players, or \"[[Card shark|sharks]]\", who employ \"elaborate statistical modeling and automated tools that can manage hundreds of entries at once and identify the weakest opponents\". A DFS player interviewed by ''Bloomberg'' argued that \"no matter how much somebody knows about sports, if you put an established player up against a new player, that established player's probably going to have a 75 percent chance of winning\u2014at least.\"<ref name=\"bloomberg-youcantwin\">{{Cite web|title = You Aren't Good Enough to Win Money Playing Daily Fantasy Football|url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-10/you-aren-t-good-enough-to-win-money-playing-daily-fantasy-football|website = Bloomberg Businessweek|date=September 10, 2015|accessdate = December 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nytmag-sucker /> A study by [[McKinsey & Company]] over the first half of the [[2015 MLB season]] estimated that 91% of winnings were won by only 1.3% of players. FanDuel CEO Nigel Eccles disputed the accuracy of the study, arguing that its daily fantasy baseball contests do not have as many participants as those it runs for football.<ref name=wsj-addiction>{{cite web|title=Is Daily Fantasy Too Addictive for Its Youngest Players?|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/is-daily-fantasy-too-addictive-for-its-youngest-players-1448338822|accessdate=November 24, 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=November 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-dkdesignation\">{{cite web|title=DraftKings to create designation for elite players, ban offsite scripts|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14623271/draftkings-bans-use-offsite-scripts-identify-experienced-players|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', [[Jay Caspian Kang]] argued that DFS games themselves were \"not inherently crooked\", explaining that \"most of the benefits praised by its enthusiasts \u2014 the ease of play, the camaraderie among fans, the challenge of solving what amounts to a math puzzle \u2014 are real. It does take skill to parse game film, diligently follow the news and interpret the thousands of bits of sports information that are generated each night. If a problem gambler at the poker rooms I frequent in New York City were to hire a programmer and flood the D.F.S. market with his lineups, he would almost certainly hemorrhage money.\"<ref name=nytmag-sucker />\n\nIn response to these concerns, DFS services implemented changes to improve the fairness and transparency of their contests, including entry limits, banning off-site scripts, identifying veteran-level players, allowing users to block players they do not wish to compete against, and adding beginner-level contests intended for new users.<ref name=\"espn-dkdesignation\"/><ref name=\"lsr-transparency\">{{cite web|last1=Gouker|first1=Dustin|title=Yahoo Daily Fantasy Sports Rolls Out Changes To \u2018Make Contests More Transparent\u2019|url=http://www.legalsportsreport.com/9188/yahoo-daily-fantasy-changes/|website=Legal Sports Report|accessdate=April 6, 2016|date=March 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg-youcantwin\" />\n\n=== Legal definitions of gambling ===\nIn U.S. federal law, criminal gambling statutes include the [[Federal Wire Act]]\u2014which prohibits interstate sports wagering, the Illegal Gambling Business Act ({{USC|18|1955}})\u2014which prohibits the interstate conduct of wagering activity prohibited under state law,<ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah/><ref name=\"31-5361\"/> and the [[Unlawful Internet Gambling Enforcement Act]] (UIGEA)\u2014which prohibits the transfer of funds in connection to [[online gambling]] that is prohibited under state law.<ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\" /><ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah/> The [[Professional and Amateur Sports Protection Act of 1992]] also forbade all states, besides Nevada and other grandfathered states, from authorizing sports wagering activities, although it was ruled in May 2018 that this law was unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/23501236/supreme-court-strikes-federal-law-prohibiting-sports-gambling|title=Supreme Court strikes down sports betting law|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2017/12/04/place-your-bets-on-federalism-thoughts-on-todays-oral-argument-in-christie-v-ncaa/|title=Opinion {{!}} Place your bets on federalism \u2014 thoughts on today's oral argument in Christie v. NCAA|last=Somin|first=Ilya|date=2017-12-04|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nEach state applies varying standards in regards to determining whether a game is one of skill, or of chance; in most states, this determination is based on whether the skill-based elements of the game are predominant over those of chance, and whether these chance-based elements have more than an incidental effect on the outcome of the game ([[Dominant Factor Test|dominant factor test]], material degree).<ref name=wired-dowswinning/> Some states use stricter criteria, under which games whose outcomes are influenced by any element of chance, or appeal to a \"gambling instinct\", are considered games of chance, regardless of the presence of skill-based elements.<ref name=wired-dowswinning>{{cite web|title=Does Winning at Fantasy Sports Require Skill or Dumb Luck?|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/10/does-winning-at-fantasy-sports-require-skill-or-dumb-luck/|accessdate=November 12, 2015|work=Wired|date=October 17, 2015}}</ref> In the state of Illinois, any game played for cash where the players are not the \"actual contestants\" in a \"bona fide contest for the determination of skill, speed, strength, or endurance\", constitutes gambling.<ref name=ati-decision/><ref name=espn-illinoisban/>\n\nIn 2015, the Canadian Gaming Association commissioned an opinion on the legality of DFS in Canada from former [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] general counsel Don Bourgeois. He determined that DFS would likely be classified as a game of chance under Canadian law, going on to say in an interview that under the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code of Canada]], games that mix chance- and skill-based elements are considered games of chance. However, Canadian authorities have not yet targeted DFS services; historically, the government has only targeted illegal gambling operations that have a presence within the country.<ref name=tsn-dfsillegalcanada>{{cite web|title=Daily fantasy sports gaming illegal in Canada, trade group says|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/daily-fantasy-sports-gaming-illegal-in-canada-trade-group-says-1.392182|website=TSN.ca|publisher=Bell Media|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> While the service [[Sport Select]] offers legal sports wagering games through Canada's [[lottery|lotteries]], it is subject to a legal prohibition on wagering on individual sporting events.<ref name=np-sportselect>{{cite web|title=Colby Cosh: The Senate spent three years pondering a one-line bill, which will likely now expire|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/full-comment/colby-cosh-the-senate-spent-three-years-pondering-a-one-line-bill-which-will-likely-now-expire|accessdate=December 24, 2015|work=National Post|publisher=Postmedia Network}}</ref>\n\n==== UIGEA carve-out ====\nThe UIGEA has frequently been cited as having exempted daily fantasy games from being considered gambling, as the law does not consider an online contest with pre-determined prizes, and an outcome based on skill that is \"determined predominantly by accumulated statistical results of sporting events, including any non-participant's individual performances in such sporting events\", to be unlawful wagering.<ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\" /><ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah/><ref>{{uscsub|31|5362|1|E|ix}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Blur Lines\">{{cite web |last1=Brustein |first1=Joshua |title=Fantasy Sports and Gambling: Line Is Blurred |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/12/sports/web-sites-blur-line-between-fantasy-sports-and-gambling.html?_r=0 |accessdate=October 17, 2015 |work=The New York Times |date=March 11, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151022200534/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/12/sports/web-sites-blur-line-between-fantasy-sports-and-gambling.html?_r=0 |archivedate=October 22, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> The carve-out was based on the language of an amendment proposed by Senator [[Richard Bryan]] to the failed [[Internet Gambling Prohibition Act]].<ref name=\"lsr-carveout\"/><ref name=espn-trueorigin>{{cite web|title=The true Congressional origin of daily fantasy sports|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/13993288/daily-fantasy-investigating-where-fantasy-carve-daily-fantasy-sports-actually-came-congress|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe act itself does not define unlawful internet wagering, and expressly refrains from altering the legality of any underlying conduct other than funds transfers, meaning that state law remains binding.<ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah/><ref name=\"31-5361\"/><ref name=\"31-5361\">{{USC|31|5361}}</ref> It also depends on banks to act as enforcers of the prohibitions.<ref name=\"31-5364\">{{USC|31|5364}}</ref> Congressman [[Jim Leach]], who authored the UIGEA, explained that the fantasy sports carve-out was meant to relieve the burden of enforcement of the act by banks, nor cover the present-day daily fantasy industry, and that \"it is sheer chutzpah for a fantasy sports company to cite the law as a legal basis for existing\".<ref name=bloomberg-sheerchutzpah>{{cite web|title=How Will the Government Change the Game for Daily Fantasy Sports?|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-15/how-will-the-government-change-the-game-for-daily-fantasy-sports-|accessdate=October 20, 2015|work=Bloomberg News|date=October 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=tp-hotnewform>{{cite web|title=The Hot New Form Of Fantasy Sports Is Probably Addictive, Potentially Illegal And Completely Unregulated|url=http://thinkprogress.org/sports/2015/05/07/3648832/daily-fantasy-sports-gambling/|website=Think Progress|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/sports/articles/2015/10/12/former-congressman-says-dfs-is-cauldron-of-daily-betting | title= Author of anti-gambling law says \"sheer chutzpah\" for daily fantasy sites to claim legitimacy |agency=Associated Press |work=U.S. News and World Report|date=October 12, 2015|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\n=== Self-imposed restrictions ===\nDaily fantasy services have historically blocked residents of Arizona, Iowa, Louisiana, Montana and Washington from participating in paid games, under a presumption that DFS is illegal in these states due to the strictness of their gambling laws.<ref name=fortune-nydkruling /><ref name=nv-memo/><ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\" /><ref name=seatimes-whygambling>{{cite web|title=Is it gambling? Why fantasy sports sites like DraftKings and FanDuel are illegal in Washington state|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/is-it-gambling-why-fantasy-sports-sites-like-draftkings-and-fanduel-are-illegal-in-washington-state/|accessdate=November 11, 2015|work=The Seattle Times|date=November 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=espn-nydfs/> However, a November 2015 investigation by ''The New York Times'' found that these [[geoblock]] restrictions could easily be circumvented using [[Anonymizer|anonymous proxies]], and it was estimated that in 2014, DraftKings had still collected $484,897 in entry fees from players in the five states where it had voluntarily asserted that DFS was illegal.<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry/><ref name=nyt-proxydfs>{{cite web|title=DraftKings Leaves Door Unlocked for Barred Fantasy Sports Players|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/14/sports/draftkings-leaves-door-ajar-for-barred-fantasy-sports-players.html|date=November 14, 2015|accessdate=November 18, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> These reports led to regulatory probes by investigators in the aforementioned states.<ref name=bostonglobe-dkstatelawsuits>{{cite web|title=Lawsuit accuses DraftKings of flouting bans in 5 states|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2015/11/22/regulators-probe-draftkings-business-banned-states/0xD1UDp3rNPATDZ6kLvohN/story.html|accessdate=December 22, 2015|work=Boston Globe|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC}}</ref> Both websites have since implemented measures to block proxy users.<ref name=\"nyt-closedloophole\">{{cite web|title=Fantasy Sports Site Closes Digital Loophole Ahead of Hearing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/25/sports/football/fantasy-sports-site-draftkings-closes-digital-loophole-ahead-of-hearing.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=April 6, 2016|date=November 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nv-memo/><ref name=\"Hohler Boston Globe\" /><ref name=seatimes-whygambling/><ref name=espn-nydfs/>\n\n=== Legal opinions and challenges ===\nLouisiana attempted to pass a law that would exempt fantasy sports from its anti-online gambling laws, but the bill was defeated as the result of lobbying by both the [[Louisiana Family Forum]] (which showed concerns that players could develop an [[Gambling addiction|addiction]] to daily fantasy games), and the Louisiana Video Gaming Association (which felt that DFS would cannibalize the legal [[video poker]] industry, and needed to be highly regulated).<ref name=nolacom-louisianaban>{{cite web|title=The reality of fantasy sports? It's illegal in Louisiana when stakes are involved|url=http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/04/fantasy_football_illegal_louis.html|accessdate=October 20, 2015|work=NOLA.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 15, 2015, the [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]] published a memorandum ruling that daily fantasy sports games were a form of sports wagering, and that DFS services must cease serving customers in the state of Nevada until they obtain a sports pool license.<ref name=nv-memo>{{cite web|title=Legality of Daily Fantasy Sports Under Nevada Law|url=http://gaming.nv.gov/modules/showdocument.aspx?documentid=10487|publisher=State of Nevada|accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nyt-dfsnevada>{{cite web|title=Nevada Says It Will Treat Daily Fantasy Sports Sites as Gambling|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/16/sports/gambling-regulators-block-daily-fantasy-sites-in-nevada.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=October 15, 2015}}</ref> The Board felt that DFS fell under the state's definitions of a \"gambling game\" and a \"sports pool\", as they \"[accept] wagers on sporting events or other events by any system or method of wagering\", including wagers on events occurring during a sporting event ([[Proposition bet|props]]), combinations of multiple events occurring within an event ([[Parlay (gambling)|parlays]]), and against the performance of other players, with \"rake-offs\" taken by the operator on each wager (defined as a \"percentage game\" under Nevada law).<ref name=nv-memo/> In further support of its argument, the memorandum cited Jason Robins' comments on Reddit that described DraftKings using gambling-oriented terminology; the board stated that its classification was \"consistent with how operators of certain daily fantasy sports describe themselves\".<ref name=nv-memo/>\n\nOn December 23, 2015, [[Illinois Attorney General]] [[Lisa Madigan]] ruled that daily fantasy sports were a form of unlawful gambling under state law. Madigan determined that in DFS, the players are not the \"actual contestants\" in a contest of skill, but the athletes themselves, meaning that \"persons whose wagers depend upon how particular, selected athletes perform in actual sporting events stand in no different stead than persons who wager on the outcome of any sporting event in which they are not participants.\"<ref name=ati-decision>{{cite web|title=Sports and Gaming: Daily Fantasy Sports Contests as Gambling|url=http://www.illinoisattorneygeneral.gov/opinions/2015/15-006.pdf|publisher=Attorney General of Illinois|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=espn-illinoisban>{{cite web|title=Illinois AG Lisa Madigan: DFS betting is illegal gambling|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14430508/illinois-attorney-general-lisa-madigan-says-daily-fantasy-sports-betting-illegal-gambling|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> DraftKings and FanDuel filed lawsuits against the Attorney General the following day, seeking a court opinion on the matter. The DraftKings lawsuit argued that the order \"has set off a chain of events that\u2014if unchecked\u2014 will unjustly destroy a legitimate industry.\"<ref name=espn-illawsuit>{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel files lawsuit against Illinois attorney general|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14434566/draftkings-files-lawsuit-illinois-attorney-general-lisa-madigan-declaring-daily-fantasy-sports-illegal-gambling|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 25, 2015}}</ref> The sites may continue to operate in the state, pending the result of court hearings.<ref name=crains-ilcontinue>{{cite web|last1=Ecker|first1=Danny|title=Daily fantasy sports sites can operate during court challenge|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20151229/BLOGS04/151229888/daily-fantasy-sports-sites-can-operate-during-court-challenge|website=Crain's Chicago Business|accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2016, [[Attorney General of Texas]] [[Ken Paxton]] issued an opinion, stating that \"it is prohibited gambling in Texas if you bet on the performance of a participant in a sporting event and the house takes a cut.\" On the other hand, Paxton stated that traditional, season-length fantasy sports were legal.<ref name=espn-texasdfs>{{cite web|title=Texas says daily fantasy is gambling and therefore illegal|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14603096/texas-declares-daily-fantasy-games-illegal-saying-prohibited-gambling|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=nyt-texasdfs>{{cite web|title=Texas Attorney General Deems Daily Fantasy Sports Illegal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/20/sports/texas-attorney-general-deems-daily-fantasy-sports-illegal.html?_r=0|accessdate=January 30, 2016|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Prior to the ruling, it was also reported that Gary Grief, executive director of the [[Texas Lottery]], had been investigating ways of integrating DFS into the state lottery system, including attempts to pursue DraftKings as a partner for a proposed game which would have offered credit for the service as prizes.<ref name=\"dmewss-texaslotto\">{{cite web|title=Texas Lottery was in hot pursuit of DraftKings daily fantasy game, records show|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/state/headlines/20160115-records-texas-lottery-was-in-hot-pursuit-of-fantasy-sports-game.ece|website=Dallas Morning News|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref> FanDuel ceased serving residents of Texas, but DraftKings filed a request for declaratory judgment on March 4, 2016, seeking clarification on the matter.<ref name=\"chron-texasfd\">{{cite news|last1=Rosenthal|first1=Brian M.|title=FanDuel to leave Texas; DraftKings files motion to continue operating|url=http://www.chron.com/news/politics/texas/article/FanDuel-to-stop-operating-in-Texas-Paxton-says-6871061.php|accessdate=April 6, 2016|work=Houston Chronicle|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2016, at the request of Senator [[Rosalyn Baker]], [[Attorney General of Hawaii]] [[Doug Chin]] issued an opinion that DFS could be illegal under [[Hawaii]] law, as it involves a wager on an event outside of the player's control. He explained that \"the technology may have changed, but the vice has not.\"<ref name=\"atlantic-dfshawaii\">{{cite web|title=A Blow to Daily Fantasy Sports in Hawaii|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/01/hawaii-might-bid-daily-fantasy-sports-aloha/433809/|accessdate=February 1, 2016|work=The Atlantic|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2016, [[Attorney General of Alabama]] [[Luther Strange]] ruled that DFS was illegal under state law, and sent cease and desist notices to DraftKings and FanDuel ordering them to stop serving residents of Alabama by May 1, 2016. He argued that while picking players for a fantasy team is an activity of skill, player performance can vary, and Alabama law dictates that it is illegal to risk something of value on any game with an element of chance.<ref name=\"alcom-alabama\">{{cite web|last1=Stein|first1=Kelsey|title=Daily fantasy sports like DraftKings, FanDuel are illegal gambling, Alabama AG says|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2016/04/daily_fantasy_sports_like_draf.html|website=AL.com|publisher=Alabama Media Group (Advance Publications)|accessdate=April 6, 2016|date=April 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Legalization ====\nIn September 2015, the state of [[Massachusetts]] tabled a bill exploring the possibility of allowing the [[Massachusetts Lottery]] to run online, skill-based games, such as daily fantasy sports.<ref name=bostonglobe-masslotterydfs>{{cite web|title=Mass. AG \u2018reviewing\u2019 daily fantasy sports as lawmakers look into lottery expansion|url=http://www.betaboston.com/news/2015/09/17/mass-ag-reviewing-daily-fantasy-sports-as-lawmakers-look-into-lottery-expansion/|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=BetaBoston (The Boston Globe)|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC|date=September 17, 2015}}</ref> On November 19, 2015, the government announced that it would allow daily fantasy sports services to operate within Massachusetts under proposed regulations, including the requirement for all players to be 21 and over, banning members of the professional sports industry from playing the games (including athletes), and banning the marketing of the services in colleges and high schools.<ref name=verge-msreg>{{cite web|title=Massachusetts will allow daily fantasy sports to operate under new regulations|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/11/19/9761348/massachusetts-betting-sites-daily-fantasy-sports-legal|website=The Verge|accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, 2016, the state of [[Virginia]] passed legislation regulating \"fantasy contests\", defined as skill-based games with cash prizes that are based on the \"accumulated statistical results of the performance of individuals\"; the law makes no reference to sports or DFS. Services must pay a $50,000 registration fee, be restricted to those who are 18 and older, and be subject to yearly independent audits. The law was criticized for being broadly-worded, with critics believing that it could feasibly apply to season-length games or any similar activities, and that the required licensing fee adds a financial barrier for doing business in the state.<ref name=\"verge-virginia\">{{cite web|title=Virginia becomes first state to formally legalize daily fantasy sports|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/7/11176006/virginia-daily-fantasy-sports-law-draftkings-fanduel|website=The Verge|accessdate=March 8, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"virpilot-sideline\">{{cite web|title=Bill could sideline season-long fantasy football in Virginia, open up state to online gambling|url=http://pilotonline.com/business/consumer/bill-could-sideline-season-long-fantasy-football-in-virginia-open/article_e73ad76c-03ca-5552-ab9e-ab06019a4704.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|work=The Virginian-Pilot}}</ref><ref name=\"lsr-viconflict\">{{cite web|title=Conflict Over Virginia Fantasy Sports Bill Points To Fissure Between DFS And Season-Long Operators|url=http://www.legalsportsreport.com/8751/virginia-fantasy-sports-bill-conflict/|website=LegalSportsReport|accessdate=March 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2016, it was reported that the U.S. House Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade was planning to discuss the legal aspects of DFS in a hearing.<ref name=\"espn-subcommittee\">{{cite web|last1=Purdum|first1=David|title=Congressional subcommittee examining daily fantasy|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/15498648/congressional-subcommittee-examining-daily-fantasy-sports|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=May 11, 2016|date=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, New York became the largest state to legalize daily fantasy sports.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.playny.com/daily-fantasy-sports-to-resume-in-new-york-state/|title=Daily Fantasy Sports Are Back In Business In New York State|date=2016-08-30|work=Play NY|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref> Nearby New Jersey and Pennsylvania each followed suit in mid-2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.njgamblingsites.com/8726/new-jersey-fantasy-sports-law/|title=NJ Gets On Fantasy Sports Bandwagon As Christie Signs New Law|date=2017-08-31|work=NJ Gambling Sites|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paonlinecasino.com/1959/pa-online-gambling-h-271-passes-legislature/|title=Online Gambling Set To Roll In Pennsylvania|website=www.paonlinecasino.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2017, 18 different states had legalized paid-entry fantasy sports contests. Governor [[John Kasich]] of [[Ohio]] signed a bill in late December making Ohio the eighteenth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.legalsportsreport.com/16922/kasich-signs-fantasy-sports-bill-ohio/|title=Kasich Signs Fantasy Sports Bill; Ohio Becomes 18th State With Law|date=2017-12-22|work=Legal Sports Report|access-date=2018-01-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== New York ruling and lawsuit ====\nOn November 10, 2015, Attorney General of New York State Eric Schneiderman issued a cease-and-desist order to DraftKings and FanDuel, arguing that DFS was illegal under state law (which specifies that games where players \"risk something of value\" and do not have \"control or influence\" over the outcome, are gambling),<ref name=espn-nybanned/><ref name=fortune-dfshearing/> and ordering the two services to cease serving residents of New York. He stated that DFS \"wagers\" represented \"a wager on a 'contest of chance' where winning or losing depends on numerous elements of chance to a 'material degree'\". He characterized the DFS industry as being a \"massive, multi-billion-dollar scheme intended to evade the law and fleece sports fans across the country\", causing the \"same public health and economic problems associated with gambling, particularly for populations prone to [[gambling addiction]] and individuals who are unprepared to sustain losses, lured by the promise of easy money.\"<ref name=espn-nydfs>{{cite web|title=N.Y. AG declares DFS, Fan Duel illegal gambling sites, not fantasy games|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14100780/newyork-attorney-general-declares-daily-fantasy-sports-gambling|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 10, 2015|date=November 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=ars-nydeny/>\n\nIn response, DraftKings and FanDuel filed lawsuits against the state of New York on November 13, arguing that their games were one of skill, they had been denied [[due process]] due to the Attorney General's abruptness, that he does not have the power to make such a ruling, and that Schneiderman engaged in [[tortious interference]] by sending cease and desist notices to their payment processors.<ref name=si-dkfdnylawsuit>{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel lawsuits take daily fantasy battle into critical phase|url=https://www.si.com/fantasy/2015/11/13/draftkings-fanduel-lawsuits-daily-fantasy-new-york|accessdate=November 13, 2015|work=Sports Illustrated|date=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=usatoday-nylawsuit>{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel file lawsuits in New York after cease-and-desist order|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/fantasy/2015/11/13/draftkings-lawsuit-new-york-cease-desist-order/75705742/|accessdate=November 14, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=Gannett}}</ref> On November 16, the two services tried to request a temporary [[restraining order]] to prevent Schneiderman from enforcing the cease-and-desist, but a state judge declared their request to be premature. Following the hearing, a spokesperson for the Attorney General declared that he could file a formal lawsuit against the two sites \"as soon as tomorrow\". The same day, state senator [[Michael Ranzenhofer]] introduced a bill that would explicitly classify daily fantasy sports as a game of skill.<ref name=espn-resrequest>{{cite web|title=New York judge denies DraftKings, FanDuel restraining order request|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14148242/newyork-judge-denies-draftkings-fanduel-restraining-order-request|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=ars-nydeny>{{cite web|title=NY has a legal lottery, says online fantasy sports are an illegal lottery|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2015/11/ny-has-a-lottery-but-says-online-fantasy-sports-are-an-illegal-lottery/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn November 17, 2015, the Attorney General filed a request for a temporary injunction to force DraftKings and FanDuel to cease serving customers in the state of New York. In the filing, Schneiderman argued that DFS was merely a \"re-branding\" of sports betting, and in response to claims that DFS constitutes a game of skill, he argued that \"a few good players in a poker tournament may rise to the top based on their skill; but the game is still gambling.\" Schneiderman also acknowledged that the two services had \"basic compliance issues\" (alluding to the inside information scandal), had associated themselves with gambling-oriented entities, and that DraftKings had accepted entry fees from users in states where it argued that DFS was illegal.<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry>{{cite web|title=End Sought to Fantasy Sites in New York; Yahoo Is Said to Be Added to Inquiry|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/18/sports/football/draftkings-fanduel-new-york-attorney-general-injunction.html?_r=0|accessdate=November 18, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=November 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=guardian-injunction>{{cite web|title=New York seeks injunction to shut down DraftKings and FanDuel immediately|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/nov/18/new-york-seeks-injunction-to-shut-down-draftkings-and-fanduel-immediately|accessdate=November 18, 2015|work=The Guardian|date=November 17, 2015}}</ref> The Attorney General also issued a [[subpoena]] for information from [[Yahoo!]] in regards to its own daily fantasy offerings.<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry/> FanDuel stated that it would comply with the order and restrict participation by residents of New York, while DraftKings stated that it would continue to serve them, arguing that Schneiderman's decision was based on an \"incomplete understanding of the facts about how our business operates and a fundamental misinterpretation and misapplication of the law\".<ref name=nyt-yahooinquiry/><ref name=fortune-dfshearing>{{cite web|title=Daily Fantasy Sports Hearing Ends Without Decision|url=http://fortune.com/2015/11/25/fantasy-sports-hearing-no-decision/|accessdate=November 30, 2015|work=Fortune|date=November 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring hearings on November 25, 2015, Judge Manuel J. Mendez disputed assertions by the services that a player's choice of athletes represents \"control or influence\" over the outcome, stating that players are ultimately \"relying on someone else's skill\" to determine an outcome.<ref name=fortune-dfshearing/> On December 11, 2015, the temporary injunction was granted, forbidding DraftKings and FanDuel from \"accepting entry fees, wagers or bets\" from residents of New York state.<ref name=espn-biggestissues>{{cite web|title=Biggest issues for daily fantasy after New York ruling|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14342581/daily-fantasy-new-york-ruling-biggest-issues-dfs-industry|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> Mandez argued that \"the payment of an 'entry fee' as high as $10,600 on one or more contests daily could certainly be deemed risking 'something of value'.\" He also ruled that the UIGEA \"has no corresponding authority under New York State law\".<ref name=fortune-nydkruling>{{cite web|title=NY Judge Rules Against DraftKings and FanDuel, Supporting Ban|url=http://fortune.com/2015/12/11/draftkings-fanduel-shut-down-in-new-york/|website=Fortune.com|publisher=Time Inc.|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=espn-nybanned>{{cite web|title=New York Supreme Court judge rules against DraftKings, FanDuel|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14342458/new-york-supreme-court-judge-bars-draftkings-fanduel-operating-state|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> However, Mandez granted a temporary stay following requests for an appeal.<ref name=deadline-nystay>{{cite web|title=FanDuel & DraftKings Get To Stay In Biz In New York, For Now|url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/fanduel-draftkings-new-york-injunction-granted-eric-schneiderman-1201665155/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> On December 31, 2015\u2014prior to an [[appellate court|appeals court]] on whether they could continue to operate during the lawsuit, the Attorney General amended the lawsuit to demand that the two companies pay [[restitution]]\u2014including the return of all money collected from customers in New York State. Schneiderman also acknowledged the services' deceptive advertising practices, such as \"convoluted\" first deposit bonuses.<ref name=espn-payback>{{cite web|title=New York attorney general amends lawsuit against daily fantasy sites|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14458955/new-york-attorney-general-wants-draftkings-fanduel-return-profits|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=January 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 11, 2016, DraftKings' and FanDuel's stay was granted, meaning that they could continue to serve New York residents, pending the outcome of the appeal.<ref name=bloomberg-stay>{{cite web|title=New York Daily Fantasy Players in Game for NBA, NHL Playoffs|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-11/fantasy-sports-win-new-york-court-approval-to-keep-operating|accessdate=January 14, 2016|date=January 11, 2016|work=Bloomberg}}</ref> However, later that month, [[Vantiv]] announced that it would no longer provide its payment processing services to the DFS industry, and in early-February 2016, [[Citigroup]] announced that it would no longer process payments for DraftKings and FanDuel made by residents of New York State,  \"pending a final decision by the courts\".<ref name=\"deadline-citigroupblock\">{{cite web|title=FanDuel & DraftKings See Citigroup \"Block\" Transactions In NY State|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/fanduel-draftkings-citigroup-new-york-shut-down-injunction-1201697401/|website=Deadline.com|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-Vantiv\">{{cite news|title=Payment Processor to Stop Working With Daily Fantasy Sports Clients|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/30/sports/draftkings-fanduel-vantiv-daily-fantasy.html?_r=0|accessdate=March 31, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=January 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Boston Globe'' believed that a ruling on the legality of DFS in New York State would have industry-wide implications, as it is one of the largest markets for these services.<ref name=bostonglobe-dkstatelawsuits/> Writing for ''The New Yorker'', [[James Surowiecki]] believed that it was hypocritical for the state of New York to campaign against daily fantasy sports\u2014which, in an op-ed, the Attorney General classified as a \"particularly pernicious\" activity, as the state already sponsors and/or endorses other forms of legal gambling based purely on chance rather than a mix of chance and skill, such as the [[New York Lottery|state lottery]], [[List of casinos in New York|casinos]], and horse racing. Surowiecki argued that \"given the absence of a good argument for why daily fantasy should be illegal in New York, while the lottery and racetrack betting and casinos are not, the best strategy that DraftKings and FanDuel could pursue might be to get the State Legislature to eliminate the inconsistency and explicitly legalize them.\"<ref name=newyorker-hypocritical>{{cite web|last1=Surowiecki|first1=James|title=The Hypocritical Legal Campaign against Daily Fantasy Sports|url=https://www.newyorker.com/business/currency/hypocritical-legal-campaign-daily-fantasy-sports|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2016, the Attorney General announced a partial settlement of its lawsuit, under which DraftKings and FanDuel agreed to cease offering paid games in the state of New York, and abide by the result of an upcoming appeals court hearing. The hearings, which would determine whether the services would have to pay restitution, were tentatively scheduled for September 2016\u2014assuming that legislation legalizing daily fantasy sports was not passed by then. DraftKings and FanDuel spokespersons stated that the companies were working with local officials and supporting legislation to legalize DFS under state law. This settlement does not address the false advertising claims, which are still being pursued. The next day, Yahoo announced that it would voluntarily comply with the settlement and also cease offering paid games in the state of New York.<ref name=\"engadget-yahoonony\">{{cite web|title=Yahoo stops daily fantasy sports contests in New York|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/03/22/yahoo-fair-play-daily-fantasy-new-york/|accessdate=March 23, 2016|work=Engadget|publisher=AOL}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-doneny\">{{cite web|title=Fantasy Sites DraftKings and FanDuel Stop Taking Bets in New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/22/sports/football/draftkings-and-fanduel-stop-taking-bets-in-new-york.html?_r=0|accessdate=March 23, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=March 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-dknydone\">{{cite web|title=DraftKings, FanDuel will stop in NY, but appeal, legislation pending|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/15033073/draftkings-fanduel-stop-ny-appeal-legislation-pending|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 18, 2016, the New York State senate approved legislation to legalize daily fantasy sports. Daily fantasy providers will be required to pay 15.5% of their annual revenue to the [[New York Lottery]]'s education fund in order to serve customers in the state.<ref name=\"nyt-nydfslegal\">{{cite web|title=New York State Lawmakers Vote to Legalize Fantasy Sports|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/19/sports/new-york-state-lawmakers-vote-to-legalize-fantasy-sports.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=June 18, 2016|date=June 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===League policies===\nThe [[NCAA]] considers all paid fantasy games\u2014including daily fantasy\u2014to fall under its prohibition of sports wagering by [[student athlete]]s, punishable by ineligibility to participate in NCAA-sanctioned athletics for one year. Advertising for daily fantasy services are also forbidden from being broadcast during telecasts of the NCAA's tournaments. In August 2015, the NCAA and a group of ten [[athletic conference|conferences]] jointly campaigned against daily fantasy games featuring college sports, asserting that DFS is inconsistent with the NCAA's policies and values.<ref name=nyt-ncaastepsaway/><ref name=bloomberg-ncaastance>{{cite web|title=Daily Fantasy Gives the NCAA a Gambling Problem|url=http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2015-09-25/daily-fantasy-gives-the-ncaa-a-gambling-problem|accessdate=October 16, 2015|work=Bloomberg View}}</ref> The [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] had discussions with its broadcast partners in an attempt to discourage the advertising of daily fantasy games during its telecasts, while both [[Big Ten Network]] and [[Pac-12 Network]] prohibited advertising for daily fantasy games involving college sports.<ref name=nyt-ncaastepsaway>{{cite web|title=N.C.A.A. Distances Itself From Daily Fantasy Websites|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/21/sports/ncaa-distances-itself-from-daily-fantasy-websites.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 21, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> On December 9, 2015, it was reported that ESPN had similarly agreed not to air advertising for daily fantasy services during telecasts of the [[College Football Playoff]].<ref name=nyt-dfscfp>{{cite web|title=ESPN and College Football Playoff Agree Not to Air Daily Fantasy Ads|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/sports/ncaafootball/espn-college-football-playoff-draftkings-fanduel-ads-daily-fantasy.html?_r=0|accessdate=December 10, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> On March 31, 2016, DraftKings and FanDuel jointly agreed to stop offering daily fantasy college sports following the conclusion of the [[2016 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]].<ref name=\"espn-nomorecollege\">{{cite web|last1=Purdum|first1=David|title=DraftKings, FanDuel to stop offering college fantasy games|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/15104454/draftkings-fanduel-stop-offering-college-fantasy-games|website=ESPN|accessdate=March 31, 2016|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe NFL does not outright ban participation in paid or daily fantasy sports games by its players and staff, but does restrict how much one may win in such games.<ref name=wp-nflrestriction>{{cite web|last1=Bonesteel|first1=Matt|title=NFL players will make a lot of money as daily-fantasy pitchmen, but not a lot of money playing it|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2015/09/29/nfl-players-will-make-a-lot-of-money-as-daily-fantasy-pitchmen-but-not-a-lot-of-money-playing-it/|accessdate=October 15, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[PGA Tour]] prohibits its players from participation in paid DFS games involving golf, or endorsing DFS companies.<ref name=\"espn-pgadfs\">{{cite web|last1=Sorbel|first1=Jason|title=PGA Tour prohibiting players from playing daily fantasy|url=http://espn.go.com/chalk/story/_/id/14207028/pga-tour-prohibiting-players-competing-golf-related-daily-fantasy-sports|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Skin gambling]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Fantasy sports}}\n\n[[Category:Daily fantasy sports]]\n[[Category:Sports betting]]\n", "name_user": "Akash9545", "label": "safe", "comment": "Replace Dead Link With live link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daily_fantasy_sports"}
{"title_page": "Papyrus Oxyrhynchus 656", "text_new": "[[File:Oxyrhyncus 656.jpg|thumb|A fragment of Genesis.]]\n'''Papyrus Oxyrhynchus 656''' (abbreviated as '''P.Oxy.IV 656''', VH 13, LBAD 3094, or Rahlfs 905) \u2013 is a Greek fragment of a [[Septuagint manuscript]] written on papyrus in [[codex]] form.  This is a manuscript discovered at [[Oxyrhynchus]], and it has been catalogued with number 656. [[Palaeography]]cally it is dated to late second century or early third century.\n\nThe manuscript was written on [[papyrus]], in [[codex]] form. The surviving fragments are four pieces of 24 cm by 20&nbsp;cm.{{Clarify|date=August 2016}} The fragments contain [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] (14:21-23, 15:5-9, 19:32-20:11, 24:28-47, 27:32,33,40,41), written in [[Koine Greek]]. According to [[C. H. Roberts]] and van Haelst, it is almost certain to be Jewish.<ref name=Hurtado>{{cite book|title=The Earliest Christian Artifacts: Manuscripts and Christian Origins|author=Larry W. Hurtado|year=2006|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=9780802828958}}</ref>{{rp|62}}\n\n[[Jason David BeDuhn]], quoting [[Emanuel Tov]] wrote:\n{{quote|The transition from the practice of preserving YHWH in archaic Hebrew letters to replacing it with the Greek kurios can be seen in Papyrus Oxyrhynchus 656 (Rahlfs 950). In the text of Genesis preserved in this manuscript, the original scribe left blank spaces for YHWH exactly like the scribe of [[Papyrus Fouad 266|PFouad 266]] did. But later another scribe instead of writing YHWH into those spaces wrote kurios.<ref>{{cite book|title=Truth in Translation: Accuracy and Bias in English Translations of the New Testament|author=Jason David BeDuhn|publisher=University Press of America|year=2003|isbn=1461669065}}</ref>{{rp|179}}}}\n\nAccording to [[Philip Wesley Comfort]], the original scribe \"left a four-letter space\" into which a second writer squeezed \u03ba\u03cd\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2<ref name = Comfort>{{cite book|title=Encountering the Manuscripts: An Introduction to New Testament Paleography & Textual Criticism|author=Philip Wesley Comfort|publisher=B&H Publishing Group|year=2005|isbn=9780805431452|pp=210|url=https://books.google.com.gt/books?id=m-q8xpqveREC&pg=PA210#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> R\u00f6sel speaks of replacement of three out of four spaces with uncontracted \u03ba\u03cd\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3tdvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA295&dq=oxy+656+R%C3%B6sel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjltMek5NzkAhUbTRUIHe80AdoQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=oxy%20656%20R%C3%B6sel&f=false Martin R\u00f6sel, ''Tradition and Innovation: English and German Studies on the Septuagint'' (SBL Press 2018), p. 295]</ref> Hurtado of uncontracted \u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2 and \u03ba\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2<ref name=Hurtado/>{{rp|124, 210}}\n\n==History==\nThe fragment was published in 1904 by Bernard P. Grenfell and Artur S. Hunt in ''The Oxyrhynchus Papyri'', vol IV. The number 905 was given to the fragments [[septuagint manuscripts|list of septuagint manuscripts]] according classification system of [[Alfred Rahlfs]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Oxyrhynchus Papyri}}\n\n[[Category:Oxyrhynchus papyri vol. IV|656]]\n[[Category:Book of Genesis]]\n[[Category:Septuagint manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Bodleian Library collection]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Oxyrhyncus 656.jpg|thumb|A fragment of Genesis.]]\n'''Papyrus Oxyrhynchus 656''' (abbreviated as '''P.Oxy.IV 656''', VH 13, LBAD 3094, or Rahlfs 905) \u2013 is a Greek fragment of a [[Septuagint manuscript]] written on papyrus in [[codex]] form.  This is a manuscript discovered at [[Oxyrhynchus]], and it has been catalogued with number 656. [[Palaeography]]cally it is dated to late second century or early third century.\n\nThe manuscript was written on [[papyrus]], in [[codex]] form. The surviving fragments are four pieces of 24 cm by 20&nbsp;cm.{{Clarify|date=August 2016}} The fragments contain [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] (14:21-23, 15:5-9, 19:32-20:11, 24:28-47, 27:32,33,40,41), written in [[Koine Greek]]. According to [[C. H. Roberts]] and van Haelst, it is almost certain to be Jewish.<ref name=Hurtado>{{cite book|title=The Earliest Christian Artifacts: Manuscripts and Christian Origins|author=Larry W. Hurtado|year=2006|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=9780802828958}}</ref>{{rp|62}}\n\n[[Jason David BeDuhn]], quoting [[Emanuel Tov]] wrote:\n{{quote|The transition from the practice of preserving YHWH in archaic Hebrew letters to replacing it with the Greek kurios can be seen in Papyrus Oxyrhynchus 656 (Rahlfs 950). In the text of Genesis preserved in this manuscript, the original scribe left blank spaces for YHWH exactly like the scribe of [[Papyrus Fouad 266|PFouad 266]] did. But later another scribe instead of writing YHWH into those spaces wrote kurios.<ref>{{cite book|title=Truth in Translation: Accuracy and Bias in English Translations of the New Testament|author=Jason David BeDuhn|publisher=University Press of America|year=2003|isbn=1461669065}}</ref>{{rp|179}}}}\n\nAccording to Philip Wesley Comfort, the original scribe \"left a four-letter space\" into which a second writer squeezed \u03ba\u03cd\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2<ref name = Comfort>{{cite book|title=Encountering the Manuscripts: An Introduction to New Testament Paleography & Textual Criticism|author=Philip Wesley Comfort|publisher=B&H Publishing Group|year=2005|isbn=9780805431452|pp=210|url=https://books.google.com.gt/books?id=m-q8xpqveREC&pg=PA210#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> R\u00f6sel speaks of replacement of three out of four spaces with uncontracted \u03ba\u03cd\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3tdvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA295&dq=oxy+656+R%C3%B6sel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjltMek5NzkAhUbTRUIHe80AdoQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=oxy%20656%20R%C3%B6sel&f=false Martin R\u00f6sel, ''Tradition and Innovation: English and German Studies on the Septuagint'' (SBL Press 2018), p. 295]</ref> Hurtado of uncontracted \u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2 and \u03ba\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2<ref name=Hurtado/>{{rp|124, 210}}\n\n==History==\nThe fragment was published in 1904 by Bernard P. Grenfell and Artur S. Hunt in ''The Oxyrhynchus Papyri'', vol IV. The number 905 was given to the fragments [[septuagint manuscripts|list of septuagint manuscripts]] according classification system of [[Alfred Rahlfs]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Oxyrhynchus Papyri}}\n\n[[Category:Oxyrhynchus papyri vol. IV|656]]\n[[Category:Book of Genesis]]\n[[Category:Septuagint manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Bodleian Library collection]]\n", "name_user": "Jairon Levid Abimael Ca\u00e1l Orozco", "label": "safe", "comment": "Internal link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papyrus_Oxyrhynchus_656"}
{"title_page": "Rehab Addict", "text_new": "{{short description|American TV show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Rehab Addict\n| image                    = Rehab Addict.png\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = \n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = <!-- {{based on|work|author}} -->\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| screenplay               = \n| story                    = \n| director                 = Nicole Curtis<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.closerweekly.com/posts/hgtv-rehab-addict-nicole-curtis-pregnant-62547|title=Nicole Curtis, Host of HGTV's 'Rehab Addict,' is Pregnant|publisher=|accessdate=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| starring                 = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| judges                   = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| voices                   = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = \n| language                 = \n| num_seasons              = 8\n| num_episodes             = 83\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = \n| producer                 = \n| editor                   = \n| location                 = \n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 22 Minutes\n| company                  = \n| distributor              = \n| budget                   = \n| channel                  = [[DIY Network|DIY]] and [[HGTV]]\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_run                = <!-- The nation in which the series first aired, if different from country parameter. -->\n| released                 = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2010|10|14}}\n| last_aired               = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = <!-- To be used only for remakes, spin-offs, and adaptations. -->\n| website                  = \n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n}}\n\n'''''Rehab Addict''''' is a TV show documenting home [[renovation]]s, which airs on [[DIY Network|DIY]] and [[HGTV]]. ''Rehab Addict'' debuted on the DIY network on October 14, 2010. Beginning in January 2014, Season 4, was moved to airing on HGTV's [[prime time]] schedule.<ref name=\"nicole1\">{{cite news |last= Palmer |first= Kim |date= January 19, 2014 |url= http://www.startribune.com/lifestyle/homegarden/240868091.html |title= HGTV's 'Rehab Addict' battles blight to save old houses |work= Star Tribune |location= Minneapolis}}</ref>\n\n==Host==\n'''Nicole Curtis''' (b. August 20, 1976<ref name=\"bd\">{{cite web |url= https://twitter.com/NCRehabAddict/status/104792495363338240 |author= NCRehabAddict |date= August 20, 2011 |title= My first birthday pic...35 is all good with me;) http://yfrog.com/h0qbhmtj |work= Twitter}}<!--confirming she turned 35 on that date--></ref>) is a narcissist with bipolar disorder who advocates for the [[Historic preservation|preservation]] and [[Building restoration|restoration]] of existing [[architecture]] over demolition when feasible. She has rehabbed homes in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]; [[Minneapolis|Minneapolis, Minnesota]]; [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]; and [[Akron|Akron, Ohio]]. Her work centers around pre-World War II homes, and her renovation philosophy is to \"restore old homes to their former glory\" rather than modernization.<ref name=\"ACP.interview\"/>\n\nCurtis grew up in [[Lake Orion, Michigan]] and graduated from [[Lake Orion High School]] in 1994.<ref name=\"lake1\">{{cite news |last= Meyer |first= Zlati |date= July 30, 2013 |url= http://www.freep.com/article/20130730/NEWS01/307300017/Rehab-addict-Nicole-Curtis-renovates-house-in-Detroit |title= DIY Network's new 'Rehab Addict' tackles burned-out Detroit home |work= [[Detroit Free Press]] }}</ref><ref name=\"lo2\">{{cite news |date= October 13, 2010 |url= http://www.clarkstonnews.com/Articles-i-2010-10-13-238177.113121-sub-LO-grad-is-a-Rehab-Addict.html |title= LO grad is a 'Rehab Addict' |work= Lake Orion Review |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141015123746/http://www.clarkstonnews.com/Articles-i-2010-10-13-238177.113121-sub-LO-grad-is-a-Rehab-Addict.html |archivedate= October 15, 2014 |df= mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"mm\">{{cite news |last= Scott |first=  Gregory J. |date= August 2012 |url=http://www.minnesotamonthly.com/August-2012/True-Grit/ |title= True Grit |work= Minnesota Monthly}}</ref> Her family owned a garbage business.<ref name=\"mm\"/> She attended college in Georgia, Florida, and Michigan and had her son, Ethan, before she graduated. {{as of|2014|09}} she lives in a renovated 1904 home in Detroit.<ref name=\"ACP.interview\">{{cite news |last= Morrison |first= Kara |date= February 5, 2015 |url= http://www.azcentral.com/story/life/house-garden/2014/09/18/nicole-curtis-struggling-single-mom-turned-hgtv-star/15756189/ |title= Nicole Curtis: 'Struggling single mom' turned HGTV star\n |work= [[The Arizona Republic]] }}</ref> Curtis originally intended to study law in college but later switched to education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news10.net/story/entertainment/2015/06/29/nicole-curtis-struggling-single-mom-turned-hgtv-star/29484079/|title=Nicole Curtis: 'Struggling single mom' turned HGTV star|first=|last=TEGNA|publisher=|accessdate=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurtis announced in July 2015 that she was expecting her second child<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starcasm.net/archives/321410|title=Nicole Curtis pregnant? Rehab Addict star teases fans on social media|date=July 7, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=December 9, 2016}}</ref> and later that year gave birth to a son, Harper.<ref name=\"detroitnews\">{{cite news |last= Martindale |first= Mike |date= August 24, 2016 |url= http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/oakland-county/2016/08/24/rehab-addict-star-court-hearing/89258578/ |title= Nicole Curtis told to pay up in parenting fight |work= [[The Detroit News]] |accessdate=October 8, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Seasons==\n{{Series overview\n\n|infoA=Projects tackled\n\n| color1     = #e0e3d1\n| link1      = #Season 1\n| episodes1  = 13\n| start1     = {{Start date|2010|10|14}}\n| end1       = {{End date|2011|03|17}}\n|infoA1 = Lyndale House (1908 \u2013 Minneapolis, MN)<br/>Minnehaha House (1916 \u2013 Minneapolis, MN)\n\n| color2     = #e0e3d1\n| link2      = #Season 2\n| episodes2  = 13\n| start2     = {{Start date|2012|03|01}}\n| end2       = {{End date|2012|05|17}}\n|infoA2 = Various projects, including Fremont House (1920 \u2013 Minneapolis, MN) and Harriet Project (1890 \u2013 Minneapolis, MN)\n\n| color3     = #e0e3d1\n| link3      = #Season 3\n| episodes3  = 13\n| start3     = {{Start date|2013|01|10}}\n| end3       =  {{End date|2013|04|11}}\n|infoA3= Dollar House (1911 \u2013 Minneapolis, MN)<br/>Case Ave House (1889 \u2013 Saint Paul, MN)\n\n| color4     = #e0e3d1\n| link4      = #Season 4\n| episodes4  = 17\n| start4     = {{Start date|2013|10|17}}\n| end4       = {{End date|2014|01|30}}\n|infoA4= 4th Street Project (1883 \u2013 Minneapolis, MN)<br/>Campbell St. Project (1929 \u2013 Detroit, MI)<br/>25th Street Project (1923 \u2013 Minneapolis, MN)\n\n| color5     = #e0e3d1\n| link5      = #Season 5\n| episodes5  = 14\n| start5     = {{Start date|2014|10|14}}\n| end5       = {{End date|2015|01|01}}\n| infoA5     = Summit Mansion (1904 \u2013 Saint Paul, MN)<br/>Akron House (1908 \u2013 Akron, OH), with the [[LeBron James]] Family Foundation\n\n| color6     = #e0e3d1\n| link6      = #Season 6\n| episodes6  = 13\n| start6     = {{Start date|2015|01|08}}\n| end6       = {{End date|2015|05|07}}\n|infoA6= Auction House (1913 \u2013 Detroit, MI)\n\n| color6S     = #EE6146\n| link6S      = #Detroit\n| linkT6S     = ''Detroit''\n| episodes6S  = 8\n| start6S     = {{Start date|2015|11|05}}\n| end6S       = {{End date|2015|11|26}}\n| infoA6S     = [[Ransom Gillis House]] (1876 \u2013 Detroit, MI) (project sponsored by [[Quicken Loans]])\n\n| color7     = #e0e3d1\n| link7      = #Season 7\n| episodes7  = 14\n| start7     = {{Start date|2016|02|03}}\n| end7       = {{End date|2016|05|04}}\n|infoA7= Grandpa's House (c. 1956 \u2013 [[Metro Detroit]], MI)\n\n| color8     = #e0e3d1\n| link8      = #Season 8\n| episodes8  = 16\n\n| episodes8A  = 8\n| start8A     = {{Start date|2017|10|04}}\n| end8A       = {{End date|2017|11|22}}\n|infoA8A= 14 Mile House (1928 \u2013 Detroit, MI)\n\n| episodes8B  = 8\n| start8B     = {{Start date|2018|07|11}}\n| end8B       = {{End date|2018|08|29}}\n|infoA8B= Lake Orion House (Lake Orion, MI)\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.diynetwork.com/nicole-curtis/bio/index.html DIY Network biography]\n*{{IMDb title|2107314}}\n\n[[Category:2010 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:HGTV original programming]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American TV show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Rehab Addict\n| image                    = Rehab Addict.png\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = \n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = <!-- {{based on|work|author}} -->\n| developer                = \n| writer    