254\n  |percentage = 42.4\n  }}\n{{Election box total no change\n  | votes = 316,971\n  | percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Books==\n* ''The Party's Over: How the Extreme Right Hijacked the GOP and I Became a Democrat'' (2014) {{ISBN|978-0525954415}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Florida}}\n* [[List of Arab and Middle-Eastern Americans in the United States Congress]]\n* [[List of American politicians who switched parties in office]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://crist.house.gov/ Congressman Charlie Crist] official U.S. House website\n* [https://charliecrist.com/ Charlie Crist for Congress] official campaign site\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Charlie_Crist_%5BD-13%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=C001111 | votesmart=24311 | fec=S6FL00160 | congress=charlie-crist/C001111 }}\n* {{C-SPAN|charlescrist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James W. Grant|Bill Grant]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]] from [[Florida]]<br />([[Classes of United States Senators|Class 3]])|years=[[United States Senate election in Florida, 1998|1998]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mel Martinez]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=David Bludworth}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Florida Attorney General|Attorney General of Florida]]|years=[[2002 Florida Attorney General election|2002]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bill McCollum]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeb Bush]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]|years=[[2006 Florida gubernatorial election|2006]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rick Scott]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alex Sink]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]|years=[[2014 Florida gubernatorial election|2014]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Gillum]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Gallagher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Florida Department of Education|Education Commissioner of Florida]]|years=2001\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=Jim Horne}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeb Bush]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]|years=2007\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rick Scott]]}}\n|-\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Richard E. Doran|Richard Doran]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Florida Attorney General|Attorney General of Florida]]|years=2003\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bill McCollum]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Jolly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[Florida's 13th congressional district]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lou Correa]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=298th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Val Demings]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FL-FedRep}}\n{{Current members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{U.S. Florida Representatives}}\n{{Governors of Florida}}\n{{RepNomFlGov}}\n{{DemNomFlGov}}\n{{third-party governors}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crist, Charlie}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Methodists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Methodists]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American people of Greek Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scotch-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:American United Methodists]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1998 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2010 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2014 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Cumberland School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Educators from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Florida Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:Florida Commissioners of Education]]\n[[Category:Florida Democrats]]\n[[Category:Florida Independents]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Florida state senators]]\n[[Category:Florida State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Florida]]\n[[Category:Independent state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Marco Rubio]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Florida]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Altoona, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Politicians from St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Seminole Caucus]]\n[[Category:St. Petersburg High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Wake Forest Demon Deacons football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician and attorney}}\n{{for|the basketball player|Charlie Criss}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Charlie Crist\n| image = Charlie Crist 115th Congress photo.jpg\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| district = {{ushr|FL|13|13th}}\n| term_start = January 3, 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[David Jolly]]\n| successor = \n| order1 = 44th [[List of governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]\n| lieutenant1 = [[Jeff Kottkamp]]\n| term_start1 = January 2, 2007\n| term_end1 = January 4, 2011\n| predecessor1 = [[Jeb Bush]]\n| successor1 = [[Rick Scott]]\n| office2 = 35th [[Attorney General of Florida]]\n| governor2 = Jeb Bush\n| term_start2 = January 7, 2003\n| term_end2 = January 2, 2007\n| predecessor2 = [[Richard E. Doran]]\n| successor2 = [[Bill McCollum]]\n| office3 = 21st [[Florida Department of Education|Education Commissioner of Florida]]\n| governor3 = Jeb Bush\n| term_start3 = January 3, 2001\n| term_end3 = January 7, 2003\n| predecessor3 = [[Tom Gallagher]]\n| successor3 = Jim Horne\n| state_senate4 = Florida\n| district4 = 20th\n| term_start4 = November 17, 1992\n| term_end4 = November 17, 1998\n| predecessor4 = Constituency redistricted\n| successor4 = [[Jim Sebesta]]\n| birth_name = Charles Joseph Crist, Jr.\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1956|07|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]], U.S\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (2012\u2013present)\n| otherparty = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (before 2010)<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (2010\u20132012)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Amanda Morrow|1979|1980|end=div}}<br />{{marriage|[[Carole Crist|Carole Rome]]|2008|2017|end=div}}\n| education = [[Wake Forest University]]<br />[[Florida State University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Samford University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| website = {{url|crist.house.gov|House website}}\n| signature = Charlie Crist Signature.svg\n}}\n'''Charles Joseph Crist Jr.''' ({{IPAc-en|k|r|\u026a|s|t}}; born July 24, 1956) is an American politician and lawyer who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from {{ushr|Florida|13}} since 2017. The district is based on [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]]. He served as the [[List of Governors of Florida|44th governor of Florida]] from 2007 to 2011.\n\nCrist began his political career as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], serving in the [[Florida Senate]] from 1993 to 1999, running unsuccessfully against incumbent [[Bob Graham]] for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in [[United States Senate election in Florida, 1998|1998]] and then serving as [[Florida Department of Education|Florida Education Commissioner]] from 2001 to 2003 and [[Florida Attorney General]] from 2003 to 2007, before being elected governor in [[2006 Florida gubernatorial election|2006]].\n\nCrist decided not to run for reelection as governor in [[2010 Florida gubernatorial election|2010]], announcing on May 12, 2009 that he was running for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by Republican Senator [[Mel Martinez]]. After initially leading in the race for the Republican nomination, he was overtaken in the polls by [[Marco Rubio]], and in April 2010 Crist left the Republican Party and ran as an [[Independent politician|independent]].<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">{{cite news |title=Crist Looks to Go It Alone |work=The Wall Street Journal |last=Wallsten |first=Peter; Bauerlein, Valerie |date=April 29, 2010 |url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052748704423504575212320310724084 |access-date=March 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710232733/https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052748704423504575212320310724084 |archive-date=July 10, 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In the [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2010|general election]] he lost to Rubio in a three-way race, taking 30% of the vote to Rubio's 49% and Democratic nominee [[Kendrick Meek]]'s 20%. Crist's term as governor ended in January 2011.\n\nOn December 7, 2012, Crist joined the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], having endorsed President [[Barack Obama]] for reelection in [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]].<ref name=\"changing\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/us/politics/charlie-crist-former-florida-governor-joins-democratic-party.html |title=Changing Affiliation Again, Former Governor of Florida Becomes a Democrat |agency=Associated Press |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 8, 2012 |accessdate=March 26, 2013}}</ref> On November 1, 2013, he announced that he was running for governor in the [[2014 Florida gubernatorial election|2014 election]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Associated Press|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/11/charlie-crist-democrat-florida-governor-race-99244.html|title=Ex-GOP Fla. Gov. Charlie Crist to run for job as Democrat|work=Politico |date=November 1, 2013 |accessdate=November 1, 2013}}</ref> He was defeated by incumbent Governor [[Rick Scott]], Crist's successor, by a 1% margin.<ref>http://enight.elections.myflorida.com/StateOffices/</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Adam C. Smith |author2=Steve Bousquet |author3=Katie Sanders |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/stateroundup/gov-rick-scott-leads-charlie-crist-in-early-returns/2205127|title=Florida Gov. Rick Scott defeats Charlie Crist for re-election |work=Tampa Bay Times|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref> In [[2016 United States House of Representatives elections|2016]], Crist was elected to Congress from his home district, the 13th, defeating incumbent [[David Jolly]], 52%-48%.<ref name=\"politicoresults\">[http://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/house/florida/ 2016 Florida House Election Results]</ref> Crist is currently the only former governor serving in the House.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCrist was born in [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]],<ref name=\"race\">{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sptimes/835232441.html?MAC=939a2bba9802553477e6bde045fe21f6&did=835232441&FMT=FT&FMTS=FT&date=May+9%2C+2005&author=LUCY+MORGAN&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&printformat=&desc=Crist+will+enter+governor%27s+race |title=Crist Will Enter Governor's Race |last=Morgan |first=Lucy |accessdate=January 12, 2007 |date=May 9, 2005 |work=St. Petersburg Times |pages=1A}}</ref> on July 24, 1956, to Charles Joseph Crist, an American physician of [[Greek Cypriot]] and [[Lebanese American|Lebanese]] descent,<ref name=\"billmaher\">{{cite episode |title=Charlie Crist, Tom Colicchio, Alicia Menendez, S. E. Cupp, P. J. O'Rourke| number=306 |episodelink=List of Real Time with Bill Maher episodes (2014)|series=[[Real Time with Bill Maher]] |network=HBO |airdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> and Nancy (n\u00e9e Lee), of [[Scots-Irish American|Scots-Irish]], [[Swiss American|Swiss]], and [[Welsh American|Welsh]] descent.<ref name=\"billmaher\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/10/20/news_pf/State/Father_is_first_for_u.shtml |work=St. Petersburg Times |author=Steve Bousquet |title=Father is first for unmarried politico |date=October 20, 2006 }}</ref> His family name is adapted from the original Greek name \"[[Christodoulou]].\"<ref name=medved>{{cite web |url=http://townhall.com/Columnists/MichaelMedved/2008/05/28/the_gop_veep_list_pros_and_cons |title=The GOP Veep List: Pros and Cons |last=Medved |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Medved |publisher=Townhall.com |date=May 28, 2008 |accessdate=October 15, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAs a child Crist moved to [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], where he attended Riviera Middle School and [[St. Petersburg High School]], from which he graduated in 1974. He is the second of four children and has three sisters: Margaret Crist Wood, Elizabeth Crist Hyden, and Catherine Crist Kennedy. He attended [[Wake Forest University]] for two years. While at Wake Forest, Crist was a walk-on quarterback for the Demon Deacons<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tampabay.com/richard-burr-an-old-football-buddy-of-charlie-crist-says-crist-in-search/2151714/|title=Richard Burr, an old football buddy of Charlie Crist, says Crist 'in search of a title'|website=Tampa Bay Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> during his freshman and sophomore years, before transferring to [[Florida State University]] in Tallahassee. Crist earned his undergraduate degree from Florida State, where he was elected vice president of the student body and became a member of the [[Pi Kappa Alpha]] fraternity. He received his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Samford University]] [[Cumberland School of Law]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Charlie Crist: A fuzzy line divides personal and political lives |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/08/27/State/Charlie_Crist__A_fuzz.shtml |publisher=Sarasota Herald Tribute |date=August 27, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1898151,00.html |magazine=Time Magazine |date=May 14, 2009 |author=Laura Fitzpatrick AND Lauren E. Bohn |title=2 Minute Bio}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter graduating from [[Cumberland School of Law]] in 1981, and passing the bar on his third attempt,<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Hegarty |title=Candidate failed 2 bar exams;Florida's top educator, who hopes to be its top legal officer, says failing taught him \"never give up.'' |url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/090101/State/Candidate_failed_2_ba.shtml |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |date=September 1, 2001 |accessdate=May 25, 2008 }}</ref> Crist was hired as general counsel to [[Minor League Baseball]], which was headquartered in St. Petersburg. Drawn to politics, Crist was a candidate for public office for the first time in 1986, in the Republican primary for a state Senate seat in [[Pinellas County]]. After losing in a [[runoff election|runoff]], Crist joined his brother-in-law in private practice in St. Petersburg, but soon returned to politics as an aide on the successful 1988 United States Senate campaign of [[Connie Mack III]], whom he has since described as his political mentor.<ref name=\"guns\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tbo.com/news/metro/MGB5Q9E6NQE.html |date=August 9, 2006 |publisher=TBO.com News / The Tampa Tribune |author=William March |title=Sticking To His Guns |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060916182231/http://www.tbo.com/news/metro/MGB5Q9E6NQE.html |archivedate=September 16, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Florida Senate==\n[[File:Charlie Crist with other Florida State Senators.jpg|thumb|right|Crist as a [[Florida Senate|Florida State Senator]]]]\nIn 1992 Crist was elected to a two-year term to the [[Florida Senate]] from the 20th District, which encompassed parts of St. Petersburg and [[south Tampa]].<ref name=\"handbook\">{{cite book |title=''The Florida Handbook 2007\u20132008'' |author1=Morris, Allen |author2=Joan Perry Morris, compilers |page=31 |edition=31st Biennial |url=http://www.PeninsularPublishing.com |publisher=Peninsula Publishing |isbn=978-0-9765846-2-9}}</ref> He defeated longtime incumbent Democratic State Senator [[Helen Davis|Helen Gordon Davis]] of [[Tampa]], 58.3 to 41.7%.<ref name=mh>{{cite news |first=Alex|last=Leary|title=Florida Democrats divided on redistricting, black representation |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/05/15/v-fullstory/2218391/florida-democrats-divided-on-redistricting.html |work=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |publisher=[[Miami Herald]]|date=May 15, 2011 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://results.elections.myflorida.com/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/3/1992&DATAMODE=|title=November 3, 1992 General Election Official Results|date=|website=Florida Division of Elections Results Archive|publisher=Florida Department of State|access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> Crist was able to unseat Gordon Davis following the 1992 decennial [[redistricting]] process, which significantly reconfigured the districts in the Tampa Bay area.<ref name=mh/> His victory was credited with helping to end the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]'s 128-year control of the Florida Senate, as the Republicans netted three seats in 1992, resulting in a 20-20 tie between the parties.<ref name=mh/>\n\nCrist was known as a [[Law and order (politics)|law-and-order]] senator, sponsoring legislation requiring inmates to [[Truth in sentencing|serve at least 85% of their sentences]] before becoming eligible for parole.<ref name=\"race\" /> He supported teacher salary increases, [[charter school]]s, and a [[Vehicle registration plates of Florida|specialty license plate]] for [[Restoration of the Everglades|Everglades conservation]].<ref name=\"handbook\" /> With Crist as chairman, the Senate Ethics and Elections Committee investigated actions of then-governor [[Lawton Chiles]] amid allegations that Chiles's campaign had made [[push polling|\"scare calls\"]] to senior citizens days before the 1994 gubernatorial election. Chiles testified before the committee and admitted that his campaign had made the calls.<ref name=\"race\" /><ref name=\"guns\" />\n\nIn 1994 Crist was reelected to a four-year term in the Senate, defeating Democrat Dana Lynn Maley with 63.3% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://results.elections.myflorida.com/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/8/1994&DATAMODE=|title=November 8, 1994 General Election Official Results|website=Florida Division of Elections Results Archive|publisher=Florida Department of State|access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Florida Education Commissioner==\nCrist gained recognition in 1998 as the Republican challenger to incumbent Democratic U.S. Senator [[Bob Graham]]. He lost to Graham by 26 percentage points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/fe1998/98senate.htm |title=1998 U.S. Senate results |publisher=[[Federal Elections Commission]] |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}</ref> In 2000 he was elected [[Education Commissioner of Florida]], a position he held until it became an appointive office in 2003, as the result of a 1998 constitutional amendment.<ref name=\"guns\" /> Crist left his position after he was elected attorney general.\n\n==Florida Attorney General==\nIn 2002 Crist was elected Florida Attorney General. His candidacy was supported by the host of ''[[America's Most Wanted]]'', [[John Walsh (television host)|John Walsh]]. Walsh and other supporters cited his work with the [[Center for Missing and Exploited Children]].\n\nCivil rights and consumer groups praised Crist for expanding the attorney general's powers during his time in office. These powers enabled him and future attorneys general to have greater power to prosecute civil rights and fraud cases. Crist also worked to combat [[E-mail spam|spam e-mail]], freeze utility rates, end telecom deception, and protect the environment.<ref name=race /><ref name=\"smiles\">{{cite news |title=Victory Smiles at Charlie Crist |publisher=The International Coordinating Committee \"Justice for Cyprus\" (PSEKA) |url=http://news.pseka.net/index.php?module=article&id=5900 |date=October 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Florida==\n[[File:Gov charlie crist.jpg|thumb|Crist's official portrait as Governor]]\n\nHaving won [[2006 Florida gubernatorial election|the 2006 election]], Crist was inaugurated as governor of Florida on January 2, 2007. He was involved in the state's purchase of sugar plantations. He also worked on education, with Florida rising into the top 10 states for K12 education under his control.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist touts Florida's improvements in education rankings|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2009/dec/21/charlie-crist/charlie-crist-touts-floridas-improvements-educatio/|publisher=Politifact|accessdate=January 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Fiscal policies===\nCrist supported President [[Barack Obama|Obama]]'s [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]], a stimulus package in response to the [[Great Recession]].<ref name=\"stimulus\">{{cite news|publisher=Forbes, Associated Press |title=Fla. gov touts stimulus package benefit at meeting |url=https://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2009/01/27/ap5968997.html |date=January 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20090205123942/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2009/01/27/ap5968997.html |archivedate=February 5, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Crist: Stimulus will help Florida |publisher=MSNBC |author=Morning Joe |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3036789/#28933203|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040202050816/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/3036789/#28933203|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=NBC News Hardball |title=GOP Gov Support Obama Stimulus |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21134540 |date= }}</ref> Fellow Republicans were angered by Crist's support for the stimulus.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Miami Herald |title=GOP seethes over Charlie Crist's stimulus-plan support |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics/story/901859.html |author=Adam C. Smith |date=February 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007103945/http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics/story/901859.html |archivedate=October 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nCrist called the act a \"godsend,\"<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/16/charlie-crist-effusive-ab_n_2146562.html Charlie Crist Effusive About Barack Obama at Tampa Press Banquet], ''Huffington Post'' (November 17, 2012).</ref> maintaining that it had saved the jobs of nearly 20,000 Florida schoolteachers and other school workers in 2009-10.<ref>Amy Sherman, [http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2012/sep/06/george-lemieux/charlie-crist-was-pro-life-pro-gun-and-anti-tax-sa/ Charlie Crist says in debate that stimulus saved 20,000 teacher jobs], PolitiFact Florida (October 10, 2014).</ref>\n\n===Social policies===\n====Capital punishment====\nAs governor, Crist supported [[capital punishment in Florida|capital punishment]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fadp.org/news/MH-20051103.htm |publisher=Miami Herald, via Herald.com |date=November 2, 2005 |title=Crist: Hands off death penalty law |author=Lesley Clark |accessdate=August 20, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022223613/http://www.fadp.org/news/MH-20051103.htm |archivedate=October 22, 2008  }}</ref>\n\n====Gun rights====\nIn 2008 Crist signed a provision preventing employers from prohibiting employees to bring firearms to the workplace, as long as the weapons are secure and the employees have a concealed carry license.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crist signs bring your gun to work bill |newspaper=Palm Beach Post |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/politics/content/state/epaper/2008/04/15/0415gunsatwork.html |date=April 15, 2008 |author=Dara Kam |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829174600/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/politics/content/state/epaper/2008/04/15/0415gunsatwork.html |archivedate=August 29, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Florida lawmakers pass \"take your guns to work\" law |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN0948339420080409 |date=April 9, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====Abortion====\nCrist's stance on abortion has been unclear at times.<ref name=CristHazy>Steve Bousquet, [http://www.sptimes.com/2006/08/18/State/Crist_s_stance_on_abo.shtml Crist's stance on abortion still hazy], ''St Petersburg Times'' (August 18, 2006).</ref> In 1995, while in the Florida Senate, Crist joined with two Democrats in the Senate Health Care Committee in voting against a proposal for a mandatory 24-hour waiting period before a woman could have an abortion, resulting in a 3-3 tie vote and the bill's defeat.<ref name=CristHazy/> In 1998, while running for the U.S. Senate, Crist wrote in a ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'' questionnaire that \"I believe that a woman has the right to choose, but would prefer only after careful consideration and consultation with her family, her physician and her clergy; not her government.\"<ref name=CristHazy/> In a debate that year he said he did not support a constitutional amendment banning abortion.<ref name=CristHazy/> In 2006, while running for governor, Crist said he did not support overturning ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' and opposed a mandatory 24-hour waiting period before a woman could have an abortion.<ref name=CristHazy/>\n\nIn 2010, while running for the U.S. Senate again, Crist said he would \"fight for pro-life legislative efforts\" and described himself as \"pro-life.\"<ref name=\"Politifact2012\">{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist was pro-life, pro-gun and anti-tax, says George LeMieux|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2012/sep/06/george-lemieux/charlie-crist-was-pro-life-pro-gun-and-anti-tax-sa/|publisher=Politifact|accessdate=January 29, 2014}}</ref> By March 2010, however, as rumors swirled that he would leave the Republican Party and become an independent, Crist reiterated that he did not support overturning ''Roe v. Wade'' and told a Christian Family Coalition group, \"We ought to, instead of change laws, change hearts.\"<ref>Adam C. Smith, [http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/stateroundup/amid-intense-chatter-crist-denies-he-would-run-as-independent/1076685 Amid intense chatter, Crist denies he would run as independent] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308083651/http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/stateroundup/amid-intense-chatter-crist-denies-he-would-run-as-independent/1076685 |date=March 8, 2010 }}, ''St. Petersburg Times'' (March 2, 2010).</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, after leaving the Republican Party and becoming an independent, Crist removed anti-abortion language from his website.<ref name=\"WinterUltrasoundBill\">Michael Winter, [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/06/florida-gov-charlie-crist-vetoes-ultrasound-abortion-bill/1 Florida Gov. Charlie Crist vetoes ultrasound abortion bill] ''USA Today'' (June 11, 2010).</ref> Shortly thereafter he vetoed a bill to require women seeking abortions to pay for and receive an [[ultrasound]], calling the measure \"punitive\" and \"almost mean-spirited.\"<ref name=\"Politifact2012\"/><ref name=\"WinterUltrasoundBill\"/> The bill also included language barring abortion coverage \"under a contract toward which any [[tax credit]] or cost-sharing credit is applied.\"<ref name=\"LarrabeeAbortionBill\">Brandon Larrabee, [http://jacksonville.com/news/florida/2010-06-01/story/abortion-bill-may-be-political-land-mine-crist Abortion bill may be political land mine for Crist], [[News Service of Florida]] (June 1, 2010).</ref> Legislative Republicans and [[anti-abortion movement|anti-abortion groups]] said his language was aimed at preventing \"what they considered the possibility of federal funding being used for abortion in Florida,\"<ref name=\"WinterUltrasoundBill\"/><ref name=\"LarrabeeAbortionBill\"/> while [[abortion rights]] groups said the broadly written provision would have resulted \"in hundreds of thousands of women losing health care coverage that they currently have.\"<ref name=\"LarrabeeAbortionBill\"/> The bill Crist vetoed also included some provisions \"intended to thwart\" the [[Affordable Care Act]], the federal [[Health care reform in the United States|health care reform]] legislation championed by President Obama.<ref name=\"WinterUltrasoundBill\"/>\n\n====Same-sex marriage and LGBT issues====\nIn 2006, as a proposed [[U.S. state constitutional amendments banning same-sex unions|state constitutional amendment banning same-sex unions]] was headed to the ballot in Florida, Crist said that such an amendment was unnecessary because state law already barred same-sex marriages.<ref name=\"MoorheadMarriage\">Molly Moorhead, [http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2013/may/09/charlie-crist/after-voting-ban-crist-now-backs-gay-marriage/ After voting for a ban, Charlie Crist now backs gay marriage], PolitiFact Florida (May 9, 2013).</ref> But in September 2005 Crist had signed a petition for the amendment during the Republican primary at the [[Christian Coalition of America|Christian Coalition]]'s request.<ref name=\"MoorheadMarriage\"/><ref name=\"ShermanSSM\">Amy Sherman, [http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2014/feb/07/charlie-crist/he-changed-his-stance-gay-marriage-charlie-crist-s/ Before he changed his stance on gay marriage, Charlie Crist says he always supported civil unions] (February 7, 2014).</ref> Crist said in campaign materials at the time that he supported \"traditional marriage.\"<ref name=\"MoorheadMarriage\"/> In 2008 Crist said he voted for the amendment, which passed.<ref name=\"MoorheadMarriage\"/>\n\nIn a debate and a radio talk show appearance in 2006, Crist indicated support for [[civil union]]s.<ref name=\"ShermanSSM\"/> In 2010, after becoming an independent during the U.S. Senate race, he declared his support for civil unions encompassing \"the full range of legal protections\" including \"access to a loved one in the hospital, inheritance rights, the fundamental things people need to take care of their families.\"<ref name=\"ShermanSSM\"/> It is unclear whether the 2008 state constitutional amendment Crist supported would have prohibited such civil unions.<ref name=\"ShermanSSM\"/>\n\nAs governor Crist deemphasized the marriage issue, saying in a late 2007 CNN appearance, \"It's not an issue that moves me. I'm just a live and let live kind of guy\", and telling the ''Orlando Sentinel'' in 2008 that the issue was not \"top-tier\" for him.<ref name=\"MoorheadMarriage\"/><ref name=\"ShermanSSM\"/>\n\nCrist initially supported Florida's ban on [[LGBT adoption|same-sex adoption]], which had been in place since 1977.<ref name=\"AdoptionSSM\">[http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2014/feb/20/charlie-crist/after-he-left-gop-charlie-crist-said-he-no-longer-/ On adoption by gay couples], PolitiFact (February 10, 2014).</ref> He publicly expressed support for the ban from the time he was attorney general in 2006 to his campaign for the U.S. Senate in 2010, even after some state legislators proposed dropping the ban in 2007 and a [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade]] judge struck down the ban as unconstitutional in 2008.<ref name=\"AdoptionSSM\"/> Crist expressed support for the ban as late as February 2010,<ref name=\"AdoptionSSM\"/> but by June 2010 he expressed openness to changing Florida law to allow same-sex adoption, saying a better approach \"would be to let judges make that decision on a case-by-case basis.\"<ref name=\"AdoptionSSM\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/localgovernment/mccollum-touts-tax-freeze-crist-open-to-gay-adoption/1103181 |title=McCollum touts tax freeze; Crist open to gay adoption |last=Smith |first=Adam C. |date=June 18, 2010 |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |publisher=tampabay.com |accessdate=September 9, 2010 |location=Sarasota, Florida |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107085356/http://www.tampabay.com/news/localgovernment/mccollum-touts-tax-freeze-crist-open-to-gay-adoption/1103181 |archive-date=November 7, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010 Crist said that he had had an \"appropriate evolution\" on gay rights and was considering dropping the state's appeal of the court ruling striking down Florida's ban on gay adoption.<ref name=\"LimAdoption\">Dara Kim, [http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2010-09-14/news/fl-crist-gay-rights-20100914_1_gay-adoption-gay-couples-charlie-crist Crist: I've had 'appropriate evolution' on gay rights], ''Palm Beach Post'' (September 14, 2010).</ref> Days later, after an appeals court struck down the ban, Crist hailed the ruling \"a very good day for Florida\" and \"a great day for children\" and announced that the state would no longer seek to enforce the ban.<ref name=\"AdoptionSSM\" /> In a Senate candidates' debate the next month he attributed his shift in positions to \"the convergence of life experience and wisdom,\" saying that he had become more tolerant and become less judgmental with age.<ref name=\"AdoptionSSM\" />\n\nIn January 2014 Crist apologized for his support for the 2008 same-sex marriage ban and for the same-sex adoption ban, telling an Orlando LGBT publication, \"I'm sorry I did that. It was a mistake. I was wrong. Please forgive me.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Crist 'Sorry' He Backed Gay Marriage Ban, Calls It A 'Mistake' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/02/charlie-crist-gay-marriage_n_4531810.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=January 15, 2014|first=Luke|last=Johnson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist apologizes for backing same-sex marriage ban|url=https://www.msnbc.com/the-last-word/crist-apologizes-lgbt-community|publisher=MSNBC|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist Says 'Sorry' for Supporting Florida's Same-Sex Marriage Ban|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/politicians/2014/01/02/charlie-crist-says-sorry-supporting-floridas-marriage-ban|work=Advocate|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Environmental work===\nIn June 2008 Crist proposed that Florida buy {{convert|187000|acre|km2}} from the United States Sugar Corporation for $1.2 billion. The purchase would remove about 187,000 acres of sugar farming for restoration efforts. In front of supporters in Palm Beach County, Crist called the deal \"as monumental as our nation's first national park.\"<ref>Guardian UK \"Florida to buy 187,000 farmland acres to preserve Everglades\" https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2008/jun/24/conservation.usa</ref> Economic changes forced the purchase to be reduced to {{convert|73000|acre|km2}} of sugar and citrus plantations for Everglades restoration projects.<ref>Miami Herald \"Crist praises water managers for support of Big Sugar land buy\" [http://www.miamiherald.com/business/breaking-news/story/1048326.html]{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref><ref>Miami Herald \"Crist has competition: U.S. Sugar has offer from another suitor\" http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2008/11/crist-has-compe.html</ref><ref>AP \"Fla. revises deal with US Sugar to save Everglades\" By Jessica Gresko The Associated Press November 11, 2008 http://www.topix.com/content/ap/2008/11/fla-revises-deal-with-us-sugar-to-save-everglades{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Deal to Save Everglades May Help Sugar Firm|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/08/us/08everglades.html|work=New York Times|accessdate=January 29, 2014|first1=Don|last1=Van Natta Jr|first2=Damien|last2=Cave|date=March 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCrist announced plans to sign executive orders to impose strict [[air pollution]] standards in Florida, with an aim to reduce [[greenhouse gas]] emissions by 80% of 1990 levels by 2050.<ref name=enn>{{cite news |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/governmentFilingsNews/idUSN1125764520070711 |title=Florida To Introduce Tough Greenhouse Gas Targets |date=July 11, 2007 |author=Jim Loney |accessdate=August 21, 2009}}</ref> In his gubernatorial campaign Crist opposed [[offshore oil drilling]]. He altered that position in June 2008, when oil reached peak prices, saying, \"I mean, let's face it, the price of gas has gone through the roof, and Florida families are suffering, and my heart bleeds for them.\"<ref>\"In Switch, Florida's Crist Eyes Offshore Drilling\" NPR https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=91680890</ref>\n\n===Other issues===\nAfter claims that computerized voting machines undercounted votes in black communities, Crist endorsed legislation requiring paper records of all ballots cast in elections. He supported a tax cut to total $25 billion over a 5-year period aimed at [[property tax]] relief.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist takes credit for Florida's largest ever tax cut|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2009/nov/10/charlie-crist/charlie-crist-is-taking-credit-for-floridas-larges/|publisher=Politifact|accessdate=January 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2010 Crist vetoed an education bill that would have linked teacher pay to test scores, a piece of legislation conservatives strongly supported.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cillizza |first1=Chris |title=Charlie Crist didn't leave the Republican party because of racism. He left it because he couldn't win a primary. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2014/05/08/charlie-crist-didnt-leave-the-republican-party-because-of-racism-he-left-it-because-he-couldnt-win-a-primary/ |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCrist supported increased regulation of the insurance industry, including property insurance rates (in the aftermath of [[Hurricane Katrina]]) and health insurance. The [[Citizens Insurance#Florida|Citizen's Property Insurance Corp]] and the [http://www.sbafla.com/fhcf/ Florida Hurricane Catastrophe Fund] had been described as risky and underfunded. Standing next to former football star [[Dan Marino]] (whose son, Michael, is [[autism|autistic]] and inspired the [[Dan Marino#Dan Marino Foundation|Dan Marino Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.childnett.tv/videos/stories/foundation_inspired_family |title=A Foundation Inspired by a Family |publisher=Childnett.Tv |accessdate=August 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919011619/http://www.childnett.tv/videos/stories/foundation_inspired_family |archivedate=September 19, 2011  }}</ref>), Crist signed a law expanding health coverage statewide for autism disorders and legislation expanding low-income coverage and creating public and private insurance options in Florida.<ref>Insurance Journal \"Fla. Gov. Crist Persuades Cabinet to Block Insurers' Exit\" http://www.insurancejournal.com/news/southeast/2007/02/01/76468.htm</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flgov.com/release/9150 |title=Florida Governor Charlie Crist &#124; Governor Crist Launches \"Shop and Compare Insurance Rates\" Web Site |publisher=Flgov.com |accessdate=August 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514160300/http://www.flgov.com/release/9150 |archivedate=May 14, 2010 }}</ref><ref>\"Governor Crist Launches Shop and Compare Website\" http://www.ShopAndCompareRates.com and http://www.flgov.com</ref><ref>Wall Street Journal \"Florida's Unnatural Disaster Charlie Crist, taxpayers and the next hurricane.\" https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123371173559046209</ref><ref>Associated Press \"Crist: Florida 'better off' without State Farm\" http://www.gainesville.com/article/20090129/NEWS/901290919/0/LIVING</ref><ref>NPR \"State Farm Abandons Florida's Homeowners Market\" https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99942808</ref>\n\n===Fundraising controversies===\n\nIn February 2006, Crist attended a fundraiser at Mar-A-Lago, hosted by [[Donald Trump]], with guests paying $500 to attend. Two of the guests became subjects of controversy.<ref>[https://www.judicialwatch.org/corruption-chronicles/florida-attorney-general-hot-water/ JudicialWatch.org, \"Florida Attorney General in Hot Water,\" Feb. 13, 2006]</ref>\n\nOne, [[Volodymyr Shcherban]], was a [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] government official who had recently fled his country after being charged with corruption.<ref>[https://www.alamy.com/feb-03-2006-palm-beach-fl-usa-gubernatorial-candidate-charlie-crist-image65147167.html ''Palm Beach Post'', via Alamy, \"Gubernatorial candidate Charlie Crist poses for photo with Ex-Ukrainian Governor (of Sumy) Volodymyr Shcherban during a fundraiser hosted for Crist by Donald Trump at Mar-a-lago Friday night.\" Feb 3, 2006 (accessed 16 Oct 2019)]</ref><ref>[https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-2005-10-14-ukrainian14-story.html ''Orlando Sentinel'', \"Former Ukrainian official arrested, faces deportation,\" October 14, 2005 (accessed 16 Oct 2019)]</ref> The other, Russell Whitney, was a businessman from [[Cape Coral, Florida]], who at the time was under investigation by Crist's office (and two of whose businesses had previously made the maximum allowable $500 contribution to Crist's campaign).<ref>[https://www.browardpalmbeach.com/news/scott-rothstein-the-crist-angle-6439666 ''Broward-Palm Beach New Times'', \"Scott Rothstein: The Crist Angle.\" Nov. 4, 2009 (accessed 16 Oct 2019)]</ref> Crist subsequently returned $1,000 to Whitney's businesses, and determined that Shcherban's entry fee had been paid by another guest.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080206160843/http://www.sptimes.com/2006/02/13/State/Crist_sees_a_fluster_.shtml ''St. Petersburg Times'' (Associated Press), \"Crist sees a fluster over two donations,\" Feb. 13, 2006]</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Crist saw the man he had chosen as Florida GOP finance chairman, his former fraternity brother oil magnate [[Harry Sargeant III]], forced to step down.<ref>[https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-ne-who-are-trump-players-20191007-yndltrxvcnbudnviwoejkfy6um-story.html ''South Florida Sun-Sentinel'', \"Who are the three South Florida businessmen tangled in Trump impeachment inquiry?\" Oct. 7, 2019 (accessed 16 Oct 19)]</ref> One of Sargeant's employees, Ala'a al-Ali of the Dominican Republic, was indicted in Los Angeles for organizing $5,000 in illegal campaign contributions to Crist, as well as $50,000 to presidential candidates [[Hillary Clinton]], [[John McCain]] and [[Rudy Giuliani]].<ref>[https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/article24527335.html ''Miami Herald'' (via ''McClatchy''), \"Feds say $5,000 donation to Florida Gov. Crist is illegal.\" Feb 27, 2009 (accessed 16 Oct 2019)]</ref>\n\n==Role in the 2008 presidential election==\n[[File:Charlie Crist cropped.jpg|thumb|Crist in Brazil, 2007]]\nSenator [[John McCain]] endorsed Crist's 2006 campaign for governor, traveling the state to campaign with him. The day before the general election, Crist held a campaign event with McCain in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]]. Later, when the Republican Presidential primary debates were held in [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]], Crist embraced McCain. Former [[New York City Mayor]] [[Rudy Giuliani]], who had also campaigned for Crist during the gubernatorial election, had sought his endorsement.<ref>Seattle Times \"We'll win Florida, Giuliani says\" {{cite web |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2004121276_rudy12.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202223326/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2004121276_rudy12.html |archivedate=December 2, 2008  }}</ref><ref>NBC News \"Giuliani pins his hopes on Florida\" http://www.nbcnews.com/id/22706715</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-01-30-104286216_x.htm |title=Gov Crist could benefit from McCain win |agency=Associated Press |last=Farrington |first=Brendan |date=January 30, 2008 |accessdate=November 13, 2008 |work=USA Today}}</ref><ref>The Boston Globe \"Calling McCain a true American hero fla governor endorses\" [https://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2008/01/27/calling_McCain_a_true_american_hero_fla_governor_endorses_senator/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724120030/http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2008/01/27/calling_McCain_a_true_american_hero_fla_governor_endorses_senator/ |date=July 24, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007 Crist signed a bill moving the date of Florida's presidential primary to January 29, 2008, contrary to national political party rules.<ref>AP and Fox News \"Florida Governor Signs Bill to Move Up Presidential Primary to January\" [http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,274254,00.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070920173255/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0%2C2933%2C274254%2C00.html |date=September 20, 2007}}</ref> Crist joined Michigan governor [[Jennifer Granholm]] in asking that their states' delegates be seated. Both national conventions ended up seating all delegates, but with only a half vote each for the sanctioned states.<ref>New York Times \"G.O.P. Plans Early-Primary Penalties\" https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/29/us/politics/29calendar.html</ref><ref>''Miami Herald'', \"All 114 FL delegates get seats on GOP convention floor\" http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2008/08/all-114-fl-dele.html</ref><ref>CNN, \"Florida, Michigan get all delegates, but each gets half vote\" [http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/05/31/dems.delegates/index.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113131005/http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/05/31/dems.delegates/index.html |date=November 13, 2008}}</ref><ref>''Politico'', \"Florida Gov. wants all delegates seated\" http://www.politico.com/blogs/thecrypt/0208/Florida_Gov_wants_all_delegates_seated.html</ref>\n\nOn January 26, 2008, Crist endorsed [[John McCain|McCain]] in the Republican primary.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/florida/story/395209.html |title=McCain scores Crist's endorsement |work=[[Miami Herald]] |date=January 26, 2008 |accessdate=October 14, 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> McCain won the Florida primary by five percentage points.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.flanews.com/?p=1693 |title=Crist's Endorsement Helped McCain Defeat Romney |publisher=Capitol News Service |last=Ray |first=Whitney |date=January 27, 2008 |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2008, Crist extended early voting hours of operation and declared that a \"state of emergency exists\" due to record voter turnout and resultant hours-long waits at locations throughout the state.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/the-trail/2008/10/28/crist_extends_early_voting_hou.html |title=Crist Extends Early Voting Hours in Fla. |work=The Washington Post |last=Flaherty |first=Mary Pat |date=October 28, 2008 |accessdate=November 22, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics/florida/story/745715.html |title=Florida's Early Voting Hours Are Extended |work=[[The Miami Herald]] |last=Rabin |first=Charles |first2=Jennifer |last2=Lebovich |first3=Marc |last3=Caputo |date=October 29, 2008 |accessdate=November 22, 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nOn November 12\u201314, 2008, Crist hosted the [[Republican Governors Association]] (RGA) annual meeting in [[Miami, FL|Miami]]. Held the week after the [[2008 United States elections|Democratic Party victories in the 2008 election]],<ref>CBS News \"Barack Obama Wins Presidency\" http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/11/04/politics/main4571289.shtml</ref> there was speculation about the meeting's tone. Then Alaska Governor [[Sarah Palin]], the defeated 2008 Republican vice presidential nominee, was a featured participant and speaker.\n\nCrist's speech at the RGA conference, \"Listen to the Voters and Serve\", included his sentiments on how the GOP should evolve:\n\n{{quote|This party can no longer hope to reach Hispanics, African Americans and other minority groups&nbsp;\u2013 we need to just do it. Embracing cultures and lifestyles will make us a better party and better leaders. This desire for inclusiveness is near and dear to my heart ... Last week, the American people made a choice and this week, if we choose to call ourselves leaders, if we truly endeavor to serve with a servant's heart for the people who count on us, then we too must work together, listen to one another and learn from the leaders who made the kind of history the American people deserve.<ref>A Message from Charlie \"Listen to the Voters and Serve\" By Charlie Crist http://www.charliecrist.com/</ref>}}\n\nCrist held a joint interview with Governor [[Mark Sanford]] of [[South Carolina]] in which they discussed the split in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] over where to direct the party's efforts to gain more voters.<ref>Bloomberg News \"Governors Crist, Sanford Split Over Republican Path to Success\" https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aahiSQ2bhTN8</ref>\n\n==2010 Senate campaign==\n{{Main|2010 United States Senate election in Florida}}\n{{Wikinews|Musician David Byrne sues Florida governor over campaign song}}\nOn May 12, 2009, Crist announced that he would not run for reelection as governor in 2010, making him the first Florida governor not to run for reelection since 1964.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://editions.lib.umn.edu/smartpolitics/2013/04/02/charlie-crist-there-and-back-a/ |title= Charlie Crist: There and Back Again? |publisher=Smart Politics |first=Eric |last=Ostermeier |date=April 2, 2013}}</ref> Instead he ran for the [[US Senate]]. His two main opponents were former Florida House Speaker [[Marco Rubio]],<ref>{{cite news |work=New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/13/us/13cristq.html |date=May 12, 2009 |title=Restless in Tallahassee, or With Eye on 2012, Governor Rolls Dice |author1=Damien Cave |author2=Gary Fineout |accessdate=August 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>Miami Herald \"Is Republican Party united behind Charlie Crist?\" [http://www.miamiherald.com/515/story/1045369.html]{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> and Democratic nominee [[Kendrick Meek]].<ref>{{cite news |work=Miami Herald |title=Kendrick Meek raises $1.5 million for Senate bid |author=Beth Reinhard |date=April 2, 2009|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/569/story/980067.html}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n\nCrist was initially the front-runner in the Republican primary, but later trailed Rubio in polls.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/04/15/politics/main6399577.shtml|title=Poll: Crist Ahead If He Runs As Independent|date=April 15, 2010 |publisher=CBS News|accessdate=April 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20002724-503544.html|title=Will Charlie Crist Run as an Independent?|last=Finn|first=Tyler|date=April 16, 2010|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=April 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCrist announced his intent to run as an unaffiliated candidate in the 2010 senate election, while at the same time, according to a press release from his campaign, he remained a registered Republican.<ref name=\"OrlandoSentinel-Apr3010\">{{cite web|title=Crist's independent run draws praise \u2013 and scorn |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2010-04-30/news/os-crist-independent-20100429_1_democratic-strategist-steve-schale-charlie-crist-independent-voters|accessdate =}}''Orlando Sentinel'', April 30, 2010.</ref> Crist officially changed his registration status to \"non party affiliated\" on May 13, 2010. He did not return campaign contributions made while he was a Republican.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reinhard |first=Beth |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/05/13/1626770/crist-no-refunds-for-former-fans.html |title=Charlie Crist won't refund campaign donations - Florida |publisher=MiamiHerald.com |date=May 13, 2010 |accessdate=August 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605140510/http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/05/13/1626770/crist-no-refunds-for-former-fans.html |archivedate=June 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2010/may/19/charlie-crist/gov-charlie-crist-changes-course-keeping-campaign-/ Gov. Charlie Crist changes course on returning campaign donations] Politifact (''Tampa Bay Tribune'' / ''Miami Herald'') May 19, 2010 ''Crist said he would \"probably give it back to them,\" leading donors to believe that as the dictionary states it was \"to be expected\" or \"without much doubt\" that they would see some of their cash back from Crist. We find Crist completely changed his position from entertaining the idea of giving the money back, to definitely not giving the money back. Our verdict: Full Flop.''</ref> Crist lost the general election, receiving 29.7% of the vote to Rubio's 48.9% and Meek's 20.2%.<ref>{{cite web |last=Florida Division of Elections |url=https://election.dos.state.fl.us/elections/resultsarchive/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/2/2010&DATAMODE= |title=Official Results of 2010 Election |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129120307/http://election.dos.state.fl.us/elections/resultsarchive/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11%2F2%2F2010&DATAMODE= |archivedate=November 29, 2014  }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, as part of a settlement of a copyright lawsuit brought by musician [[David Byrne]], Crist apologized for his Senate campaign's use of Byrne's song \"[[Road to Nowhere]]\" without permission.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/david-byrne-forces-charlie-crist-record-embarrassing-apology-20110412-103915-351.html|title=David Byrne forces Charlie Crist to record embarrassing apology for stealing Talking Heads song}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s4k13LmlcUE|title=Charlie Crist Official Apology to David Byrne for Copyright Infringement}}</ref>\n\nBy the spring of 2015 there was speculation that Crist would seek the Democratic nomination for Florida's [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2016|2016 senate race]]. This would have been his third run for the seat (he lost in 1998 and 2010). In March 2015 Crist said he would not seek the nomination. That same month he endorsed U.S. Congressman [[Patrick Murphy (Florida politician)|Patrick Murphy]]'s Senate candidacy.\n\n==Out of politics, 2011\u201314==\nIn January 2011 Crist joined the [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] office of national personal injury law firm [[Morgan & Morgan PA|Morgan & Morgan]] after expressing an interest in returning to the legal field during his final week in office as governor of Florida. Crist worked primarily in the firm's class action sector as a complex litigation attorney, serving as a \"[[Rainmaker (business)|rainmaker]]\" for the firm.<ref name=\"DixonMorgan\">Matt Dixon, [http://www.naplesnews.com/news/state/charlie-crist-touted-as-attorney-for-morgan--morgan-but-hasnt-been-in-court-ep-504428072-341006661.html Charlie Crist: Touted as attorney for Morgan & Morgan, but hasn't been in court], ''Naples Daily News'' (July 21, 2014).</ref> In November 2016, after almost six years with the firm, he was elected to represent Florida's 13th Congressional District.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/democrat-charlie-crist-elected-floridas-13th-district|title=New Member: Democrat Charlie Crist Elected in Florida's 13th District|date=November 9, 2016|website=Roll Call|access-date=April 24, 2017}}</ref> In February 2018 Brad Slager of ''Sunshine State News'' cited evidence that Morgan & Morgan was \"attempting to purge all evidence\" of its relationship with Crist now that he was a \"rookie congressman\" with \"little-to-no power.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Slager |first1=Brad |title=Is Morgan & Morgan Trying to Memory-Hole Charlie Crist? |url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/morgan-morgan-trying-memory-hole-charlie-crist |website=Sunshine State News |accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Crist performed paid consulting work for Coastal Construction, a Miami-based construction firm owned by Crist's longtime friend Tom Murphy, the father of former U.S. Representative [[Patrick Murphy (Florida politician)|Patrick Murphy]].<ref name=\"DixonMorgan\"/>\n\nCrist has been a part-time guest lecturer at [[Stetson University College of Law]],<ref>Becky Bowers, [http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/gubernatorial/charlie-crist-is-a-big-hit-in-first-law-lecture-at-stetson/1163329 Charlie Crist is a big hit in first law lecture at Stetson] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506062656/http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/gubernatorial/charlie-crist-is-a-big-hit-in-first-law-lecture-at-stetson/1163329 |date=May 6, 2016 }}, ''Tampa Bay Times'' (April 12, 2011).</ref> with the title of Distinguished Professorial Lecturer.<ref>[http://www.stetson.edu/law/news/index.php/2011/02/28/crist-will-be-distinguished-professorial-lecturer/ Crist will be Distinguished Professorial Lecturer], Stetson University (February 28, 2011).</ref>\n\nIn August 2012 Crist endorsed President [[Barack Obama|Obama]] in his [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2012|campaign for reelection]] over Republican nominee [[Mitt Romney]], saying that the Republican Party \"pitched so far to the extreme right on issues important to women, immigrants, seniors and students that they've proven incapable of governing for the people.\"<ref>Vanessa Williams, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/election-2012/wp/2012/08/26/former-fla-governor-charlie-crist-endorses-obama/ Former Fla. governor Charlie Crist endorses Obama], ''Washington Post'' (August 26, 2012).</ref><ref>Charlie Crist, [Here's why I'm backing Barack Obama], ''Tampa Bay Times'' (August 26, 2012).</ref> Crist was a speaker at the [[2012 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], saying, \"I didn't leave the Republican Party; it left me.\"<ref>Emily Schultheis, [http://www.politico.com/story/2012/09/crist-speaks-to-dem-convention-080883 Charlie Crist defends Obama at DNC], ''Politico'' (September 6, 2012).</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hwYVraqaTn4 Charlie Crist Remarks at 2012 Democratic National Convention] (official video).</ref>\n\n===Party switch and ''The Party's Over''===\nOn December 7, 2012, Crist announced that he had joined the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"changing\"/> In his 2014 book ''The Party's Over'' he recounted his journey from one party to the other. He claimed that his career in the Republican Party was destroyed by a hug between him and Obama at a [[Fort Myers]] town hall on February 10, 2009. \"It was the kind of hug I'd exchanged with thousands and thousands of Floridians over the years,\" Crist wrote. \"I didn't think a thing about it as it was happening.\" But it \"ended my viable life as a Republican politician. I would never have a future in my old party again. My bipartisan hopes and dreams, I would discover soon enough to my shock and disappointment, were vastly overstated and hopelessly out of date.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crist |first1=Charlie |title=The Hug That Killed My Republican Career |url=http://time.com/4608/the-hug-that-killed-my-republican-career/ |website=Time |accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, however, Crist told [[Fusion TV|Fusion]]<nowiki>'s</nowiki> [[Jorge Ramos (news anchor)|Jorge Ramos]] that he had left the Republican Party because of its racial attitudes. \"I couldn't be consistent with myself and my core beliefs, and stay with a party that was so unfriendly toward the African-American president\u2014I'll just go there,\" Crist said. \"I was a Republican and I saw the activists and what they were doing. It was intolerable to me.\" ''[[The Washington Post]]''<nowiki/>'s Chris Cilizza rejected this claim, citing ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'' political editor Adam Smith as saying that Crist \"was happy as a Republican when the polls showed him leading Marco Rubio by 20 points.\" Cilizza wrote that Crist's party switch \"epitomized for many within the Republican base that Crist lacked any core principles or beliefs and, instead, simply went with whatever was popular at the moment.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cillizza |first1=Chris |title=Charlie Crist didn't leave the Republican party because of racism. He left it because he couldn't win a primary. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2014/05/08/charlie-crist-didnt-leave-the-republican-party-because-of-racism-he-left-it-because-he-couldnt-win-a-primary/ |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=September 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a ''[[The New Republic|New Republic]]'' review, Isaac Chotiner called ''The Party's Over'' an \"account of why Crist switched parties\" and wrote that Crist had \"revealed himself\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chotiner |first1=Isaac |title=Charlie Crist's Achingly Bad Search for Self |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/116435/charlie-crists-partys-over-reviewed-isaac-chotiner |website=New Republic |accessdate=September 15, 2018}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Rolling Stone Magazine]]'' in 2014, Jeb Lund described Crist as \"a Republican conveniently converted to Democrat\", adding, \"what made Crist dynamic as a Republican ... was a vaguely populist nose-thumbing at Republican orthodoxy\", and that \"Charlie Crist is a Democrat only if you are a Republican.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lund |first1=Jeb |title=The Florida Farce: Rick Scott Vs. Charlie Crist |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/the-florida-farce-rick-scott-vs-charlie-crist-20140929 |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=September 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==2014 gubernatorial election==\n{{Main|2014 Florida gubernatorial election}}\nIn July 2013 it was announced that Crist was releasing a new book in the process of being written.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist has \"no-holds-barred\" book coming out|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/charlie-crist-has-no-holds-barred-book-coming-out/2130689|publisher=Tampa Bay.com|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Crist Is Writing A Book Because He Is Likely Going To Run For Governor Of Florida|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/10/charlie-crist-book-florida_n_3575416.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=January 15, 2014|first=Jason|last=Linkins|date=July 10, 2013}}</ref> The release hinted that he would run in the 2014 gubernatorial election. The book, released in February 2014, is titled ''The Party's Over: How the Extreme Right Hijacked the GOP and I Became a Democrat''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Florida Governor Charlie Crist attacks rivals in new book|url=http://www.wtsp.com/rss/article/351855/250/Charlie-Crist-attacks-rivals-in-new-book|publisher=WTSP|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist attacks rivals in new book|url=http://jacksonville.com/opinion/blog/403455/matt-dixon/2014-01-08/charlie-crist-attacks-rivals-book|publisher=Jacksonville.com|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref> It details why Crist left the Republican Party and became a Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist's new book: Rick Scott is a 'terrible governor,' Sarah Palin is 'different'|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/charlie-crists-new-book-rick-scott-is-a-terrible-governor-sarach-palin-is/2160188|publisher=Tampa Bay.com|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref> On November 1, 2013, Crist filed to run for governor as a Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ex-GOP Fla. Gov. Crist to run for job as Democrat|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/nov/1/ex-gop-fla-gov-crist-run-job-democrat/|work=Washington Times|accessdate=November 1, 2013}}</ref> He won the Democratic nomination but was defeated in the general election by Republican incumbent [[Rick Scott]]. Crist holds the rare distinction of losing a statewide general election in Florida as a Republican, Democrat and Independent candidate.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2016 Congressional campaign===\nOn October 20, 2015, Crist announced that he would seek the Democratic nomination for [[Florida's 13th congressional district]], his home district, in the [[2016 United States House of Representatives elections|2016 U.S. House of Representatives elections]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/stateroundup/charlie-crist-announces-hes-running-for-congress/2250475 |title=Former Florida Gov. Charlie Crist announces he's running for Congress |work=Tampa Bay Times |date= |accessdate=October 21, 2015}}</ref> He had previously announced on [[Twitter]] that he would not run for [[political office]] in [[2016 United States elections|2016]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=CharlieCrist|number=577582802796875776 |title=I will not be seeking office in 2016, but I will be working alongside my fellow @FlaDems. Join me at http://t.co/VGsDGXVgvk.|date=March 16, 2015 |accessdate=October 21, 2015}}</ref> Republican incumbent [[David Jolly]], who succeeded 43-year incumbent [[Bill Young]] in a 2014 special election, was vacating the seat to run for the same Senate seat for which Crist ran in 1998 and 2010.\n\nBut when Senator [[Marco Rubio]] decided to run for reelection, Jolly dropped out of the Senate race and sought reelection to the House, even though the 13th district had become significantly friendlier to Democrats when a court tossed out Florida's original congressional map. The new map drew nearly all of St. Petersburg, along with most of the more Democratic southern portion of Pinellas County, into the 13th.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu/post/crist-revives-political-career-win-over-jolly|title=Crist Revives Political Career With Win over Jolly|publisher=[[WUSF-FM]]|author1=Steve Newborn|author2=Mark Schreiner|date=November 9, 2016}}</ref> The district had been in Republican hands without interruption since 1955, and had been one of the first areas of Florida to turn Republican. However, it had become more of a swing district at the presidential level since the 1990s; it has supported a Democrat for president in all but one election since 1992.\n\nIn the general election, Crist defeated Jolly 52-48%,<ref name=\"politicoresults\"/> becoming the first Democrat to win the seat in 62 years.\n\n===2018 Congressional campaign===\nIn 2018 Crist was endorsed by the [[League of Conservation Voters]] (LCV) Action Fund, which called him \"a leader on protecting Florida from and planning for the impacts of climate change during his time as Governor and in Congress.\" Crist won the election.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Auster |first1=Craig |title=LCV ACTION FUND ENDORSES CHARLIE CRIST FOR RE-ELECTION |url=https://www.lcv.org/article/lcv-action-fund-endorses-charlie-crist-re-election/ |website=League of Conservative Voters |accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nCrist was sworn in on January 3, 2017. He is a member of the [[Blue Dog Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://bluedogcaucus-costa.house.gov/members |format=|publisher=Blue Dog Coalition|date=|accessdate=February 7, 2018}}</ref> the [[New Democrat Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author= |url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=|accessdate=February 2, 2018}}</ref> the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=|publisher=Citizen's Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=October 20, 2018}}</ref> and the [[U.S.-Japan Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://usjapancaucus-castro.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=U.S. - Japan Caucus|date=|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn December 18, 2019, Crist voted for both articles of impeachment against President Donald J. Trump.<ref>https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-impeachment-vote-results-house-2019-12 </ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Committee on Appropriations]]'''\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Defense|Subcommittee on Defense]]\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Commerce, Justice, Science, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Commerce, Justice, Science, and Related Agencies]]\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Financial Services and General Government|Subcommittee on Financial Services and General Government]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]]\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics|Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics]]\n\n==Political positions after party switch==\n===Immigration===\nIn June 2017 Crist was one of 24 House Democrats to vote for [[Kate's Law]]. The next month he was one of five Democrats to vote to fund President Trump's border wall, and the next day issued a statement saying that he opposed the wall.<ref>{{cite web |last1=IANNELLI |first1=Jerry |title=Florida Democrat Charlie Crist Votes to Fund a Border Wall He Says He Doesn't Support |url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/florida-democrat-charlie-crist-votes-to-fund-trumps-border-wall-with-mexico-9530153 |website=Miami New Times |accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Same-sex marriage===\nOn May 9, 2013, Crist announced that he supports [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]]: \"I most certainly support marriage equality in Florida and look forward to the day it happens here.\"<ref name=\"WP Gay Marriage\">{{cite news|last=Weiner|first=Rachel|title=Charlie Crist endorses gay marriage|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/05/09/charlie-crist-endorses-gay-marriage/|accessdate=May 22, 2013|newspaper=Washington Post|date=May 9, 2013|quote=\"I most certainly support marriage equality in Florida and look forward to the day it happens here,\" the Republican-turned-independent-turned-Democrat wrote on his Facebook page. He congratulated Delaware on becoming the 11th state to legalize gay marriage.}}</ref> In both 2006 and 2008, Crist announced his support for the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]], but by 2010 he had endorsed adoption rights for gay couples.<ref name=\"WP Gay Marriage\" /><ref name=WG>{{cite news|last=Associated Press release|title=Ex-Republican Charlie Crist backs gay marriage|url=http://www.wisconsingazette.com/national-gaze/ex-republican-charlie-crist-backs-gay-marriage.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130630162236/http://www.wisconsingazette.com/national-gaze/ex-republican-charlie-crist-backs-gay-marriage.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 30, 2013|accessdate=May 22, 2013|newspaper=Wisconsin Gazette|date=May 9, 2013|quote=The statement marks a shift in Crist's views on gay marriage. He once supported Florida's constitutional ban on gay marriage, but also later said he wouldn't support a similar federal ban.}}</ref>\n\n===United States embargo against Cuba===\nCrist wants to lift the [[United States embargo against Cuba]], saying it has not helped to change the government of [[Cuba]]. He had supported the embargo earlier as Republican and independent.<ref>[http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article1960168.html Charlie Crist flip-flops on U.S. embargo against Cuba]</ref>\n\n===Gun policy===\nFollowing the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]] in December 2012, Crist announced a reversal of some of his previous stances on gun control. Before 2012 he had sometimes accused his opponents of not supporting gun rights strongly enough. He was also endorsed by the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]] in 2006. In 2012 Crist announced that he supported reinstating the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]], banning [[high-capacity magazine]]s, and instating more extensive [[National Instant Criminal Background Check System|background checks]].<ref name=\"Leary 2018\">{{cite news| title=Former Gov. Charlie Crist shifts on guns, supports new restrictions| url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/national/former-gov-charlie-crist-shifts-on-guns-supports-new-restrictions/1266801| last=Leary| first=Alex| work=Tampa Bay Times| location=Tampa Bay, Florida| access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref> In the wake of the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]], he announced his support for additional measures, including a ban on [[Bump fire#Bump fire stocks|bump stocks]],<ref name=\"Sidorowicz 2018\">{{cite news| url=http://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/as-hundreds-rally-for-gun-control-bill-to-put-guns-in-florida-classrooms-withdrawn/67-520130542| title=As hundreds rally for gun control, bill to put guns in Florida classrooms withdrawn| last=Sidorowicz | first=Josh| work=wtsp.com| location=Tampa, Florida| access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref> and also said he does not support arming teachers.<ref name=\"Perry 2018\">{{cite web| url=https://floridapolitics.com/archives/258088-charlie-crist-hopes-donald-trump-will-push-gun-control-regulations| title=Charlie Crist hopes Donald Trump will push for gun control regulations| date=March 5, 2018| website=Florida Politics| publisher=Peter Schorsch| last=Perry| first=Mitch| access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhen he left the gubernatorial office in 2011, Crist had an A rating from the NRA.<ref name=\"NRA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nraila.org/articles/20140711/florida-alert-governor-scotts-record-on-second-amendment-issues| title=Florida Alert: Governor Scott's Record on Second Amendment Issues| last=Turner| first=Jim| website=NRA-ILA| publisher=National Rifle Association of America, Institute for Legislative Action| date=July 11, 2014| access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref> In 2016 he received an F rating from the NRA, its lowest rating.<ref name=\"Nielsen 2016\">{{cite news| url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/new-mailer-slams-charlie-crist-anti-gun-policies|title=New Mailer Slams Charlie Crist on Anti-Gun Policies| last=Nielsen| first=Allison| date=October 20, 2016| work=Sunshine State News| location=Florida| access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Felons' voting rights===\nIn a February 12, 2018, op-ed for ''[[USA Today]]'', Crist complained that Florida was \"one of only three states that permanently bans non-violent, ex-felons from voting\" and that this \"disenfranchisement of 1.5 million of our fellow citizens is shameful.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crist |first1=Charlie |title=Charlie Crist: Ex-felons in Florida need their voting rights back |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2018/02/11/lets-give-ex-felons-their-voting-rights-back-charlie-crist-column/308710002/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:MMCrist.JPG|thumb|right|170px|Crist and his former wife [[Carole Rome]]]]\n\n==Personal life==\nIn July 1979 Crist married Amanda Morrow. They divorced within a year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/08/27/State/Charlie_Crist__A_fuzz.shtml |title=Charlie Crist: A fuzzy line divides personal and political lives |newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |date=August 27, 2006 |last=Bousquet |first=Steve |accessdate=October 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nCrist became engaged to [[Carole Rome]] on July 3, 2008, after nine months of dating, and they married<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.tampabay.com/buzz/2008/12/arrivals-to-cri.html |title=Crist\u2013Rome Wedding Photos |newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |date=December 12, 2008 |accessdate=December 13, 2008}}</ref> on December 12 of that year at the [[First Methodist Church of St. Petersburg]], where Crist is a member.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cbs4.com/local/Florida.Governor.Charlie.2.790985.html |title=Governor Crist and Carole Rome set wedding date |publisher=[[WFOR-TV]] |accessdate=October 12, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007023354/http://cbs4.com/local/Florida.Governor.Charlie.2.790985.html |archivedate=October 7, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dolinski|first=Catherine|title=Crist's December Wedding Will Follow Tradition|date=November 13, 2008|newspaper=[[The Tampa Tribune]]|page=6}}</ref> In February 2017 Crist announced that he had filed for divorce.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Adam C|title=Charlie Crist files for divorce from wife Carole|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article134704329.html|newspaper=Miami Herald|accessdate=February 24, 2017|date=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Charlie Crist\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 484,466\n| percentage = 50.11\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Tom Warner\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 257,049\n| percentage = 26.59\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Locke Burt\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 225,360\n| percentage = 23.31\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 966,875\n| percentage= 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin | title=2002 Florida Attorney General election<ref>https://doe.dos.state.fl.us/elections/resultsarchive/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/5/2002&DATAMODE= {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720032959/https://doe.dos.state.fl.us/elections/resultsarchive/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11%2F5%2F2002&DATAMODE= |date=2013-07-20 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Charlie Crist\n  |votes      